<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="11">
<HEAD>ADAM DAVY'S FIVE DREAMS ABOUT EDWARD II. [<I>Laud MS.</I> 622 (<I>end of the</I> 14<I>th cent.</I>), <I>leaf</I> 26, <I>back.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO oure lorde Iesu crist in heuene,</L>
<L>Ich to-day shewe myne sweuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich mette in one ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="4">Of a kni&yogh;th of mychel mi&yogh;th:</L>
<L>His name is ihote sir Edward &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Prince of Wales<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare
<Q><L>"Nou is <I>Edward of Carnarvon</I></L><L>King of Engelond al aplyht",</L></Q> in "The Elegy on the Death of Edw. I", from Harl. 2253, leaf 73, in Mr Thos. Wright's <I>Political Songs</I>, for the Camden Society, 1839, p. 249. Edw. III was never created Prince of Wales. The Black Prince was, but was never king.</NOTE>, Engelonde &thorn;e faire &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Me mette &thorn;at he was armed wel,</L>
<L N="8">Bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; yrne &amp; wi&thorn; stel;</L>
<L>And on his helme &thorn;at was of stel,</L>
<L>A Coroune of gold bicom hym wel.</L>
<L>Bifore the shryne of seint Edward he stood,</L>
<L N="12">Myd glad chere, &amp; mylde of mood,</L>
<L>Mid two kni&yogh;ttes armed on ei&thorn;er side,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;th &thorn;ennes goo ne ride.</L>
<L>hetilich<NOTE PLACE="foot">A.S. <I>hetelice</I>, hatefully, hotly.</NOTE> hij leiden hym vpon,</L>
<L N="16">Als hij mi&yogh;tten myd swerd don.</L>
<L>He stood &thorn;ere wel swi&thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oled al-to-gedres her wille;
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>No strook ne &yogh;af he a&yogh;einward</L>
<L N="20">To &thorn;ilk &thorn;at hym weren wi&thorn;erward<NOTE PLACE="foot">A.S. <I>wi&eth;er</I>, against; <I>wi&eth;erweard</I>, contrary, adverse.</NOTE>.</L>
<L>Wounde ne was &thorn;ere blody non,</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at hym &thorn;ere was don.</L>
<L>&para; After &thorn;at me &thorn;ou&yogh;th, onon,</L>
<L N="24">As &thorn;e tweie kni&yogh;ttes weren gon,</L>
<L>In ei&thorn;er ere of oure kyng</L>
<L>&thorn;ere spronge out a wel fare &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>Hij wexen out so bri&yogh;th so glem</L>
<L N="28">&thorn;at shyne&thorn; of &thorn;e sonne-bem;</L>
<L>Of diuers coloures hij weren,</L>
<L>&thorn;at comen out of bo&thorn;e his eren</L>
<L>ffoure bendes alle by rewe on ei&thorn;er ere,</L>
<L N="32">Of diuers colours, red &amp; white als hij were;</L>
<L>Als fer as me &thorn;ou[&yogh;th] ich mi&yogh;th see,<MILESTONE N="27a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hij spredden fer &amp; wyde in &thorn;e cuntre.</L>
<L>fforso&thorn;e me mette &thorn;is ilk sweuene&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">Ich take to witnesse god of heuene&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e wedenysday bifore &thorn;e decollacioun of seint Ion<NOTE PLACE="foot">Decollation of John the Baptist, Aug. 29.&mdash;Nicolas.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>It is more &thorn;an twelue mone&thorn; gon.</L>
<L>God me graunte so heuene blis,</L>
<L N="40">As me mette &thorn;is sweuene as it is.</L>
<L>Now god &thorn;at is heuene kyng,</L>
<L>To mychel ioye tourne &thorn;is metyng!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="43">A No&thorn;er sweuene me mette, on a tiwes-ni&yogh;th</L>
<L>Bifore the fest of alle halewen<NOTE PLACE="foot">All Hallows, or All Saints' Day, Nov. 1.&mdash;Nicolas.</NOTE>, of &thorn;at ilk kni&yogh;th;</L>
<L>His name is nempned here-bifore;</L>
<L>Blissed be &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was bore!</L>
<L>ffor we shullen &thorn;e day see,</L>
<L N="48">Emperour ychosen he wor&thorn;e of cristiente.</L>
<L>God vs graunte &thorn;at ilk bone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ilk tydyng here we sone</L>
<L>Of sir Edward oure derwor&thorn; kyng
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="13"></L>
<L N="52">Ich mette of hym ano&thorn;ere fair metyng:</L>
<L>To oure lorde of heuene ich telle &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at my sweuene tourne to mychel blis.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;th he rood vpon an Asse&mdash;</L>
<L N="56">And &thorn;at ich take god to witnesse!&mdash;</L>
<L>ywonden he was in a Mantel gray;</L>
<L>Toward Rome he nom his way;</L>
<L>Vpon his heuede sat an gray hure;</L>
<L N="60">It semed hym wel a mesure;</L>
<L>he rood wi&thorn;outen hose &amp; sho,&mdash;</L>
<L>his wone was nou&yogh;th so forto do;&mdash;</L>
<L>his shankes semeden al blood rede;</L>
<L N="64">Myne herte wop for grete drede;</L>
<L>Als a pilgryme he rood to Rome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ider he com wel swi&thorn;e sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;rid sweuene me mette a ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="68">Ri&yogh;th of &thorn;at derwor&thorn;e kni&yogh;th;</L>
<L>&thorn;e wedenysday a ni&yogh;th it was,</L>
<L>Next &thorn;e day of seint lucie<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Lucy. Virgin and Martyr, Dec. 13.'&mdash;Nicolas.</NOTE> bifore cristenmesse.</L>
<L>Ich shewe &thorn;is, god of heuene:</L>
<L N="72">To mychel ioye he tourne my sweuene!</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;th &thorn;at ich was at Rome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ider ich com swi&thorn;e sone:</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="foot">'pope' <I>crosst through</I>.</NOTE>, &amp; sir Edward oure kyng,</L>
<L N="76">Bo&thorn;e hij hadden a newe dubbyng;</L>
<L>Hure gray was her clo&thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ere clo&thorn;es sei&yogh; ich no&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope<NOTE PLACE="foot">'pope' <I>crosst through</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;ede bifore, mytred wel faire I-wys;</L>
<L N="80">&thorn;e kyng Edward com corouned myd gret blis;</L>
<L>&thorn;at bitokne&thorn; he shal be</L>
<L>Emperour in cristianete:</L>
<L>Iesus crist ful of grace,</L>
<L N="84">Graunte oure kyng, in euery place,</L>
<L>Maistrie of his wi&thorn;erwynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">A.S. <I>wi&eth;erwynna</I>, adversary, enemy.</NOTE>,
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>And of alle wicked sarasynes!</L>
<L>Me met a sweuene, on wor&thorn;ing-ni&yogh;th<NOTE PLACE="foot">I can't find what or when this is.</NOTE>.</L>
<L N="88">Of &thorn;at ilche derwor&thorn;e kni&yogh;th;</L>
<L>God ich it shewe, &amp; to witnesse take,</L>
<L>And so shilde me fro synne &amp; sake!</L>
<L>In-to an chapel ich com of oure lefdy;</L>
<L N="92">Iesus crist, hire leue son, stood by;</L>
<L>On rode he was, an louelich Man,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ilk &thorn;at on rode was don.</L>
<L>He vnneiled his honden two,</L>
<L N="96">And seide, 'wi&thorn; &thorn;e kni&yogh;th he wolde go':</L>
<L>"Maiden, &amp; moder, &amp; mylde quene,</L>
<L>Ich mote my kni&yogh;th to-day sene.</L>
<L>Leue moder, &yogh;iue me leue,</L>
<L N="100">ffor ich ne may no lenger bileue;</L>
<L>Ich mote conueye &thorn;at ilk kni&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;at vs ha&thorn; serued day and ni&yogh;th:</L>
<L>In pilerinage he wil gon,</L>
<L N="104">To bien awreke of oure fon."</L>
<L>"Leue son, &yogh;oure wille, so mote it be,</L>
<L>for &thorn;e kni&yogh;th bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;th ha&thorn; serued me,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e at oure wille wel faire I-wys,</L>
<L N="108">&thorn;erfore he ha&thorn; serued heuene-riche blis."</L>
<L>God &thorn;at is in heuene so bri&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Be wi&thorn; oure kyng bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;th!</L>
<L>Amen, Amen, so mote it be!</L>
<L N="112">&thorn;erto bidde&thorn; a pater noster &amp; an Aue.</L>
<L>&para; Adam, &thorn;e marchal, of stretford-atte-bowe&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel swi&thorn;e wide his name is yknowe,&mdash;</L>
<L>He hym-self mette &thorn;is metyng&mdash;</L>
<L N="116">To witnesse he take&thorn; Iesu heuene kyng,&mdash;</L>
<L>On Wedenysday in clene leinte</L>
<L>A voice me bede I ne shulde nou&yogh;th feinte;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sweuenes &thorn;at her ben write,</L>
<L N="120">I shulde swi&thorn;e don my lorde kyng to wite.
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>Ich ansuerde, '&thorn;at I ne mi&yogh;th for derk gon.'</L>
<L>&thorn;e vois me bad goo, for li&yogh;th ne shuld ich faile non,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at I ne shulde lette for no&thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="124">&thorn;at ich shulde shewe &thorn;e kyng my metyng.</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; ich went swi&thorn;e onon,</L>
<L>Estward as me &thorn;ou&yogh;th ich mi&yogh;th gon:</L>
<L>&thorn;e li&yogh;th of heuene me com to,</L>
<L N="128">As ich in my waye shulde go.</L>
<L>"Lorde, my body ich &yogh;elde &thorn;ee to,</L>
<L>What &yogh;oure wille is wi&thorn; me to do.</L>
<L>Ich take to witnesse god of heuene,</L>
<L N="132">&thorn;at so&thorn;lich ich mette &thorn;is ilche sweuene<NOTE PLACE="foot">"The Lady protests too much, methinks."&mdash;<I>Hamlet</I>, III. ii. 240.</NOTE>!</L>
<L>I ne reiche what &yogh;ee myd my body do,</L>
<L>Als wisselich Iesus of heuene my soule vndergo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;ursday next &thorn;e beryng of oure lefdy<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nativity of the Virgin Mary, Sept. 8.&mdash;Nicolas.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="136">Me &thorn;ou&yogh;th an Aungel com sir Edward by:</L>
<L>&thorn;e Aungel bitook sir Edward on honde;</L>
<L>Al bledyng &thorn;e foure for&thorn;er clawes so were of &thorn;e lombe.</L>
<L>At Caunterbiry, bifore &thorn;e hei&yogh;e autere, &thorn;e kyng stood,</L>
<L>yclo&thorn;ed al in rede: murre he was of &thorn;at blee red as blood.</L>
<L N="141">God, &thorn;at was on gode-friday don on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>So turne my sweuene ni&yogh;th &amp; day to mychel gode!</L>
<L>Tweye poynt&yogh; &thorn;ere ben &thorn;at ben vnshewed,<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">ffor me ne wor&thorn;e to clerk ne lewed;</L>
<L>Bot to sir Edward oure kyng,</L>
<L>hym wil ich shewe &thorn;ilk metyng.</L>
<L>&para; Ich telle &yogh;ou forso&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen les,</L>
<L N="148">Als god of heuene maide marie to moder ches,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Aungel com to me, Adam Dauy, &amp; sede,</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;ou, Adam, shewe &thorn;is, &thorn;ee wor&thorn;e wel yuel mede!"</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore, my lorde sir Edward &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="152">I shewe &yogh;ou &thorn;is ilk metyng,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e Aungel it shewed me in a visioun.
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is tokenyng bifalle, so doo&thorn; me in-to prisoun!</L>
<L>Lorde, my body is to &yogh;oure wille<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. willelle.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="156">&thorn;ei&yogh; &yogh;ee wille&thorn; me &thorn;erfore spille,</L>
<L>Ich it wil take in &thorn;olemodenesse,</L>
<L>Als god graunte vs heuene blisse;</L>
<L>And lete vs neuere &thorn;erof mysse,</L>
<L N="160">&thorn;at we ne moten &thorn;ider wende in clennesse!</L>
<L>Amen, amen, so mote it be,</L>
<L>And lete vs neuere to o&thorn;ere waye tee!</L>
<L>Who so wil speke myd me, Adam &thorn;e marchal,</L>
<L N="164">In stretfor&thorn;e-bowe he is yknowe, &amp; ouere al.</L>
<L>Ich ne shewe nou&yogh;th &thorn;is forto haue mede,</L>
<L>Bot for god almi&yogh;tties drede;</L>
<TRAILER>&para; ffor it is soo&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="end">[Follows, <I>The Jest of Alisaunder</I>, printed in Weber's <I>Romances</I>, vol. i.
<Q><L>"DIuers is &thorn;is myddellerede</L><L>To lewed Men &amp; to lerede;</L><L>Bysynesse / care &amp; sorou&yogh;</L><L>Is myd Man vche morow&yogh;e." (&amp;c.)]</L></Q></NOTE></TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="legend">

<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="17">
<HEAD>The Legend or Life of St. Alexius,<LB>IN FOUR VERSIONS, FROM SIX MANUSCRIPTS.</HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P><LIST>
<LABEL>1.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The longest version, in 12-line stanzas, from Laud MS. 622, in the Bodleian.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The shortest version, in couplets, from the Cotton MS., Titus A xxvi, in the British Museum.</ITEM>
<LABEL>3.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The shorter 6-line-stanza version, from the grand Vernon MS. (ab. 1400 A.D.) and Laud 108, both in the Bodleian.</ITEM>
<LABEL>4.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The longer 6-line-stanza version, from Laud MS. 463 in the Bodleian, and Trin. Coll. MS. Oxford 57 [81].</ITEM>
</LIST>
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="18"></P><P>[THE first following version of the <I>Life of St Alexius</I>, from Laud 622, is the longest&mdash;and latest, no doubt<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is a MS. of the Life in the Durham Cathedral Library, but my enquiries about it have not yet elicited any answer.</NOTE>,&mdash;of the English forms of the story. It was unknown to Dr Horstmann when he edited his <I>Altenglische Legenden;</I> and he having calld my attention to the other three versions of the Alexius legend, I have, for completeness' sake, added them here. I have also printed the Laud 108 opposite the Vernon text, from which it differs slightly sometimes in words, and in more distinctly Midland forms (<I>waster</I>, was there, l. 10; <I>hauest tou</I>, l. 490; <I>and tou</I>, l. 496; <I>and te</I>, l. 547; some <I>a</I> forms, like <I>gan</I>, l. 168), for convenience of comparison of two later repre|sentatives of one unknown original. I should perhaps apologize for wasting so much space on a mere legend of a so-calld saint's life. But the present story is the same pathetic one as Guy of Warwick's; it is prettily versified; and the comparing of the four ways in which the same incidents are told, has a certain interest: one likes to see how the religious-story writers of old spun out or shortend their material<NOTE PLACE="foot">Note how the shorter versions lengthen the end of the story.</NOTE>: and the oddness of their notions as to the line of his images' life that pleasd the God and Father of men, is always in|structive, specially when set beside many of the popular ideas on this and like subjects now. If folk would but stop attributing to God, motives, opinions, arrangements and likings, which they'd con|sider an insult to set down to any wise and good friend of their own, how much useless bother would come to an end!</P><P>Dr Horstmann,&mdash;who edited the Laud 108 Life in Herrig's <I>Archiv</I>, vol. iii. p. 102-10, 1873<NOTE PLACE="foot">I believe that he has since edited the Vernon, Trinity and Laud-463 texts.</NOTE>&mdash;says that the sources of the Alexius legend are the '<I>Vita metrica</I>, auctore Marbodo, primum archidiacono Andegavensi, deinde Redonensi episcopo (&dagger; 1123)', printed in the Acta Sanctorum, Boll. 17. Juli, p. 254-256; and another '<I>Vita</I>, auctore anonymo', ib. p. 251-254. To the last, the Laud 108 version is nearly related, often even in words. Eight Middle High German versions of this Legend were edited by Mass|mann, Quedlinburg, 1843. The following Early English lives do not belong to the great Collection of long-line "Saints' Lives" in the Harleian, Vernon, and other MSS, from which I printed a selec|tion<NOTE PLACE="foot">And mistakingly printed 'i<SUP>c</SUP>' as Midland or Northern 'ic', instead of the Southern 'ich'.</NOTE> for the Philological Society in 1863 for its <I>Transactions</I>, of 1858. This Collection will be edited in a separate volume some day for the E. E. Text Society, by Dr Horstmann, after he has edited for us all the Extra Legends not in the Collection or in the Vernon Gospel-stories.]</P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="19">
<HEAD>THE LEGEND OR LIFE OF ST. ALEXIUS.<LB>FROM SIX MANUSCRIPTS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>[<I>Laud MS.</I> 622, <I>leaf</I> 21, <I>back</I>.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>ALle &thorn;at willen here in ryme</L>
<L>Hou gode Men in olde tyme</L>
<L N="3">Loueden god almi&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;at weren riche of grete valoure,</L>
<L>Kynges sones and Emperoure,</L>
<L N="6">Of bodies stronge &amp; li&yogh;th:</L>
<L>&yogh;ee habbe&thorn; yherd ofte in geste</L>
<L>Of holy men maken feste</L>
<L N="9">Bo&thorn;e daye &amp; ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L>fforto haue &thorn;e ioye in heuene</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Aungels song &amp; mery steuene,</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;ere blis is brode &amp; bri&yogh;th.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To &yogh;ou alle, hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ri&yogh;th so&thorn;e to biknowe</L>
<L N="15">&yogh;oure soules forto saue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e self waye &thorn;at god &yogh;ede</L>
<L>To folowe hym I wolde &yogh;ou rede,</L>
<L N="18">heuene forto craue;</L>
<L>And so duden &thorn;apostles alle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to Iesu wolden calle,</L>
<L N="21">ffor nou&yogh;th &thorn;ai nolde bilaue,</L>
<L>And to penaunce &thorn;ai hem took,</L>
<L>werldes wele &thorn;ai al forsook</L>
<L N="24">Oure lordes loue to haue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;ise o&thorn;ere holy seintz &amp; gode,</L>
<L>Martirs, virgines mylde of mode,</L>
<L N="27">And &thorn;ise confessoures,</L>
<L>Religious &thorn;at her lijf willen di&yogh;th,</L>
<L>fforto seruen god almi&yogh;th</L>
<L N="30">By tides &amp; by houres;</L>
<L>&yogh;ee haue yherd saide wel ofte</L>
<L>Man may nou&yogh;th lede lijf to softe,</L>
<L N="33">And wonen in heuene boures.</L>
<L>&thorn;e godspel sei&thorn; we moten lete</L>
<L>werldes lijf, &thorn;at &thorn;inke&thorn; vs swete,</L>
<L N="36">And suffren hard shoures,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffader &amp; moder &amp; werldes goode,</L>
<L>And folowe hym &thorn;at dyed on rode</L>
<L N="39">ffor oure synnes sake;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an shullen we haue his loue,</L>
<L>And ioye &amp; blis wi&thorn; hym a-boue</L>
<L N="42">&thorn;at he for vs gan make.</L>
<L>I shal &yogh;ou now telle wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of on &thorn;at is name cou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="45">&thorn;at suffred woo &amp; wrake.</L>
<L>his holy lijf &amp; his godenesse</L>
<L>I may tellen more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L N="48">In woo hou he gan wake.
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; he forsook confort of al his kynde,</L>
<L>Richesse he lete al bihynde,</L>
<L N="51">To god al he hym took:</L>
<L>Alexius is his name in storie,</L>
<L>writen of whom is made memorie</L>
<L N="54">In many holy book.</L>
<L>In Rome, &thorn;at was noble Cite,</L>
<L>woned a Man of grete pouste,</L>
<L N="57">&thorn;at mychel mir&thorn;e a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. of a]</NOTE> wook;</L>
<L>his lijf he lad worschiplich,</L>
<L>honoured he was of pouere &amp; riche</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at on hym gan look.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens was his name;</L>
<L>Of godenesse was his fame</L>
<L N="63">In &thorn;e Cite of Rome.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore &thorn;e riche Emperoure</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Cite made hym Cenatoure.</L>
<L N="66">ffor loos of his wisdome.
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>Riche he was of grete honoures,</L>
<L>Of londes, Castels, &amp; of toures;</L>
<L N="69">Men speken of hym ylome</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;inges wi&thorn;outen strijf;</L>
<L>Vche man he tau&yogh;tte holy lijf</L>
<L N="72">To his court &thorn;at come.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Stronge he was in armes &amp; li&yogh;th,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins Erle, baroun, &amp; kni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="75">his lordes ri&yogh;th to defende;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore hym loued &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>And made hym maister &amp; gouern|oure</L>
<L>Of his tresore to spende.</L>
<L>To his somouns in armes clers</L>
<L>Two &thorn;ousandes he had of bachelers,</L>
<L N="81">&thorn;at curteis weren &amp; hende,</L>
<L>And alle yshred in clo&thorn;es of golde,</L>
<L>None fairer mi&yogh;tten ben on molde,</L>
<L N="84">In &thorn;e werldes ende.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Men &thorn;at &yogh;eden in pilerinage</L>
<L>And Men of ordre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. oydre]</NOTE>, was his vsage</L>
<L N="87">Often forto fede.<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dame Agloes hi&yogh;th his spouse,</L>
<L>Her dedes weren wel preciouse</L>
<L N="90">Holy lijf to lede.</L>
<L>She was fair honeste &amp; wijs,</L>
<L>Louelich, &amp; of gret prijs,</L>
<L N="93">Ycome of gode kynrede;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins no Man she mystook,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; contenaunce ne wi&thorn; look,</L>
<L N="96">Noi&thorn;er in word ne dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Barayne was &thorn;at gode wijf,</L>
<L>In sorou&yogh; she ledde her lijf,</L>
<L N="99">ffor she no childe hadde.</L>
<L>hir lorde for &thorn;at ilk &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Ofte his honden gan to wrynge,</L>
<L N="102">And sorou&yogh;ful lijf he ladde;
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>ffor he wende &thorn;at god almi&yogh;th</L>
<L>had ben wroo&thorn; wi&thorn; hym apli&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="105">&thorn;ereof sore hym dradde.</L>
<L>Ofte he bisou&yogh;th god in heuene</L>
<L>Sende hem a childe, wi&thorn; mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="108">To maken hem bli&thorn;e &amp; gladde,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Conforte of hym forto haue,</L>
<L>her godes after hem to saue,</L>
<L N="111">her londes &amp; her ledes;</L>
<L>her eyre of hym forto make,</L>
<L>And her richesse hym bitake,</L>
<L N="114">Palfreies &amp; her stedes.</L>
<L>Ofte &thorn;ai maden &thorn;us her bone,</L>
<L>And god sent hem grace sone,</L>
<L N="117">&thorn;at fulfilde were &thorn;oo dedes:</L>
<L>A son conceyued &thorn;at gode wijf;</L>
<L>Tyme com in her olde lijf</L>
<L N="120">ybore it most be nedes
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;ai &thorn;ankeden god, &amp; glade were,</L>
<L>And avoweden in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L N="123">Chastite bo&thorn;e to take,</L>
<L>And to lyuen in clene lijf,</L>
<L>Eufeniens &amp; his gode wijf,</L>
<L N="126">And synne to forsake.</L>
<L>&thorn;e childe was mery in al manere,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ai maden her praiere,</L>
<L N="129">Ani&yogh;th as &thorn;ai gan wake.</L>
<L>Alexius &thorn;ai gonnen hym calle;</L>
<L>yloued he was amonges hem alle</L>
<L N="132">&thorn;at to hym gonnen take.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alexius was sett to boke,</L>
<L>To gode maistres &thorn;ai hym toke,</L>
<L N="135">And wise of clergie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e more he wex in elde &amp; leng&thorn;e,</L>
<L>To seruen god he dude his streng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="138">And his moder Marie.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Emperour whan he was brou&yogh;th</L>
<L>&thorn;ere dedes of Armes weren ywrou&yogh;th</L>
<L N="141">To lernen chiualrye;</L>
<L>&thorn;ere mi&yogh;th he sen in tour[na]ment</L>
<L>what kni&yogh;th was dou&yogh;ttiest of dent</L>
<L N="144">And man of most maistrie.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; His fader was bo&thorn;e wijs &amp; ware,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at his son so wel hym bare,</L>
<L N="147">he loued hym al his lijf.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;th to don swiche puruyaunce,</L>
<L>whar-wi&thorn; he mi&yogh;th hym avaunce</L>
<L N="150">And wynne hym a wijf.</L>
<L>To a riche prince his son he sent,</L>
<L>And afterward to hym he went,</L>
<L N="153">Stille wi&thorn;outen strijf:</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;tter he had, bri&yogh;th &amp; shene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e heritage shulde hires bene</L>
<L N="156">Of Castel &amp; londes rijf.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; whan ay&thorn;er herd o&thorn;eres wille,</L>
<L>And speken &thorn;erof to-gedre stille</L>
<L N="159">To make &thorn;at sposaile,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tyme comen was &thorn;e day</L>
<L>To fulfille wi&thorn;outen delay,</L>
<L N="162">Certeyn, wi&thorn;outen faile,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e chirche of seint Bonefas</L>
<L>wi&thorn; &thorn;is maiden &thorn;ai token &thorn;e pas,</L>
<L N="165">&thorn;at hei&yogh;e was of paraile;</L>
<L>As custume was &amp; shulde be,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai maden gret solempnite,</L>
<L N="168">&thorn;e Pope &amp; his conseile.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alexius was shamefast,</L>
<L>And of weddyng he was agast,</L>
<L N="171">his vijs al pale bywent;</L>
<L>Leuer hym were to be ded</L>
<L>&thorn;an haue ytrowed &thorn;at ilk red</L>
<L N="174">By his owen assent.</L>
<L>He ne wist what he mi&yogh;th don;</L>
<L>fful gret sorou&yogh; com hym on,</L>
<L N="177">he helde hym-self shent.</L>
<L>To god he gan hym al affye,</L>
<L>And to his moder seint Marie,</L>
<L N="180">Trewely, wi&thorn; gode entent.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Na&thorn;eles he lete his heuynysse,</L>
<L>And made mychel ioye &amp; blisse</L>
<L N="183">At &thorn;at solempnite.</L>
<L>He bare hym curteislich &amp; tsllie,</L>
<L>To fulfille his faders wille,</L>
<L N="186">Glad as he had ybe.</L>
<L>ffulfild was &thorn;e weddyng</L>
<L>wi&thorn; ioye &amp; blis in al &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="189">&thorn;at many man mi&yogh;th see.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ni&yogh;th was comen, &amp; &thorn;e day gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kni&yogh;ttes waten on &amp; on</L>
<L N="192">To her owen cuntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens his son gan calle,</L>
<L>And tidynges amonge hem alle</L>
<L N="195">He tolde hym &thorn;at were newe.</L>
<L>'Son, to &thorn;i chaumbre &thorn;ou most wende,</L>
<L>To &thorn;i wijf fair &amp; hende,<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="198">Blysful &amp; bri&yogh;th of hewe.'
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>And whan Alixius herd &thorn;at word</L>
<L>It pricked his hert as speres oord,</L>
<L N="201">So sore it gan hym rewe;</L>
<L>Bot his fader wra&thorn;&thorn;i he nolde,</L>
<L>He had leuer be vnder molde,</L>
<L N="204">&thorn;at neuer man hym knewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; whan &thorn;e folk was went away,</L>
<L>And he al-one in chaumbre lay,</L>
<L N="207">Alexius gan to preche;</L>
<L>Of Iesu he bigan his game,</L>
<L>werldes likyng he gan blame,</L>
<L N="210">his &yogh;onge wijf to teche.</L>
<L>He tau&yogh;tte hir, &thorn;at was so hende,</L>
<L>Hou she shulde haue god to frende</L>
<L N="213">&thorn;at is oure soules leche;</L>
<L>&yogh;if she wolde alle her lijf</L>
<L>Duelle bo&thorn;e maiden &amp; wijf,</L>
<L N="216">&thorn;e fende she mi&yogh;th do wreche.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;at maiden herkned swi&thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>And whan he seide had al his wille</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy gost hir lau&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>And she hym graunted wi&thorn; mylde mood</L>
<L>To louen Iesu &thorn;at dyed [on] rood,</L>
<L N="222">As he hym-self hir tau&yogh;tte.</L>
<L>Alexius was &thorn;oo glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>his ioye cou&thorn;e he noman ki&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="225">his spouse a ryng he rau&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>And seide to hir, 'my suete &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Take to &thorn;ee &thorn;is ilk ryng,</L>
<L N="228">And kepe it in &thorn;ine au&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Of me whan &thorn;ou wilt haue mynde</L>
<L>Loke here-on, as &thorn;ou art hende,</L>
<L N="231">Bo&thorn;e by day &amp; ni&yogh;th.</L>
<L>In pilerynage now wil I go,</L>
<L>And half &thorn;e godenesse &thorn;at I do</L>
<L N="234">Graunte &thorn;ee god almi&yogh;th.'
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>Alexius &thorn;us his leue tooke;</L>
<L>Rewely his wijf gan on hym loke</L>
<L>&thorn;at was so fair &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. w]</NOTE> bri&yogh;th;</L>
<L N="238">She ne wist to what londe</L>
<L>&thorn;at she mi&yogh;th sende hym any sonde,</L>
<L N="240">Doune fel &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;th.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alixius from his richesse</L>
<L>In-to pouert &amp; wrecchednesse,</L>
<L N="243">ffrom his frendes he fledde.</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e Cee he com wel sory,</L>
<L>A shippe he fonde to seil redy,</L>
<L N="246">&thorn;e holy gost hym ledde.</L>
<L>Of his golde &amp; of his pens</L>
<L>wel he aquited his despens,</L>
<L N="249">hendely of &thorn;at he hedde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wynde aroos at her wille,</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er &thorn;ai wolde, loude or stille;</L>
<L N="252">At her likyng &thorn;ai spedde.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; At a Cite Galys men calle</L>
<L>To londe &thorn;ai gonnen aryuen alle,</L>
<L N="255">wi&thorn;outen enpeirement.</L>
<L>Alexius of hem took leue,</L>
<L>And worschiplich &thorn;ai hym &yogh;eue:</L>
<L N="258">To chircheward he went.</L>
<L>He &thorn;anked god wi&thorn; good wille</L>
<L>Erly &amp; late, loude &amp; stille,</L>
<L N="261">&thorn;at &thorn;ider hem hadde sent.</L>
<L>He bisou&yogh;th god, &amp; gan to wepe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at from &thorn;e fende he shulde hym kepe</L>
<L N="264">And his enticement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;us he &thorn;at had riche wedes,</L>
<L>Hei&yogh;e hors, &amp; gode stedes,</L>
<L N="267">And Armes bri&yogh;th &amp; shene,</L>
<L>Al he leet &thorn;e godes gret,</L>
<L>And went on his bare feet,</L>
<L N="270">his soule to make clene.
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>Ofte it fel in his mende</L>
<L>Of his fader &amp; moder hende,</L>
<L N="273">&thorn;at sou&yogh;th he schulde bene.</L>
<L>He wolde for none kynnes &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&thorn;at Men hadden of hym knouyng,</L>
<L N="276">&thorn;erfore he gan to flene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffrom &thorn;at cuntre swi&thorn;e he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>To-ward Surrie in feble wede,</L>
<L N="279">&thorn;at noman shulde hym knowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;ere he duelled in grete pouerte,</L>
<L>In hunger, in &thorn;orst, &amp; o&thorn;er smerte,</L>
<L N="282">&thorn;at many man it sowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cee of grece passed he is,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e Cite of Annys,</L>
<L N="285">He com &thorn;at ilk &thorn;rowe.</L>
<L>God he bitau&yogh;tte his compaignye,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ede to a chirche of seint Marie</L>
<L N="288">wi&thorn; herte meke and lowe.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; At &thorn;at chirche is an ymage</L>
<L>Of oure lefdy vpon a stage,</L>
<L N="291">&thorn;at many man ha&thorn; sou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>It was ymaked of Aungels honde,</L>
<L>To def &amp; doumbe of o&thorn;ere londe</L>
<L N="294">Miracle &thorn;ere was wrou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Alexius was glad &amp; bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>His ioye cou&thorn;e he noman ki&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="297">In hert ne in &thorn;ou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>whan he mi&yogh;th seen in signe</L>
<L>Hou goddes ymage fair &amp; digne</L>
<L N="300">In his moders barme was brou&yogh;th.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Often he made his orisoune,</L>
<L>wepande wi&thorn; deuocioune,</L>
<L N="303">To &thorn;e quene of heuene,</L>
<L>And seide, 'moder mylde &amp; free,</L>
<L>Praie &thorn;i son of gret pouste</L>
<L N="306">ffor his names seuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at from heuene com to &thorn;ee,<MILESTONE N="23a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By assent of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L N="309">&thorn;orou&yogh; &thorn;e Aungels steuene,</L>
<L>Here to suffre many peynes</L>
<L>In al his body &amp; his veynes,</L>
<L N="312">In er&thorn;e as I can neuene,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'And &thorn;at he shewe&thorn; in his mercy,</L>
<L>Marie, to &thorn;ee I make my cry,</L>
<L N="315">&thorn;at am a synful Man;</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; his blood &amp; peynes grene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche to vs purchaced ene,</L>
<L N="318">ffro helle he vs wan.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>Swete Iesu, heuene sire,</L>
<L>warisshed he is &thorn;at wil &thorn;e desire</L>
<L N="321">ffrom &thorn;e fende sathan.</L>
<L>wel is hym &thorn;at suffren may</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i loue ni&yogh;th oi&thorn;ere day,</L>
<L N="324">Peyne &thorn;at paie &thorn;ee can.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>&para; whan no&thorn;ing nas hym bileued,</L>
<L>And he fer from his frendes to dreued,</L>
<L N="327">his clo&thorn;es weren to rent.</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e pouere in &thorn;e chirche haw&yogh;e</L>
<L>he begged, &amp; was her felaw&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="330">And took &thorn;at god hym sent.</L>
<L>Almesse &thorn;at god hym &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pouer &thorn;at wolde &thorn;ere bileue</L>
<L N="333">wi&thorn; hym in present,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af &thorn;at haluendel &amp; more,</L>
<L>And was hym-self of hungred sore,</L>
<L N="336">And took it in good entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Euery sonenday houseled he was,</L>
<L>And shryuen also of vche trespas</L>
<L N="339">&thorn;at fel to any synne.</L>
<L>Michel he waked &amp; litel he sleep,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he shulde his body wi&thorn; kepe,</L>
<L N="342">Litel hym com wi&thorn;inne.</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e tyme he took his tourne</L>
<L>ffrom Rome, &thorn;ere he was borne,</L>
<L N="345">he was sou&yogh;th of his kynne</L>
<L>In alle cuntrees, in euery toun,</L>
<L>In chirche, in felde, vp &amp; doun,</L>
<L N="348">ffor nou&yogh;th wolde &thorn;ai blynne.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&para; His kynrede com &thorn;ere hym biside,</L>
<L>&thorn;at had ysou&yogh;th hym fer &amp; wide,</L>
<L N="351">&amp; &yogh;af hym her Almesse,</L>
<L>As he sat amonge &thorn;e pouere,</L>
<L>In grete meschief &amp; stronge to couere,</L>
<L N="354">ffor hunger in wrecchednesse.</L>
<L>Sore of hym &thorn;ai gonnen rewe,</L>
<L>Stille he satt, &amp; wel hem knewe,</L>
<L N="357">Her names more &amp; lesse.</L>
<L>Ychaunged was his faire hewe</L>
<L>&thorn;orou&yogh; reyn &amp; wynde &thorn;at on hym blewe,</L>
<L N="360">And o&thorn;er stronge destresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&para; whan &thorn;ai mi&yogh;tten nou&yogh;th spede,</L>
<L>Ne hym of axen in no &thorn;ede</L>
<L N="363">Ne in no londe of take,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; sorou&yogh; &thorn;ai gradde, allas! allas!</L>
<L>And wenten to Rome, &thorn;e ri&yogh;th pas,</L>
<L N="366">her sorou&yogh; mi&yogh;th nou&yogh;th slake.</L>
<L>Alexius no&thorn;ing &thorn;ou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Bot on Iesu crist he &thorn;ou&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="369">And grete ioye he gan make</L>
<L>ffor he ne was nou&yogh;th biknowe</L>
<L>Of his frendes hei&yogh;e ne lowe,</L>
<L N="372">His wel&thorn;e gan a-wake.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens seide in his mende,</L>
<L>'&thorn;e most wrecche fer oi&thorn;ere hende</L>
<L N="375">Certes now am I.</L>
<L>Conforte ne ioye ne may me come;</L>
<L>Now my childe is me bynome</L>
<L N="378">My song is tourned to cry.</L>
<L>My wijf is barayne, &amp; ek olde;</L>
<L>She ne may haue no childe for colde,</L>
<L N="381">Oure heir al forto by.</L>
<L>In sorou&yogh; &amp; care my lijf is di&yogh;th,</L>
<L>ffor to dye it were my ri&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="384">And hennes to party.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>&para; wi&thorn; &thorn;at his moder fel to grounde</L>
<L>And lay yswowen a longe stounde,</L>
<L N="387">And roos vp al afrayed:</L>
<L>'My leue son, &thorn;at were so meke,</L>
<L>I ne woot where I shal &thorn;ee seke,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;erefore I am dismayed.'</L>
<L>His moder ne mi&yogh;th lete sorou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er at euene ne at morowe,</L>
<L N="393">In saw&yogh;e as it is seide.</L>
<L>To hir chaumbre she went in hast,</L>
<L>And of hire bedd &thorn;e clo&thorn;es doun cast,</L>
<L N="396">And si&thorn;en hem al to breyde,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ciclatounes &thorn;at weren of prijs,</L>
<L>Pelured wi&thorn; Ermyne &amp; wi&thorn; grijs,</L>
<L N="399">Alle she cast away,</L>
<L>And wered clo&thorn;es symple &amp; blake.</L>
<L>Litel she sleep, &amp; mychel gan wake,</L>
<L N="402">And fasted euery daye.</L>
<L>'Lorde,' she seide, 'almi&yogh;tty,</L>
<L>To &thorn;ee &amp; to &thorn;i moder mary</L>
<L N="405">I make a vow, &amp; saye,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I shal neuer hennes wende</L>
<L>Tyl Alexius come oi&thorn;er sende,</L>
<L N="408">Oi&thorn;er I be roted in clay.'
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now mowen &yogh;ee here pleynt pitouse</L>
<L>Of Alexius trewe spouse,</L>
<L N="411">Hou she made her mone;</L>
<L>In gret sorou&yogh; was hir entent,</L>
<L>Her here she drou&yogh;, her clo&thorn;es rent,</L>
<L N="414">Grymly she gan grone.</L>
<L>'Al my &yogh;ou&thorn;e &amp; my solas,</L>
<L>Myne hope, is lorne, allas,</L>
<L>And my bidyng alone.<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I. am bo&thorn;e maiden &amp; wijf,</L>
<L>I. noot to whom telle my strijf,</L>
<L N="420">I lyue as ankre in stone.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Si&thorn;&thorn;e I ne haue to whom me mene,</L>
<L>Lijk is my lijf on to sene&mdash;</L>
<L N="423">&thorn;at am wi&thorn;outen red&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e turtel &thorn;at is for sorou&yogh; lene,</L>
<L>And trede&thorn; on no gras grene,</L>
<L N="426">Si&thorn;en hire make is ded.</L>
<L>Allas, hou shal I. ioye haue?</L>
<L>Oi&thorn;er hou shal I my-seluen saue</L>
<L N="429">To lyue in maidenhede?</L>
<L>Me were leuer of hym a si&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;an welde al &thorn;is londe ri&yogh;th</L>
<L N="432">In leng&thorn;e &amp; in brede.'
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>&para; She roos vp erlich a morowe,</L>
<L>And to his moder she went in sorou&yogh;</L>
<L N="435">ffor loue of hire spouse,</L>
<L>And praied hir &thorn;at she most duelle</L>
<L>wi&thorn; hir, &thorn;at sorou&yogh;ful pleynt to telle,</L>
<L N="438">&thorn;at strong was and greuouse.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lefdy was wel apaied</L>
<L>whan she had &thorn;us yseied,</L>
<L N="441">&thorn;at was so preciouse.</L>
<L>And at oo bed &amp; oo clo&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Seuentene &yogh;er was her duellyng</L>
<L N="444">Bo&thorn;e in one house.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lordynges, &yogh;ee &thorn;at wille&thorn; lere,</L>
<L>a faire miracle &yogh;ee mowen here:</L>
<L N="447">Bifore &thorn;at self ymage,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere &thorn;at Alexius sate</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pouere men in &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="450">As a pouere page,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ymage, &thorn;at aungels gonne wirche,</L>
<L>Spaak to &thorn;e serieauntz of &thorn;e chirche</L>
<L N="453">&thorn;ere she stood on &thorn;e stage,</L>
<L>And hete hem alle wi&thorn;outen lettynge</L>
<L>Goddes sergeaunt to chirche brynge</L>
<L N="456">wi&thorn;outen any outrage.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'He is ri&yogh;th stedfast of lijf;</L>
<L>His werkes shullen ben made rijf</L>
<L N="459">Ouer al fer &amp; neere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy gost wi&thorn;inne hym rest;</L>
<L>Charite sitte&thorn; in his breest,</L>
<L N="462">Brennande as fyre.</L>
<L>Longe in pouerte his lijf he ha&thorn; led;</L>
<L>He ne com neuere in no bed</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;ise seuentene &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>His holy lijf, bot god alone,</L>
<L>Ne woot non in &thorn;is werldes wone;</L>
<L N="468">To seint&yogh; he may be pere.'
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e sergeauntz lepen out in hast,</L>
<L>As men &thorn;at weren sore agast,</L>
<L N="471">And ful of grete drede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ymage &thorn;at to hem spak</L>
<L>Of goddes sergeaunt wi&thorn;outen lak</L>
<L N="474">&thorn;at sat in beggers wede.</L>
<L>wyde aboute &thorn;ai hym sou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ut founden &thorn;ai hym nou&yogh;th</L>
<L N="477">Amonge &thorn;e pouere felawrede;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ai nou&yogh;th hym fynde mi&yogh;th,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at ymage onon ri&yogh;th</L>
<L N="480">Hastilich &thorn;ai &yogh;ede,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To &thorn;at Maryole wi&thorn; teres clere,</L>
<L>And bisou&yogh;th hir on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="483">'&thorn;at she sent hem grace</L>
<L>Goddes man hou &thorn;ai shulden knowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at had ben hei&yogh;e &amp; bare hym lowe,</L>
<L N="486">And where he sat in place.'</L>
<L>&thorn;e ymage spaak ofte wordes newe,</L>
<L>'I &yogh;ou hote, sergeaunt&yogh; trewe,</L>
<L N="489">A&yogh;ein[ward] &thorn;at &yogh;ee pace;</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e pouere he sitte&thorn;, to-tore</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bihynde &amp; bifore,</L>
<L N="492">wi&thorn; a lene face.'
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e sergeaunt&yogh; stirten out skeet,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai founden hym, &amp; kisten his feet,</L>
<L N="495">And mercy &thorn;ai hym cryde,</L>
<L>And ledden hym in-to holy chirche,</L>
<L>Goddes werkes forto wirche,</L>
<L N="498">&thorn;ereinne to abide.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e gode mannes loos</L>
<L>&thorn;e miracle &amp; &thorn;e cry aroos</L>
<L N="501">Ouere al in vche syde;</L>
<L>Michel poeple &thorn;ider ran,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e miracles &thorn;at herden &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="504">Of cuntrees fer &amp; wyde;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And worschiped hym in word &amp; dede,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at mi&yogh;tten in leng&thorn;e &amp; brede;</L>
<L N="507">And duden hym gret honoure,</L>
<L>And beden hym, bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L>He bere her erande to god almi&yogh;th</L>
<L N="510">&thorn;at is oure saueoure.</L>
<L>&thorn;o was Alexius swi&thorn;e woo</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at he was honoured soo,</L>
<L N="513">And made grete doloure;</L>
<L>For swiche honoure &amp; swiche glorie,</L>
<L>As it is writen in his storye,</L>
<L N="516">He ne loued in toun ne toure.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor &thorn;at his meryte wolde slake</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde of god take,</L>
<L N="519">&thorn;erfore it liked hym ille.</L>
<L>werldes honoure forto flee,</L>
<L>Al by ni&yogh;th, in pryuete,</L>
<L N="522">He stale away ful stille</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e londe of Galys.</L>
<L>To seint Iames chirche I-wys</L>
<L N="525">he com wi&thorn; gode wille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he sete amonge pouere men,</L>
<L>And beged his mete in &thorn;e fen,<MILESTONE N="24a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="528">his penaunce to fulfille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;oo he had &thorn;ere twelfmon&thorn;e ysete</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pouere Men, &amp; begged his mete,</L>
<L N="531">His fadres sergeaunt&yogh; come</L>
<L>And sou&yogh;tten hym forso&thorn;e I-wys</L>
<L>In pilerynage at Galys,</L>
<L N="534">To bryngen hym to Rome.</L>
<L>And whan Alexius hem gan see,</L>
<L>Stillelich he gan flee,</L>
<L N="537">As man of ri&yogh;t wisdome:</L>
<L>In-to thars he &thorn;ou&yogh;th fare,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e Royn he fonde &yogh;are</L>
<L N="540">A shippe &thorn;at was al tome,
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And Pilgrymes gret plente</L>
<L>&thorn;at wolden passen ouer &thorn;e Cee,</L>
<L N="543">To tars &thorn;at wolden &yogh;are.</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;e shipman, for goddes loue</L>
<L>&thorn;at is in heuene vs aboue,</L>
<L N="546">he most wi&thorn; hem fare.</L>
<L>Grete grucchyng &thorn;ai alle made;</L>
<L>Alexius fer &amp; ner gan wade,</L>
<L N="549">ffor nou&yogh;th wolde he spare;</L>
<L>Euere he cried loude &amp; shille,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai graunted hym his wille,</L>
<L N="552">&thorn;oo was he out of care.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;ai drowen vp seil, &thorn;e wynde was good,</L>
<L>And saileden ouer &thorn;e salt flood,</L>
<L N="555">&thorn;e weder was at her wille;</L>
<L>vntil, &thorn;e &thorn;rid dayes ende,</L>
<L>Swiche a storme Iesus gan sende,</L>
<L N="558">&thorn;at alle hem liked ille.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai wenden wel haue went to tars;</L>
<L>&thorn;e wynde was gret, &amp; no&thorn;ing skars,</L>
<L N="561">&thorn;onder dyned shille;</L>
<L>ffor li&yogh;ttynges grete, &amp; &thorn;onder blast,</L>
<L>wel sore &thorn;e poeple was agast,</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;ai grete &amp; groned grille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e wynde hem droof, forso&thorn;e to seyne,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e londe of Romeyne,</L>
<L N="567">&thorn;ere Alexius was borne;</L>
<L>&thorn;oo was &thorn;e poeple in wel more care,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at &thorn;ai were aryued &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="570">&thorn;an &thorn;ai weren er biforne;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at tyme were &thorn;e folk of Rome</L>
<L>&thorn;e mest shrewen of cristendome</L>
<L N="573">wi&thorn;outen o&thorn;es ysworne.</L>
<L>ffor pilgrymes &thorn;at aryueden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>her catel &thorn;at &thorn;ai wi&thorn; hem bere,</L>
<L N="576">On hast was forlorne.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ri&yogh;th so bifel by &thorn;oo dawes</L>
<L>By Alexius &amp; his felawes.</L>
<L N="579">Of sorou&yogh; was her speche;</L>
<L>Also sumtyme bifel a cas,</L>
<L>&thorn;oo god almi&yogh;tty bad Ionas</L>
<L N="582">To Nyniue gon &amp; preche;</L>
<L>Ionas wist wel her wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of niniue weren ille</L>
<L N="585">And wicked for to teche;</L>
<L>Away Ionas wolde haue ystole</L>
<L>ffrom goddes hest, &amp; han hym hole;</L>
<L N="588">Ak sone hym fel a wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ionas wende god bigile,</L>
<L>And wolde haue went to ano&thorn;er yle</L>
<L N="591">In &thorn;e grikkissh Cee;</L>
<L>he gan to shippen atte Ryuage;</L>
<L>wynde aroos wi&thorn; wood rage,</L>
<L N="594">&thorn;at sorou&yogh; it was to see.</L>
<L>ffyue dayes euere iliche it lest</L>
<L>wi&thorn; sorou&yogh; &amp; care, her tempest,</L>
<L N="597">&thorn;at seyl ne mi&yogh;th &thorn;ere be.</L>
<L>&thorn;an seide &thorn;e maister 'forso&thorn;e Iwys</L>
<L>Sum cursed Man amonges vs is,</L>
<L N="600">&thorn;at wel witen mowe we.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'we wille&thorn; caste amonges vs alle,</L>
<L>Lott, on whom it may bifalle,</L>
<L N="603">And ouere bord he shal be cast.'</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e prophete herde &thorn;is,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;th he had ydon amys,</L>
<L N="606">And was sore agast.</L>
<L>&thorn;ries &thorn;ai beren aboute &thorn;at lot,</L>
<L>Ac on Ionas fel vche grot,</L>
<L N="609">&thorn;e first and &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>&thorn;e maister hym &thorn;rew ouere bord;</L>
<L>A whal hym swalewe at oo word</L>
<L N="612">ffor oo morsel in hast;
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ere he dwelled forso&thorn;e apli&yogh;th</L>
<L>&thorn;re dayes fulle &amp; &thorn;re ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="615">ffor Ionas was vntrewe;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e &thorn;re dayes ende,</L>
<L>Swiche grace god gan sende,</L>
<L N="618">&thorn;e Cee to londe hym &thorn;rewe.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e whal was comen to londe,</L>
<L>&thorn;erto was many mannes honde</L>
<L N="621">On hym forto hewe;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e whal was to-cleued,</L>
<L>Ionas pylte vp his heued,</L>
<L N="624">And gan his body shewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L>&para; vp he roos, &thorn;e folk to teche,</L>
<L>And goddes wordes he gan preche,</L>
<L N="627">And lered hem her lefnesse,</L>
<L>And made hem wynne goddes loue,</L>
<L>To wonen wi&thorn; hym in heuene aboue,</L>
<L N="630">&thorn;e poeple more and lesse.</L>
<L>&para; Ri&yogh;th so Alexius had yment</L>
<L>To Tars forto haue ywent;</L>
<L N="633">Ac god hym sent destresse,</L>
<L>And made hym to Rome wende,</L>
<L>To wonen &thorn;ere among his frende,</L>
<L N="636">holy wryt bere&thorn; witnesse.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L><MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio">&para; whan Alexius was to londe ygon,</L>
<L>Seyl &thorn;ai drou&yogh;en vp onon,</L>
<L N="639">And wenten in &thorn;e Cee,</L>
<L>Al to thars till &thorn;ai come</L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e wicked londe of Rome,</L>
<L N="642">And maden solempnite.</L>
<L>Alexius com in-to his owe,</L>
<L>And of his frendes was he nou&yogh;th knowe,</L>
<L>ffor so naked was he;</L>
<L>And als a straunge man he went</L>
<L>To his fader wi&thorn; gode entent,</L>
<L N="648">And seide to hym par charite,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Eufeniens, goddes frende,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art holden good &amp; hende,</L>
<L N="651">Alesed of gret Almesse!</L>
<L>ffor his loue &thorn;at was ybete,</L>
<L>And for vs suffred woundes grete,</L>
<L N="654">helpe me in &thorn;is destresse,</L>
<L>ffor I ne can to no Man gon</L>
<L>Mete to crauen, bot &thorn;ee on,</L>
<L N="657">No herberewe more ne lesse;</L>
<L>Make of me &thorn;i bede-man!</L>
<L>And by hym &thorn;at &thorn;is werlde wan,</L>
<L N="660">&thorn;ou mi&yogh;th haue heuene blis;
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L>&para; '&yogh;iue me &thorn;e crommes of &thorn;i table,&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;an doostou dedes merciable,&mdash;</L>
<L N="663">And herberewe in &thorn;ine house;</L>
<L>And of Alexius, &thorn;i son so fre,</L>
<L>Afterward I shal telle &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="666">&thorn;at &thorn;ou helde preciouse:</L>
<L>&thorn;an shaltou be day &amp; ni&yogh;th</L>
<L>Glad, whan &thorn;ou hym seest wi&thorn; si&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="669">And ek &thorn;i trewe spouse.'</L>
<L>Eufeniens ansuered &thorn;oo,</L>
<L>'I graunt wel &thorn;at it be so.</L>
<L N="672">&thorn;ine bedes &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt ouse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To a Man he hym bitook,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seke Men cou&thorn;e wel look,</L>
<L N="675">Nou&yogh;th as a Man of task;</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;at Man he bad hym &thorn;ink,</L>
<L>And brynge hym bo&thorn;e mete &amp; drynk</L>
<L N="678">whan he wolde ask.</L>
<L>'&yogh;if god wil, my creatoure,</L>
<L>He shal be kepte wi&thorn; honoure,</L>
<L N="681">His peynes forto lask,</L>
<L>To seien his bedes, &amp; bidde for me</L>
<L>To veray god in trinite,</L>
<L N="684">fforto he be roted to ask.'
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens bad he shulde be</L>
<L>&thorn;ere &thorn;at he mi&yogh;th hym ysee</L>
<L N="687">late and erly;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e halle he shulde be layd.</L>
<L>was &thorn;ere non &thorn;at it wi&thorn;sayd,</L>
<L N="690">Bot graunted hastyly;</L>
<L>&thorn;ai loued hym more &thorn;an any man.</L>
<L>To kepe hym wel, he hete hem &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="693">And wisten neuer why</L>
<L>His wijf hym loued at herte dere;</L>
<L>wel wolde she &thorn;at he serued were,</L>
<L N="696">And mychel was hym by.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L>&para; wi&thorn;outen any grucchyng word,</L>
<L>Mete &thorn;at was vpon hire bord</L>
<L N="699">&thorn;ai senten hym to almesse,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;th of her owen dissh,</L>
<L>were it flessh oi&thorn;er fissh,</L>
<L N="702">while he was in destresse;</L>
<L>&thorn;us was &thorn;e pilegryme yserued &thorn;an.</L>
<L>who he was, wist noman,</L>
<L N="705">Gret was his &thorn;olemodenesse;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if his moder oi&thorn;er his wijf</L>
<L>hadden ywist Alexius lijf,</L>
<L N="708">It had ben her gladnesse.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L>&para; wi&thorn; hym &thorn;ai speken, &amp; hym sei&yogh;en</L>
<L>wi&thorn; her mou&thorn;e &amp; wi&thorn; her ei&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="711">ffader &amp; moder &amp; wijf;</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;th for &thorn;an non hym knew,</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er by hide ne by hew;</L>
<L N="714">Al chaunged was his lijf.</L>
<L>His fader he sei&yogh; often grete,</L>
<L>And his moder teres lete</L>
<L N="717">ffourty si&thorn;es &amp; fyue.</L>
<L>yuel mi&yogh;th hym liken &thorn;at sei&yogh; &thorn;is;</L>
<L>his martirdom was strong I-wys,</L>
<L N="720">Of sorou&yogh; &amp; paynes ryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alexius in al wise</L>
<L>Dude to god his seruise</L>
<L N="723">wi&thorn; stedfast wille in hert,</L>
<L>In fastyng, &amp; in orisouns,</L>
<L>In many manere deuociouns</L>
<L N="726">Of peynes &thorn;at weren smert.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>And al was forto wynne heuene;</L>
<L>To here Aungels wi&thorn; mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="729">he suffred &thorn;is pouert</L>
<L>ffulle seuentene &yogh;er;</L>
<L>he wered breech maked of her,</L>
<L N="732">And al swiche was his shert.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sergeauntz, &thorn;at &thorn;ere-inne were,</L>
<L>Ofte si&thorn;es gramed hym &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="735">And despised hym fast.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wasshyng of her vessel</L>
<L>&thorn;ai cast on hym euerydel,</L>
<L N="738">&thorn;at was swi&thorn;e vnwrast;</L>
<L>And cleped hym shrewe ypo|crite,</L>
<L>And ofte-tymes gonne hym smyte</L>
<L N="741">Vnder &thorn;e cheke in hast:</L>
<L>Ac Alexius was of god fulfild,</L>
<L>In gode penaunce he it helde,</L>
<L N="744">And &thorn;anked hem at &thorn;e last.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alexius, &thorn;at was goddes kni&yogh;th,</L>
<L>ffor penaunce &thorn;at was on hym li&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="747">Almest his lijf was lorne.<MILESTONE N="25a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wel he sei&yogh;, &thorn;orou&yogh; de&thorn;es law&yogh;es,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he drou&yogh; to his endyng daw&yogh;es,</L>
<L N="750">ffor de&thorn; com hym biforne.</L>
<L>His sergeaunt he cleped sone,</L>
<L>And for his loue, bad hym a bone,</L>
<L N="753">&thorn;at bare &thorn;e crovne of &thorn;orne,</L>
<L>To fecche hym enk &amp; parchemyne,</L>
<L>fforto write in latyne</L>
<L N="756">His lijf si&thorn;&thorn;e he was borne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L>&para; His sergeaunt was glad &amp; bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Enk &amp; parchemyn also swi&thorn;e</L>
<L N="759">He fette, &amp; hym bitook;</L>
<L>Alexius &thorn;o write bigan;</L>
<L>Ak &thorn;ere was non bifore &thorn;an</L>
<L N="762">&thorn;at wist he cou&thorn;e in book.</L>
<L>&thorn;ere-inne he wroot oord &amp; ende,</L>
<L>Hou he fro his wijf gan wende,</L>
<L N="765">And al his kyn forsook;</L>
<L>And hou Alex at his partyng,</L>
<L>whan he took his wijf &thorn;e ryng,</L>
<L N="768">hou rewly she gan look;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And hou in pilerynage he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>In hunger, in &thorn;orst, in pouere wede,</L>
<L N="771">And in what manere,</L>
<L>And hou he sat in grete destresse</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e pouere, &amp; fenge almesse</L>
<L N="774">Seuentene &yogh;ere;
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>And hou his frendes comen hym by,</L>
<L>And he hem knew apertely,</L>
<L N="777">&thorn;at sou&yogh;tten hym fer &amp; nere;</L>
<L>And hou he stale a-way hem fro,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non hym knew of alle &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="780">So chaunged was his chere;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And hou &thorn;e ymage of oure lefdy</L>
<L>&thorn;e sergeauntz hete apertely,</L>
<L N="783">In, hym, forto take,</L>
<L>And byd his bedes in &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L>Goddes werkes &thorn;ere to wirche,</L>
<L N="786">His sorou&yogh; forto slake;</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;at folk com fer &amp; wyde</L>
<L>To &thorn;at chirche in vche syde,</L>
<L N="789">honour hym forto make;</L>
<L>And hou he stale away hem fro,</L>
<L>And wolde nou&yogh;th be honoured so,</L>
<L N="792">bot libbe in woo &amp; wrake;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And hou he wolde to tars haue went,</L>
<L>And whiche a tempest god hym sent,</L>
<L N="795">&thorn;at droof hem to Romeyne;</L>
<L>And hou he bad his fader good</L>
<L>herberewe &amp; o&thorn;er lyues food,</L>
<L N="798">He wroot forso&thorn;e to seyne;</L>
<L>And hou he sei&yogh; seuentene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>ffader, &amp; moder, &amp; wijf &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="801">wi&thorn; sorou&yogh; &amp; mychel peyne;</L>
<L>And he wolde hem nou&yogh;th yknowe,</L>
<L>Bot bare hym bo&thorn;e symple &amp; lowe,</L>
<L N="804">&thorn;at had ben Man of meyne.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Iesus, &thorn;at is kyng of glorie,</L>
<L>his martirdom &amp; his victorie</L>
<L N="807">Sei&yogh;, &amp; his trauaile;</L>
<L>And whan he had his lijf ywrite,</L>
<L>he hidde &thorn;ere noman shulde ywite,</L>
<L N="810">his book of gode paraile.</L>
<L>Priuelich Alex it bare,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noman mi&yogh;th &thorn;erof be-ware</L>
<L N="813">Hou mychel it wolde auaile;</L>
<L>And, whan he dyed, I vnderstonde</L>
<L>It was founden in his ri&yogh;th honde,</L>
<L N="816">writen wi&thorn;outen faile.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L>&para; On palme sonenday, after messe,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirche amonge &thorn;e presse,</L>
<L N="819">A voice com, I &yogh;ou rede,</L>
<L>ffrom heuene adoune, wel shille &amp; clere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seide to hem in &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="822">where-of many gonne drede,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>And seide, '&yogh;ee &thorn;at trauailed be</L>
<L>In hunger &amp; &thorn;urst for loue of me,</L>
<L N="825">Come&thorn;! I shal &yogh;ou fede,</L>
<L>In heuene, &thorn;at is so fair &amp; bri&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;are euere is day &amp; neuere ni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="828">And ioye wi&thorn;outen drede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e poeple &amp; &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at voice songen &thorn;e letanye</L>
<L N="831">wi&thorn; gode deuocioun;</L>
<L>And bisou&yogh;tten &thorn;e heuene kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde &yogh;iue hem tokenyng</L>
<L N="834">ffro heuene to er&thorn;e adoun,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e voice what it were</L>
<L>&thorn;at among hem com &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="837">wi&thorn; so mery soun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e voice com eft ano&thorn;er tyme,</L>
<L>And seide as I schal seie in Ryme;</L>
<L N="840">Herkne&thorn; &thorn;is resoun:
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L>&para; '&thorn;ere is a Man of dedes gode,</L>
<L>Spirituel, &amp; mylde of mode,</L>
<L N="843">Now in Rome Cite;</L>
<L>In penaunce he is &yogh;ou amonge,</L>
<L>Certeynly &yogh;ee ne shullen nou&yogh;th longe</L>
<L N="846">here in er&thorn;e hym see;</L>
<L>A gode fridayes morowenyng</L>
<L>he shal wende to heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="849">&thorn;at sytte&thorn; in trinite.</L>
<L>Take&thorn; wi&thorn; hym &thorn;e ri&yogh;th pace</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chirche of seint Boneface</L>
<L N="852">wi&thorn; grete solempnite.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;ai sou&yogh;tten hym &amp; nou&yogh;th ne founde,</L>
<L>And hadden many sorou&yogh;ful stounde,</L>
<L N="855">Til &thorn;e gode fryday;</L>
<L>wi&thorn; gret deuocioun among,</L>
<L>Of bedes &amp; of chirche song,<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="858">To god &thorn;ai maden her pray;
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>&thorn;ai praiden hym for his pyte,</L>
<L>And for his mychel humilite,</L>
<L N="861">&thorn;at he hem sent to say</L>
<L>where was &thorn;e Man &thorn;e Aungel of tolde</L>
<L>Twyes er &thorn;an wi&thorn; wordes bolde,</L>
<L N="864">&thorn;at in swiche payne lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e &thorn;rid tyme com &thorn;e voice</L>
<L>ffro hym &thorn;at was don on croice</L>
<L N="867">wi&thorn; gret solempne li&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And seide, 'wende&thorn; wi&thorn;oute soioure</L>
<L>To Eufeniens &thorn;e Cenatoure,</L>
<L N="870">ffor &thorn;ere he lij&thorn; vche ni&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e good ha&thorn; ben his lijf;</L>
<L>His werkes shullen be made rijf;</L>
<L N="873">His soule is fair &amp; bri&yogh;th.'</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk tyme, as I &yogh;ou seie,</L>
<L>His gost went &thorn;e ri&yogh;th weie</L>
<L N="876">ffro &thorn;e body to god almi&yogh;th.
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e holy pope Innocent</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Emperoures swi&thorn;e went,</L>
<L N="879">Sire Eufeniens to calle,</L>
<L>And chalenged hym in &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>Eufeniens &amp; his wijf yfere,</L>
<L N="882">Ri&yogh;th amonge hem alle;</L>
<L>'In &thorn;ine house is, &thorn;at is so meke,</L>
<L>Goddes man &thorn;at we seke;</L>
<L N="885">Hou may &thorn;is cas bifalle?</L>
<L>we haue ysou&yogh;th hym fer &amp; wyde,</L>
<L>Hou darstou goddes sergeaunt hyde</L>
<L N="888">In boure oi&thorn;er in halle?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens ansuered sone,</L>
<L>As he au&yogh;tte forto done,</L>
<L N="891">To &thorn;e pope Innocent,</L>
<L>And seide, &thorn;ei&yogh; he shulde deye,</L>
<L>Of swiche a Man cou&thorn;e he nou&yogh;th seye,</L>
<L>By god omnipotent<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. omnipototent]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>'ffor swiche a Man &yogh;if I knewe,</L>
<L>ffayn I wolde hym to &yogh;ou shewe</L>
<L N="897">Treuly wi&thorn; god entent.'</L>
<L>&thorn;an seiden &thorn;e Cardinales twelue,</L>
<L>'God &yogh;eue &thorn;at it were &thorn;i-selue</L>
<L N="900">Byfore vs in present.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In &thorn;at tyme tweie emperoures</L>
<L>Of Rome kepten &thorn;e honoures</L>
<L N="903">wi&thorn; her cristen menee;</L>
<L>&thorn;at on hete Archadius,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;ere Honorius;</L>
<L N="906">&thorn;ai weren hende &amp; fre.
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>wi&thorn; Eufeniens &thorn;ai wenten ri&yogh;th</L>
<L>fforto fecchen goddes kni&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="909">&thorn;at was so good of fe.</L>
<L>Ac eufeniens was swi&thorn;e li&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And went bifore his hous to di&yogh;th</L>
<L N="912">wi&thorn; gret solempnite</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eufeniens, whan he hom cam,</L>
<L>Al his meignee he vndernam,</L>
<L N="915">&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ai euere ysowe</L>
<L>Any Man &thorn;at so holy were</L>
<L>As &thorn;e Aungel tolde of ere,</L>
<L N="918">Of his meignee to knowe.</L>
<L>Alexius wardeyn com &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And seide, 'sir, it is &yogh;oure bede|man,</L>
<L N="921">&thorn;at lij&thorn; ded by &thorn;e wowe;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast so longe yfed,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; mete &amp; drynk, cloo&thorn; &amp;. bed,</L>
<L N="924">He bare hym euer lowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'I trowe wel it may so be,</L>
<L>whom so &yogh;ee seche, &thorn;at it is he,</L>
<L N="927">ffor he was good of lijf;</L>
<L>His bedes he bad as a frere,</L>
<L>Ne wolde he nou&yogh;th, while he was here,</L>
<L N="930">Louen fi&yogh;th ne strijf;</L>
<L>A book in his honde he halt</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fast, &amp; narewe yfalt,</L>
<L N="933">who &thorn;at it cou&thorn;e descryue;</L>
<L>I ne woot what he &thorn;ereinne wrou&yogh;th;</L>
<L>&thorn;e parchemyn I hym bou&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="936">Gon fourty dayes &amp; fyue.'
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;oo &thorn;at &thorn;is herden &thorn;e Emperoures</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere lordes of honoures,</L>
<L N="939">&thorn;ai &thorn;ankeden god almi&yogh;th.</L>
<L>He led hem &thorn;ere lay &thorn;at body,</L>
<L>Clene &amp; fair, &amp; sumdel rody,</L>
<L N="942">fface feir &amp; bri&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&thorn;e on Emperoure his honde vp took,</L>
<L>And wolde haue taken out &thorn;e book</L>
<L N="945">&thorn;at was fair of si&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Alexius &thorn;e book helde &thorn;oo;</L>
<L>&thorn;an was &thorn;e Emperour swi&thorn;e woo,</L>
<L N="948">And in his herte afli&yogh;th.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(80)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Emperour &thorn;oo speke bigan,</L>
<L>And seide vnto &thorn;e body &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="951">&thorn;ere it lay in &thorn;e herne;</L>
<L>'&thorn;ou&yogh; we ben Men of synful lijf,</L>
<L>Emperours we ben wi&thorn;outen strijf,</L>
<L N="954">Rome forto gouerne;</L>
<L>we defenden holy chirche</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins hem &thorn;at wolden wirche</L>
<L N="957">Dedes stoute &amp; sterne;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore delyuer vs &thorn;i book,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e poeple &thorn;ere-on mowe look,</L>
<L N="960">wisdom forto lerne.'
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(81)</HEAD>
<L>&para; whan &thorn;ai hadden so yseide,</L>
<L>Alexius, &thorn;ere he was yleide,</L>
<L N="963">Opened vp his honde;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pope wolde he nou&yogh;th forsake,</L>
<L>Bot lete hym &thorn;oo &thorn;e book vptake,</L>
<L N="966">To rede &thorn;at he fonde.</L>
<L>&thorn;oo &thorn;apostoile had his book,<MILESTONE N="26a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His chaunceler he it bitook</L>
<L N="969">To rede, I vnderstonde;</L>
<L>Othoo was his name,</L>
<L>A Man yholde of gode fame</L>
<L N="972">Ouer al Rome londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(82)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;e book he red wi&thorn; gode wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk herkned &amp; helde hem stille</L>
<L N="975">wi&thorn;outen any boost</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e book was red &amp; seide.</L>
<L>Alexius was bifore hem leide,</L>
<L N="978">ffulfild of &thorn;e holy gost.</L>
<L>&thorn;e chaunceler wel loude grad</L>
<L>whan he &thorn;e book of Alexius rad</L>
<L N="981">Among &thorn;e cristen ost;</L>
<L>hou he fro frendes gan wende,</L>
<L>And hou his fader fer &amp; hende</L>
<L N="984">Sou&yogh;th hym by euery cost;
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(83)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And hou he was to &thorn;e Emperoure</L>
<L>ysent, to be Man of valoure</L>
<L N="987">And lernen chiualrie,</L>
<L>Of huntyng, &amp; of Ryuere,</L>
<L>Of chesse pleieyng &amp; of tablere:</L>
<L N="990">Al nas wor&thorn; a flye;</L>
<L>Leuer hym was to conne good,</L>
<L>And seruen god wi&thorn; mylde mood,</L>
<L N="993">and his moder Marie:</L>
<L>And hou he &yogh;ede seuentene &yogh;er</L>
<L>In pilerinage fer &amp; ner</L>
<L N="996">wi&thorn; mychel maladye;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(84)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And o&thorn;er &yogh;eres seuentene</L>
<L>wi&thorn; his fader he had ybene,</L>
<L N="999">his bedeman by &thorn;e wowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at fader ne moder ne his wijf</L>
<L>wisten of his holy lijf,</L>
<L N="1002">Ne &thorn;at he was hire owe;</L>
<L>And hou his fader sergeauntz alle,</L>
<L>veyn glorie gonne hym calle,</L>
<L N="1005">And gorre on hym gonne &thorn;rowe;</L>
<L>And hou he &thorn;e book ywriten hadde:</L>
<L>Of al his lijf, &thorn;ere he it radde</L>
<L N="1008">To &thorn;e poeple hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(85)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;oo Eufeniens &thorn;ise wordes herd,</L>
<L>Of his son hou it ferd,</L>
<L N="1011">Gret was his sorou&yogh;eyng;</L>
<L>His face he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. his]</NOTE> rent, &amp; his her.</L>
<L>Men sorou&yogh;ed for hym fer &amp; ner,</L>
<L N="1014">He fel in swowenyng.</L>
<L>On his owen son &thorn;at was,</L>
<L>His cry was euere, 'allas! allas!</L>
<L N="1017">de&thorn;! why nyltou me stynge?</L>
<L>Allas! sorou&yogh;! what is &thorn;i red?</L>
<L>&thorn;ou hast me brou&yogh;th vnto my ded;</L>
<L N="1020">Myne herte wil to-sprynge.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(86)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Now I may no ioye haue;</L>
<L>No confort ne may me saue;</L>
<L N="1023">My blis is al forlorne!</L>
<L>ffor my son &thorn;at lij&thorn; here ded,</L>
<L>In elde he shulde haue ben my red.</L>
<L N="1026">Allas! &thorn;at I was borne!</L>
<L>O son, whi woldestou suffren smert,</L>
<L>And dye wi&thorn; me here in pouert,</L>
<L N="1029">A begger as &thorn;ou worne?</L>
<L>To &thorn;i comyng was al my speire,</L>
<L>To haue ymade of &thorn;ee myne eire,</L>
<L N="1032">Of londe, Castel &amp; corne.'
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(87)</HEAD>
<L>&para; His moder herd &thorn;at tydynge;</L>
<L>ffor hir son she gan flynge</L>
<L N="1035">In Rage as a lyonesse;</L>
<L>Sorou&yogh;-fullich her pleynt she made;</L>
<L>Noman mi&yogh;th hire herte glade,</L>
<L N="1038">Of al &thorn;e grete presse.</L>
<L>His fader had ylore &thorn;e speche;</L>
<L>To his moder was no leche</L>
<L N="1041">&thorn;at mi&yogh;th her cry acesse.</L>
<L>Letted she nou&yogh;th for al &thorn;e &thorn;rong,</L>
<L>&thorn;at she ne ran &thorn;e poeple among,</L>
<L N="1044">Hire son to clyppe &amp; kysse.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(88)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "O son, &thorn;at soke of myne pappes,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou hast ysent me sory happes,</L>
<L N="1047">&thorn;us sone art went me fro.</L>
<L>I wende haue yhad of &thorn;ee solas;</L>
<L>Myne hope is tynt, allas! allas!</L>
<L N="1050">And wel&thorn;e is went to woo.</L>
<L>Son, &thorn;ou doest vs stronge tourment!</L>
<L>Oure ioye is al away went!</L>
<L N="1053">ffor sorou&yogh; we shullen vs sle;</L>
<L>ffor often &thorn;ou sei&yogh; &thorn;i fader &amp; me</L>
<L>Erlich &amp; late wepe for &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="1056">And ek &thorn;i wijf also.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(89)</HEAD>
<L>&para; '&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;ee shulden haue serued trewe,</L>
<L>ffele tymes on &thorn;ee &thorn;ai &thorn;rewe</L>
<L N="1059">ffil&thorn;e &amp; foule vryne,</L>
<L>And beten &thorn;ee ofte swi&thorn;e sore;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou suffredest euermore,</L>
<L N="1062">And took it nou&yogh;th to pyne.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>Why woldestou cast &thorn;ee in care,</L>
<L>Of hem to suffre swiche bysmare,</L>
<L N="1065">&thorn;at weren &thorn;ine owen hyne?</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ise seuentene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Ne woldestou noman tellen here</L>
<L N="1068">&thorn;ou come of body myne."
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(90)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor&thorn; com &thorn;oo his trewe wijf</L>
<L>wi&thorn; sorou&yogh;, &amp; care &amp; drery lijf,</L>
<L N="1071">And nei&yogh; for doel ded.</L>
<L>'Allas! she seide, my ioye cast,</L>
<L>Kare &amp; sorou&yogh; ben in me fast,</L>
<L N="1074">As widewe wi&thorn;oute red.</L>
<L>Al my wel&thorn;e is fro me went,</L>
<L>No womman is in swiche tourment</L>
<L N="1077">In leng&thorn;e ne in brede.<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;is werlde, &amp; it myne were,</L>
<L>I wolde &yogh;iue it fer and nere,</L>
<L N="1080">To seen his fairehede.
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(91)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'It is no wonder of my doloure;</L>
<L>Yshadewed is al my myroure<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. myrou&thorn;e]</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="1083">And lorne is my bri&yogh;thnesse;</L>
<L>Myne herte may nou&yogh;th lange dure.</L>
<L>Cursed wor&thorn;e &thorn;ou, dame auenture,</L>
<L>&thorn;at doost me destresse!</L>
<L>After fair weder falle&thorn; reyn,</L>
<L>After wynnyng wep ageyn,</L>
<L N="1089">And care is after kysse,</L>
<L>Erly to day by &thorn;e morowe,</L>
<L>I ne wist of care ne of sorowe:</L>
<L N="1092">To bale is tourned my blisse.'
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(92)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;apostoile &amp; &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>&thorn;emperoures &amp; her chiualerie,</L>
<L N="1095">Token &thorn;at confessoure,</L>
<L>And leiden on a bere ri&yogh;th;</L>
<L>ffair &amp; wel hij habbe&thorn; hym di&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="1098">wi&thorn; menske &amp; honoure;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chirche of seint Bonefas,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; &thorn;e corps &thorn;ai token &thorn;e pas</L>
<L N="1101">wi&thorn;outen any soioure;</L>
<L>&thorn;e belles alle a&yogh;ein hem rungen,</L>
<L>Preostes &amp; clerkes merily sungen</L>
<L N="1104">wi&thorn; &thorn;at swete floure.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(93)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Noman may telle wi&thorn; tunge</L>
<L>&thorn;e miracles &thorn;at of hym sprunge</L>
<L N="1107">As &thorn;ai &thorn;at body bere;</L>
<L>Deef &amp; doumbe, halte &amp; blynde,</L>
<L>Alle mi&yogh;tten bote fynde,</L>
<L N="1110">In maladie &thorn;at were;</L>
<L>Men &thorn;at weren in palesye,</L>
<L>Lunatik, oi&thorn;er in frenesie,</L>
<L N="1113">Bote hadden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Swiche presse was &thorn;e poeple among,</L>
<L>&thorn;emperoures mi&yogh;tten nou&yogh;th for &thorn;rong</L>
<L N="1116">Beren for&thorn; &thorn;e bere.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(94)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;ai bi&thorn;ou&yogh;tten hem in &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>&thorn;at folk was ful of Coueitise,</L>
<L N="1119">And tresore onon of sende,</L>
<L>And casten aboute siluer &amp; golde,</L>
<L>Take it vp who &thorn;at wolde,</L>
<L N="1122">Largely to spende.</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;th for &thorn;an in euery strete</L>
<L>&thorn;e presse was swi&thorn;e grete,</L>
<L N="1125">&thorn;ai mi&yogh;tten hem nou&yogh;th defende;</L>
<L>&thorn;ai leten lygge &thorn;at tresoure,</L>
<L>And foloweden &thorn;at confessoure</L>
<L N="1128">&thorn;at day to &thorn;e ende.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(95)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ri&yogh;th at seint Bonefas chirche,</L>
<L>To seint Alexi &thorn;ai gonne wirche</L>
<L N="1131">A riche monument:</L>
<L>Seuene dayes his frendes duelleden &thorn;ere</L>
<L>ffor his body &thorn;at lay on bere,</L>
<L N="1134">And si&thorn;ens hom &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>His fader / his moder / &amp; his wijf,</L>
<L>Lyueden after in holy lijf</L>
<L N="1137">Trewely wi&thorn; gode entent.</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ai dyeden alle &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai wenten wi&thorn; solempnite</L>
<L N="1140">To god omnipotent.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(96)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &thorn;us ende &amp; orde &yogh;ee han yherd,</L>
<L>Of seint Alexi hou it ferd,</L>
<L N="1143">wi&thorn;outen any lesyng.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e worschip of god in glorie,</L>
<L>Out of latyn is drawen &thorn;is storie,</L>
<L N="1146">&thorn;orou&yogh; mi&yogh;th of heuene kyng.</L>
<L>alle &thorn;at habben yherd his vye,
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>God brynge hem to &thorn;e compaignye</L>
<L N="1149">&thorn;ere Aungels ben wonyynge;</L>
<L>And sende vs, lorde, &thorn;i mylde mood;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;orou&yogh; &thorn;ee sprynge&thorn; al good</L>
<L N="1152">wi&thorn;outen any endynge.</L>
<TRAILER>Amen, Amen, Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20">
<HEAD>[<I>MS. Cotton, Titus, A xxvi, lf</I> 145.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>THE LYFE OF ST. ALEXES.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[A]lle &thorn;at wolle a whyle here dwell,</L>
<L>herkynnythe, and I woll yowe tell</L>
<L>A tale Sone of grete pyte:</L>
<L N="4">Att rome, by-ffell in &thorn;at Cyte,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>There somtyme wonnyd a man,</L>
<L>hys name was callyd eufemyan;</L>
<L>he was ryche in all thyng,</L>
<L N="8">And euery day seruyd as a kyng;</L>
<L>he had I-now&yogh;e of worlldys well,</L>
<L>And seruantes with hym many and fele,</L>
<L>Thre thowesant to hym were atend|aund,</L>
<L>That weryd gold on here pendaunt.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
<L N="13">In hys owne hous euery daye,</L>
<L>A custyume was that I schall saye:</L>
<L>there boredes that were fayre spred,</L>
<L N="16">There pormen schulde be fede;</L>
<L>Of all pormen of ylk a gate,</L>
<L>there was none &thorn;at werned &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> yate.</L>
<L>A wyfe he had, she hyght a gales,</L>
<L N="20">An holey woman withowten lees;</L>
<L>She louyd god with all her myght,</L>
<L>And seruyd hym bothe daye and nyght;</L>
<L>She was of gode wyll, and hart Free</L>
<L N="24">To all &thorn;e dedes of charite.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>there she wollde clothe and fede,</L>
<L>and helpe men at here nede.</L>
<L>By twene theym chyllde had &thorn;ey none,</L>
<L N="28">there fore they made mykell mon.</L>
<L>theye were allwaye blythe and hende,</L>
<L>In hope that god shollde hem sende</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio">Some maydyn chyllde, or some man,</L>
<L>That theyre herytages myght hane;</L>
<L N="33">So long theye prayed with good entent,</L>
<L>that a man chyllde god hem sent;
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>whan they wyst &thorn;at hit was so,</L>
<L N="36">Chanse theye leuyd bothe twoo,</L>
<L>Sythyn &thorn;ey wollde for no need</L>
<L>Com to gedur in Flesschely ded.</L>
<L>Whan thys man chyllde was borne,</L>
<L>Fayne were here frendys therforne;</L>
<L N="41">Theye bare the chylde to chirche A none,</L>
<L>And crystenyd hyt in the Font stone.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>there theye callyd &thorn;e chylde Alexe;</L>
<L>Sone hit throofe, and wele hit wex.</L>
<L>Whan hit was vij yere olde and more,</L>
<L N="46">hys freendys sett hym wnto lore;</L>
<L>he was sone Full goode of wytt,</L>
<L>And wnderstode the holy wryte;</L>
<L N="49">he loued god in all his thought,</L>
<L>And of thys worllde gaffe he nought;</L>
<L>he sawe thys worllde was butt gylle,</L>
<L N="52">for hit showld laste but a whyle;
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>neuerthe les whan he was elde,</L>
<L>lone and felde For to wellde,</L>
<L N="55">hys fader puruyde hym a wyffe,</L>
<L>Wit whome he soulde led hys lyffe;</L>
<L>A mayden there was fayre and Fre,</L>
<L>Com of &thorn;e rycheste of that cette.<MILESTONE N="146a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="59">In holy chyrche vppon a daye</L>
<L>They were spousyde in goddys laue;</L>
<L>Atte here spousyng I wott there stode</L>
<L>Beshoppys felle and prestes goode;</L>
<L>Sythen theye made a mangery</L>
<L N="64">With all the beste of here aleye;
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>All that comyn thyder &thorn;at daye</L>
<L>theye were seruyd welle to paye,</L>
<L>Com &thorn;ey erley, com the late,</L>
<L N="68">theye wer neuer wernyd &thorn;e yate;</L>
<L>there was nowder man nor knaue,</L>
<L>Byt mete and drynke he myght haue.</L>
<L>Euery man had there plente</L>
<L N="72">Of claret wyne and pymente;</L>
<L>There was many a riche wyne,</L>
<L>In sylluer and in golde fyne;</L>
<L>Many a coppe and many a pece,</L>
<L>with wyne wernage &amp; eke of grece;
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>And many A noder ryche vessell</L>
<L>with wyne of gascoyne and of rochell.</L>
<L>whan euyne com &thorn;at elke a gest</L>
<L N="80">was gone to bed to take hys rest,</L>
<L>Eufemyan callyd hys sone Anone,</L>
<L>And bad hym &thorn;at he shoulde gone</L>
<L>In to hys chaumbur to hys fere,</L>
<L N="84">And cowmfort her in hys manere.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>Alex was to hym obedyent,<MILESTONE N="146b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and ded his faders comawndement;</L>
<L>In to a chaumbur he com full ryght,</L>
<L>And redy there he founde hys bryght,</L>
<L>And toke here in his armys twoo,</L>
<L>And downe they layde bothe twoo;</L>
<L>'dame,' he sayde, 'nou it ys soo,</L>
<L N="92">Of Flessche ar wee allso.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>Noue may we be gladde of &thorn;is lyffe,</L>
<L>For thowe art bothe moder and wyffe;</L>
<L N="95">For allwaye rede &thorn;at hit so be,</L>
<L>For nowe muste me wende frome the.</L>
<L>Whylys I was yong I made a vowe,</L>
<L>That I wyll Fullfell hyt nowe,</L>
<L>For to wende a pylgremage,</L>
<L N="100">Noue woll I doo &thorn;at vyage,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt lewe here at home,</L>
<L>agayne as goddys wyll I come.'</L>
<L>he yaffe her a gyrdell and a ryng,</L>
<L>all for a tokyng at &thorn;eyre departyng;</L>
<L>And Forthe he went that elke nyght.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e sse he come full ryght;</L>
<L>The shipe was redy, and ouer went,</L>
<L N="108">wynde att wyll god hym sent.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>whan he come Into a Fer contre,</L>
<L N="110">he come into a ryche cytte,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
<L><MILESTONE N="147a" UNIT="folio">Knowyn he wollde in no wyse be</L>
<L N="112">Of no man &thorn;at shoullde hym see.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>In that cyte was an Image,</L>
<L N="114">That was lyke goddes wysage,</L>
<L>Many a pylgryme had hit sought,</L>
<L>For hit was neuer with honde wrought.</L>
<L>Alex herd ther of than t[e]lle,</L>
<L>Than thought he there to duell.</L>
<L>A none he yaffe Frome hym awaye</L>
<L N="120">to powre men all hys monaye;</L>
<L>And bought hym pore man ys wede,
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>That none of theyme shoullde thak hede,</L>
<L>And axed his met eorly and late,</L>
<L>With poremen att the mynster yate.</L>
<L>All the mete &thorn;at he myght gete,</L>
<L N="126">Bot euery day a melys mete</L>
<L>To pore men gaffe A noone ryght,</L>
<L>he lefft hym sylffe none ouer nyght.</L>
<L N="129">there dwellyd he xvij yere,</L>
<L>And lede his lyffe in thys manere;
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>his Fader and hys modyr bothe,</L>
<L>Than he was to theyme Fvll lothe;</L>
<L>his fadyr made gret dole and sorowe,</L>
<L N="134">Bothe on euen and on morowe.</L>
<L>'Alas!' he sayde, and wrong his honde,</L>
<L>'Why is my sonne went owte of lond?</L>
<L>I wende haue hade of hym a knyght,</L>
<L>with me to stonde In all my ryght;</L>
<L>nowe ys he wente &thorn;at was my blysse,
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>I west hym neuer do man a mys.</L>
<L>Nowe haue I none of my lynage<MILESTONE N="147a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That maye welde myn herytage.'</L>
<L N="143">Than sayde his moder, and wepte full sore,</L>
<L>'Noue shall I see my sonne no more;</L>
<L>I was full glade whan he was borne,</L>
<L N="146">nowe ys all my Ioye forlorne.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>I haue hade robbys maney and fayre,</L>
<L>Nowe woll I next me were the ayre,</L>
<L>Tyll I maye some tydynges here</L>
<L N="150">of my sone that was so dere.'</L>
<L>than spake his wyffe, and wepte among.</L>
<L>'My leffe,' she sayde, 'was done wrong,
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>he toke me in my fadyrs bowre,</L>
<L N="154">And brought me hydder with grete honouer.</L>
<L>And he has me nowe for-sakyng,</L>
<L N="156">To Iesu cryst I wyll me takyne;
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>Sorowe and morenyng may I well make,</L>
<L>As the turtell dothe withowten his make.</L>
<L>Ioyefull schall I neuer bee,</L>
<L N="160">Tyll I maye my leman see.'</L>
<L>hys Fader send bothe fer and vyde</L>
<L>Messengers on euery syde,</L>
<L>To seke his sonne where he was went,</L>
<L>Bothe Fer and nere where he was went.</L>
<L N="165">Sythen affter yt befell soo,</L>
<L>Of messengeres there com too,</L>
<L>Ryght to the Ryche Cete,<MILESTONE N="148a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="168">There alex lywyd In pourte.</L>
<L>As they com In to a strete,</L>
<L>Alex com and shoulde hym mete;</L>
<L>Sone knewe he &thorn;eyme fwll welle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey knewe hym neuer a dele.</L>
<L>lowde he spake vnder hys hoode,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>'For goddes lowe do me som goode;'</L>
<L>Theye gaffe hym of theyre money,</L>
<L>For goddes lowe there in the waye.</L>
<L N="177">whan Alex sawe &thorn;eye knwe hym nought,</L>
<L>he thanked god in all hys thought.</L>
<L>'lorde,' he sayde, 'I thank the</L>
<L>the grace &thorn;at thowe hast sent me;</L>
<L>Myne owne men that shoullde bee,</L>
<L>hate gewyn me of theyre cheryte.'</L>
<L>Alex dwellyd styll there</L>
<L N="184">Fully xlij yere and more.</L>
<L>To chyrche he went euery daye,</L>
<L>his goode bedeyes there for to saye;</L>
<L>In to that chyrche, with owtyn fayle,</L>
<L>Was an Images of fayre entayele,</L>
<L N="189">Of owre lady &thorn;at is so Free,</L>
<L>With here sonne wppon here knee;
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>That Images spake, &thorn;at was so bryght,</L>
<L N="192">to the sexteyene vppon a nyght.</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="148b" UNIT="folio">'Take,' sche sayde, 'my seruante swythe,</L>
<L>he hathe me seruyd all hys lyeffe;</L>
<L>Full offte he wolle to me lowthe,</L>
<L>hit is no ryght &thorn;at he is withowte.'</L>
<L>'lady,' he sayde, 'I knowe hym nought,
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
<L N="198">Nor I wott neuer where he schull be sought.'</L>
<L>She sayde, 'he sitte&thorn;e eorly and late</L>
<L>Withowtyn att the mynster yate.'</L>
<L>Anon he owte of his slepe brayde,</L>
<L>And thought what &thorn;e Image sayde.</L>
<L N="203">And forthe went the sextayne,</L>
<L>And fownde alexknelyng In &thorn;e Rayne.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
<L>Fayne was he that he hym founde,</L>
<L>A-non he toke hym vpe be &thorn;e hande.</L>
<L>'A-ryse,' he sayde, 'my leve and dere,</L>
<L>hit ys no ryght &thorn;at thowe sitt here.</L>
<L>Com,' he sayde, 'my lady bade,</L>
<L>And there of mayst &thorn;ou be glade.'</L>
<L N="211">All that hard this tydynges,</L>
<L>Theye worshippyd Iesu, hewyn kyng.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>Whan Alex sawe hit schulde be ryffe,</L>
<L N="214">hys penance and hys holy lyffe,</L>
<L>here kepte he to haue mede,</L>
<L>In this worllde for his goode deede;</L>
<L>Bytt stylly he yeede a waye<MILESTONE N="149a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="218">In to a-nodr dyuers contre.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e se he cam in &thorn;at entente,</L>
<L>In to spreusse he wollde haue wente;
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
<L N="221">byt there com A storme of wynde &amp; rayne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. raynde]</NOTE></L>
<L>And droffe &thorn;e shipe home a gayne,</L>
<L>That In a lytyll stonde they come</L>
<L N="224">Ryght to &thorn;e cyte of rome.</L>
<L>Alex sayde &thorn;an with sympyll cher,</L>
<L>'Alas!' he sayde, 'wat do we here?
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>Myght hitt haue bene affter me,</L>
<L>here wollde I nought haue I-bee;</L>
<L>Butt gode wollde hit myght befall</L>
<L N="230">I myght be in my fadris haull,</L>
<L>So that I myght vnknowen be</L>
<L>of hym and of his meyny.'
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>Forthe he vent vpe be a strete,</L>
<L N="234">many a man there gan mete;</L>
<L>But there was no man &thorn;at hym knwe,</L>
<L>So was he lene and blake of hewe.</L>
<L>There come his fader hyme agayne,
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
<L N="238">With mayny a knyght and many a swane,</L>
<L>Than com with hym on ylke a syde;</L>
<L>Alex stode stelle theyme to a-byde.</L>
<L>'Syr,' he sayde, 'for goddes sake</L>
<L>Wyll yee thys porman In thake?
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>for his lowe &thorn;at dyed on Roode,<MILESTONE N="149b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gywe me clethe and manys foode;</L>
<L>and for his lowe &thorn;at went for the,</L>
<L>God sende &thorn;e grace hym for to see.'</L>
<L N="247">This ryche man with stode &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And callyd one of his owne men,
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>And gaffe hym mete an dr[i]nk bothe,</L>
<L>And with pore men hym to clothe.</L>
<L>There dwellyd alex wythem alle,</L>
<L>Sewentene yere in his Faders hall;</L>
<L>There was no man, hye ne llawe,</L>
<L>yongne owlde, &thorn;at hym myght knowe;
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
<L N="255">his owne men for rebaundrye</L>
<L>dyd hym manye a welonye.</L>
<L>They hylde water wppon hys hede,
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>And gaff hym &thorn;at was in the dyche levyd;</L>
<L N="259">But euer he hylde hym stylle,</L>
<L>And Alle he suffyrde with goode wyll.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>A-gayne xvij wyntersende,</L>
<L>Whane he schowlde owte of &thorn;is worllde wend,
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>he prayd hym &thorn;at brout hys mete,</L>
<L>Prev[i]ly he shoullde hym gete</L>
<L N="265">A lytyll ynke and perchemyne,</L>
<L>And all hys lyffe he wrote there In.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>whan hit was wretyn, he hit Follde,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="150a" UNIT="folio">And In his hand he gan hit hollde.</L>
<L>And a none he dyed, I wys,</L>
<L N="270">And dyght his sowlle to hewyn blys.</L>
<L>That ylke a daye in tym of masse,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>whan all fowlke att chirche was,</L>
<L>A woyce cam frome &thorn;e trinite</L>
<L N="274">To the bysshope of that cyte.</L>
<L>'Com to me,' he sayde, '&thorn;at woll swynke,</L>
<L>And I schall gywe yowe met and drynke;
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
<L N="277">'Sek ye vpe my serwaunte, where &thorn;at he be,</L>
<L>That he maye praye for this cete.'</L>
<L>ollde and yonge, lesse and more,</L>
<L N="280">All hard this &thorn;at were there:</L>
<L>For hit was no man, lewde ne leryd,</L>
<L>But of this woyce he nas a-Feryd.
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>Goddes seruaunte anon was sought,</L>
<L N="284">but who hit was &thorn;ey knowe hym nought;</L>
<L>That voyce sayde on that ylke a daye,</L>
<L>And tolde hym redyly where he laye;</L>
<L N="287">'In eufamyans hous,' he sayde, 'is he,</L>
<L>That hathe my Serwaunt long I-be.'
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
<L N="289">the besshope And &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>went in to euffamyans hous;</L>
<L>They axyd hym of syche a man;</L>
<L>he sayde he knwe there of noone.</L>
<L N="293">on of his seruaunttes was thane thore,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>That stode and lokeyd Alex by|fore.</L>
<L>'Syr,' he sayde, 'I trowe hit be</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio">That poreman &thorn;at yee toke to me,</L>
<L N="297">That long has bene in your hall,</L>
<L>he is an holy man with all.'
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>This ryche man went to hym a noone,</L>
<L>And founde Alex ded as ony stone,</L>
<L N="301">But his vysage was allso bryght</L>
<L>As the sonne on &thorn;e daye lyght.</L>
<L>Than trowyd well eufemyan</L>
<L>That he was an holey man;</L>
<L>he callyd &thorn;e bysshopes &amp; &thorn;e Empe|rowres</L>
<L N="306">To se &thorn;at cors so presyowse.</L>
<L>In theye com a non ryght,</L>
<L>And saue the body &thorn;at was so bryght;</L>
<L N="309">downe on knes theye fell thow,</L>
<L>And oder many that were &thorn;ere moo,</L>
<L>And thankyd god In trinite,</L>
<L>That theye myght his seruaunte see.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>The bysshope, as he stode hym nye,</L>
<L N="314">A perchement leffe in his honde he see,</L>
<L>But he hyllde his hand so faste,</L>
<L>That owte he myght hit natt wrast.</L>
<L N="317">'Sonne,' sayde &thorn;e bysshope, 'I praye &thorn;ee</L>
<L>that in thye honde &thorn;oue lett me see;</L>
<L>Synfulle all thou&yogh;e hit bee,</L>
<L N="320">I haue powre and dyngnytee</L>
<L>For to lousse and for to bynde</L>
<L>Thym &thorn;at I in syn Fynde.<MILESTONE N="151a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>There Fore, sone, let me wetten</L>
<L N="324">what ys in thy bocke wrytyn.'
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>The beshope toke &thorn;e boke so hynde,</L>
<L>That Alex hys hond on bynde;
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>the beshope &thorn;at Rolle red A non,</L>
<L N="328">That &thorn;ey yt harde euerychone.</L>
<L>There was there in redly tolde</L>
<L>Alle hys lyfe, yong and olde.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>Whan hys Fader harde of thys,</L>
<L N="332">That he was hys sone I wys,</L>
<L>'lorde,' he sayde, 'howe maye &thorn;ys bee?</L>
<L>ys thys my sone &thorn;at I here scee?</L>
<L>Sewentene yere wyt All,</L>
<L N="336">I had fynde hym in myn halle;</L>
<L>I myght nat wyt for none Asaye,</L>
<L>What he was, nyght nor daye.</L>
<L>"leffe sone," he sayde, "why ded &thorn;ou soo?</L>
<L>Thowe saw I was For &thorn;e Full woo;</L>
<L N="341">for &thorn;owe were not At my wylle,
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>And ewer more &thorn;ou helde &thorn;e styll;</L>
<L>Thyne own saruantes &thorn;at sholde be,</L>
<L N="344">myche harme ded &thorn;ey to &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>Theye kest water on thyn hede,<MILESTONE N="151b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And gafe &thorn;e &thorn;at was in the dyche leuyde,</L>
<L>And euer &thorn;ou bare &thorn;e meke and lawe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at no man should &thorn;e there cnawe.</L>
<L>In heuyn ther fore &thorn;ou hast mede:</L>
<L N="350">Sonne, praye fore me, fore I haue nede."'
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>hys moder lyued in In longyng,</L>
<L>whan sche herde of thys tydyng,</L>
<L>She com Forthe with A raply rese,</L>
<L N="354">As A lyon lept oute of A lees;</L>
<L>She weppyd And cryde sore,</L>
<L>As thay don &thorn;at arne woo.</L>
<L>'let me,' she sayd, 'my sone see;</L>
<L N="358">I Fed hym on myn owne kee.'
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>whan she hym sawe, she Fylle downe,</L>
<L>All was A waye here Resonne.</L>
<L>whan she rose she stoode hym by,</L>
<L>She kyssyde hym, And sayd on hye,</L>
<L N="363">'Sonne,' she sayde, And wept Full sore,</L>
<L>'Nowe schall I speke with &thorn;e no more.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Thowe hast be sought in meny A londe,</L>
<L>With messengerys, And with sonde,
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>Bot there was no man myght &thorn;e see,</L>
<L N="368">And euer &thorn;ou sat be owre knee.</L>
<L>lewe sonne, &thorn;ou praye for mee,<MILESTONE N="152a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That I may &thorn;e in bleyss see.'
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>hys wyfe &thorn;at was In chamber stokyn,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ys tydynges harde sche spokyn;</L>
<L>She com forthe in A sempyll pace,</L>
<L N="374">Sory, I wott, welle &thorn;at che was;</L>
<L>She swonnyd at &thorn;e fryst syght,</L>
<L>That on here was blake, &thorn;at rest was wyght.</L>
<L>Than she sayd with mylde chere,</L>
<L>'Where hastowe be, my leman dere?</L>
<L>Full long I myght &thorn;e A-byde,
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
<L N="380">Fore thowe hast soughte pylgermages wyde.</L>
<L>Thowe hast beene frome long,</L>
<L>Forsothe I haue done &thorn;e no wrong;</L>
<L>Wyghe &thorn;e speke nowe I ne maye,</L>
<L>Nowe maye I weddowe be for Aye,</L>
<L>I maye be weddow And mayden dde,</L>
<L>And I haue done as ye me bade.</L>
<L>Thowe weddest me to be &thorn;y Free,</L>
<L N="388">O nyght togeder when we were,</L>
<L>Bot, good leuan, nowe praye for me</L>
<L>That we to geder in blese maye be.'
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>The folke come fast owte of &thorn;e cete,</L>
<L N="392">that ryche Relyke for to see.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>Sone in a A lytell stonde &thorn;er was</L>
<L>Bothe grete throng And prece.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>The emperoure, that stode &thorn;er &thorn;oo,</L>
<L N="396">Sawe &thorn;e folke presyd ssoo;</L>
<L>Sylvyr in &thorn;e strete &thorn;ey cast,</L>
<L>To lete the folke &thorn;at com so Fast,</L>
<L>Bot of sylver yaffe &thorn;ey no force,</L>
<L>Alle held hem Fast to se &thorn;at corce.</L>
<L N="401">At &thorn;e last with trawayle borne hyt was</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chyrche of seynt bonyfface.</L>
<L>whan yt was to &thorn;e chyrche I-brought,</L>
<L>A ryche tombe &thorn;ere was wrought,</L>
<L>Of marbyll And of ryche stonys,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Craffetyly, And for &thorn;e nonce,</L>
<L>of sylvyr And of golde coloure,</L>
<L>They layd in &thorn;ys Ryche tresowre.</L>
<L N="409">Sythen cam on to hys tombe</L>
<L>Blynde And lame, dethe And dome,</L>
<L>And other man many And felle:</L>
<L>Thorowe grace of god &thorn;ey hadden hell.</L>
<L>Be thys holy man men may ssee,</L>
<L>That god lowyght wele pouerte;</L>
<L>he for soke thys worlde all bedene,</L>
<L>And lowyd god, And yt ys sene
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
<L N="417">he for soke hys Fader, Moder, And wyffe,</L>
<L>And lyvyd A pore manys lyfe;</L>
<L>Nowe is he in Ioye &thorn;at last[et]he Aye.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>God bryng us &thorn;ere &thorn;at best maye.</L>
<L N="421">Praye wee All &thorn;at yt soo bee.</L>
<L>Amen, Amen, For cheryte.</L>
<TRAILER>explicit sante alex.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<DIV3 TYPE="manuscript"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20">
<HEAD>[<I>Vernon MS., leaf</I> 44.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sitte&thorn; stille with-outen strif,</L>
<L>And i wol tellen ou of a lyf</L>
<L N="3">Of an holy Mon;</L>
<L>Alix was his nome.</L>
<L>To seruen god &thorn;hu&yogh;te him no schome,</L>
<L N="6">&thorn;er-of neuer he ne blon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his fadur was a gret lording,</L>
<L>Of rome a kyngus euenyng,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="9">and hihte Eufemian.</L>
<L>Pore men to clo&thorn;e and fede,</L>
<L>In al rome, &thorn;at riche &thorn;eode,</L>
<L N="12">such nas &thorn;er nan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>eueri day were in his halle</L>
<L>I-leid &thorn;reo bordus, forte calle</L>
<L N="15">pore Men to fede.</L>
<L>Hem to serue he was wel glad;</L>
<L>he dude as iesu crist him bad;</L>
<L N="18">he hoped &thorn;erfore to haue mede.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whon he was serued bi and bi,</L>
<L>&thorn;enne was he redi</L>
<L N="21">to go to his mete;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e loue of Godes sone,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Men of Religione</L>
<L N="24">wolde he sitte and ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His wyf hi&yogh;te dame Agloes,</L>
<L>to sigge so&thorn; with-oute les,</L>
<L N="27">&thorn;at muche was to preyse.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>But heo dede &thorn;e same manere</L>
<L>as dede hir lord, as &yogh;e may here,</L>
<L N="30">was heo nout at ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Children bi-twene hem hedde &thorn;ei none,</L>
<L>&thorn;er-of to god &thorn;ei maden heor mone</L>
<L N="33">bo&thorn;e dai &amp; niht.</L>
<L>Iesu crist herde her bone,</L>
<L>&amp; sende hem a ful good sone,</L>
<L N="36">heor herte forte liht.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio">So sone was bore &thorn;at blisful child,</L>
<L>Alix bo&thorn;e meke and Mild,</L>
<L N="39">and of maners hende.</L>
<L>sone after wi&thorn; gret hast,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei Auouwede bo&thorn;e chast</L>
<L N="42">to heore lyues ende.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er-aftur was hit not longe,</L>
<L>Alix cou&thorn;e speke and gonge,</L>
<L N="45">and was i-set to lere;</L>
<L>sone he was a wel god clerk,</L>
<L>&amp; muche he loued godus werk</L>
<L N="48">forte speke &amp; here.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As time as he bi-gon to belde,</L>
<L>and was i-come to Monnes elde,</L>
<L N="51">him was chosen a wyf,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e Emperors bour,</L>
<L>a maiden god with gret honour,</L>
<L N="54">to wedden wi&thorn;-oute strif.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon heo weren weddet &thorn;e furste ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>in godus lawe as hit was ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="57">&amp; weren i-brou&yogh;t to house,</L>
<L>Mekeliche he gon hire teche</L>
<L>to drede god of sunne is leche,</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at is Maidenes spouse.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He preched hire with al his miht,</L>
<L>of sunne heo scholde haue no pli&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="63">but holden hir Maidenhed.</L>
<L>Of Iesu &thorn;at Maiden clene,</L>
<L>in whom was neuere wem i-sene,</L>
<L N="66">heo schulde han hire med.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne tok he his gold ryng,</L>
<L>and &yogh;af hit to &thorn;at Maide &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="69">and seide to hire &thorn;us:</L>
<L>'Tac &thorn;is Ryng and kep hit me,</L>
<L>til &thorn;at godes wille be,</L>
<L N="72">crist beo bi-twene vs.'
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon he hedde don as i ou sei,</L>
<L>he tok his leue &amp; went his wei</L>
<L N="75">from &thorn;at Maiden fre.</L>
<L>A parti god with him he tok,</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;at o&thorn;ur he forsok,</L>
<L N="78">and wende him to &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He fond schipes redi,</L>
<L>to on he wente priueli,</L>
<L N="81">ouer forte fare.</L>
<L>whon he was ouere on &thorn;e sond,</L>
<L>he was in an vnkou&thorn; lond,</L>
<L N="84">&thorn;er he con neuer are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He went him for&thorn; with godus wille,</L>
<L>a feir cite he com tille,</L>
<L N="87">&thorn;e nome i schal ou telle.</L>
<L>Edissa hette &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>godus seruaunt forte be,</L>
<L N="90">&thorn;erinne forte dwelle.
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e goodus &thorn;at he wi&thorn; him brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>of hem wolde he ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="93">he &yogh;af hem pore men.</L>
<L>His Robe he &yogh;af &thorn;er he sauh nede,</L>
<L>and clo&thorn;ed him-self in pore wede,</L>
<L N="96">for no mon scholde him ken.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He ede to A chirche hei,</L>
<L>&thorn;er pore men seeten in &thorn;e wei,</L>
<L N="99">Almus forte take.</L>
<L>AMongus hem he sat a-doun,</L>
<L>and asked wi&thorn; deuociun</L>
<L N="102">sum god for Godus sake.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at chirche was of vr ladi,</L>
<L>&thorn;er-Inne was a gret celli,</L>
<L N="105">an ymage of hire sone,</L>
<L>Maked of a wonder werk,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&thorn;ur lewed mon nor clerk</L>
<L N="108">ne mi&yogh;t wite hou hit was done;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor&thorn;i was &thorn;ider gret sekyng</L>
<L>of on and o&thorn;ur, old and &yogh;yng,</L>
<L N="111">of al &thorn;at Cuntre,
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>ffor&thorn;i &thorn;e pore &thorn;at &thorn;er ware,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e betere mi&yogh;te fare</L>
<L N="114">for heore Charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alix, of al &thorn;at mi&yogh;te he gete,</L>
<L>nedliche bote he moste ete,</L>
<L N="117">he ne held to his bi-houe;</L>
<L>To pore men &thorn;at wolde hit take,</L>
<L>he &yogh;af hit for cristes sake,</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at sitte&thorn; us alle aboue.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nou is Alix dwelled &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>his fader atom sike&thorn; wel sore,</L>
<L N="123">and sei&thorn;, Allas! Allas!</L>
<L>His Moder wepe&thorn; niht and day,</L>
<L>&amp; sei&thorn;, Allas! &amp; weila-wey,</L>
<L N="126">&thorn;at euere heo i-boren was.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His wyf wepe&thorn; and make&thorn; hir mone,</L>
<L>&amp; sei&thorn; &thorn;at heo schal liuen alone</L>
<L N="129">as turtul on &thorn;e treo.</L>
<L>Euermore with-outen Make,</L>
<L>Ioye and blisse heo wole forsake</L>
<L N="132">til heo hire spouse i-seo.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou is fader, with dreri chere,</L>
<L>bidde&thorn; his Men comen him nere,</L>
<L N="135">as &thorn;ei wolde haue heore mede.</L>
<L>He pre&yogh;e&thorn; hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben boun</L>
<L>to wenden &amp; sechen his deore sone,</L>
<L N="138">in eueriche a &thorn;eode;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e ne dwelle for no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>er &yogh;e han herd sum god ti&thorn;ing</L>
<L N="141">wher &thorn;at he be.</L>
<L>Go&thorn; nou for&thorn;, and god ow spede,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore i schal, so God me rede,</L>
<L N="144">&yogh;iuen ou gold and ffe.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now wende &thorn;ei for&thorn; Alix sekande,</L>
<L>vchone to diuerse lande,</L>
<L N="147">&yogh;if &thorn;ei mi&yogh;te him winne.</L>
<L>Summe of hem &thorn;orwh Godus grace,</L>
<L>comen in-to &thorn;at ilke place</L>
<L N="150">&thorn;at Alix was Inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He sat in pore Mennes rowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e him not knowe,</L>
<L N="153">&thorn;ei &yogh;euen him Charite.</L>
<L>He tok hit wi&thorn; mylde mod,</L>
<L>and seide, 'Iesus, &thorn;at died on Rod,</L>
<L N="156">lorde, i &thorn;onke &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, i-&thorn;onked be &thorn;ou ay,</L>
<L>&thorn;at i haue beden &thorn;at ilke day,</L>
<L N="159">&thorn;at i may for &thorn;i sake;</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at in myn owne lond,</L>
<L>serued me to fot and hond,</L>
<L N="162">her Almus to take.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;is Men &thorn;at weren out-sent,</L>
<L>a&yogh;ein ham-ward &thorn;ei hem went</L>
<L N="165">to sire Eufemiane.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sworen alle bi heuene kyng</L>
<L>of Alix herde heo no&thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="168">as wide as &thorn;ei hedden i-gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In eueri lond [&thorn;at] we han ben</L>
<L>we founde no mon &thorn;at him cou&thorn;e sen,</L>
<L N="171">&thorn;at to him cou&thorn;e vs wisse.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>"Nou, allas! &thorn;at i was boren;</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e haue i nou forloren</L>
<L N="174">mi Ioye and my blisse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &thorn;is tale wol we non dwelle,</L>
<L>of Alix wol we nou telle,</L>
<L N="177">&thorn;at riche pore mon.</L>
<L>Alix was pore Monnes fere</L>
<L>fulle seuentene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="180">fro &thorn;at he bi-gon,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sittinge in a chirche-&yogh;erde,</L>
<L>among pore men an herde,</L>
<L N="183">in a simple wede.</L>
<L>An ymage in &thorn;at chirche stoode</L>
<L>of his Modur &thorn;at died on rode,</L>
<L N="186">for ur alre nede.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Atte seuentene &yogh;eres ende</L>
<L>spac and seide wordus hende</L>
<L N="189">&thorn;at ymage of tre,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wardein of &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L>&amp; seide, "wardein, if &thorn;ou worche</L>
<L N="192">eny-&thorn;ing for me,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ffecche &thorn;ou in mi sones nom,</L>
<L>for seuentene &yogh;er hit is gon</L>
<L N="195">&thorn;at he ha&thorn; ben &thorn;er-oute.</L>
<L>I warne &thorn;e witerli</L>
<L>to dwelle her-in he is wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L N="198">&thorn;er-of haue &thorn;ou no doute;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"He ha&thorn; serued heuene bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;e holi gost in him is liht,</L>
<L N="201">&amp; &yogh;iue&thorn; him mi&yogh;t and grace,
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>&thorn;at his pre&yogh;ere, with milde steuene,</L>
<L>is swete &amp; god &amp; hei&yogh; in heuene</L>
<L N="204">bi-fore mi sone face."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;enne seide &thorn;e wardeyn, 'ladi,'</L>
<L>he seide, 'i wolde fayn, &amp; i</L>
<L N="207">wuste whulche.'</L>
<L>'Go out faste as &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t go,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou fyndest &thorn;er on &amp; no mo,</L>
<L N="210">bring him in &thorn;at ilche.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e wardein wente him out ful &yogh;are,</L>
<L>he fond him redi sittinge &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="213">he brou&yogh;te him in ful sone.</L>
<L>He seide, 'sire, &yogh;if hit be &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art welcome nou vs tille,</L>
<L N="216">here-in schaltou wone.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I was out aftur &thorn;e sent,</L>
<L>&thorn;orwh vr ladies comaundement,</L>
<L N="219">&thorn;e in forte take;</L>
<L>with muchel honour schaltou haue</L>
<L>alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt craue,</L>
<L N="222">for &thorn;at ladies sake.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;enne &thorn;is word bi-gon to springe,</L>
<L>&amp; of him was gret spekynge,</L>
<L N="225">for his holynesse.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore he &thorn;ou&yogh;te forte wende,</L>
<L>to ano&thorn;ur lond forte lende,</L>
<L N="228">&thorn;er me kneu&yogh; him lesse.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er wolde he no lengor beo:</L>
<L>monnus honour forte fle,</L>
<L N="231">fro &thorn;at stude he wente</L>
<L>In-to Laodiciane,</L>
<L>for&thorn; &thorn;e ri&yogh;te wey a-none,</L>
<L N="234">as Iesu crist him sente.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In-to a-no&thorn;ur lond he &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>godus wille til he hedde wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="237">&thorn;er nomon hed him knowe.</L>
<L>Assone as he was in &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>forte wende &thorn;er he wolde beo,</L>
<L N="240">&thorn;e wynd bi-gon to blowe;
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e wynt bi-gon &thorn;e schip to driue,</L>
<L>til &thorn;ei bi-gonne to aryue,</L>
<L N="243">as hit was godus wille,</L>
<L>In rome, &thorn;er he was fed &amp; boren,</L>
<L>&thorn;er his woninge was bi-foren,</L>
<L N="246">of al him &thorn;hu&yogh;te hit ille.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whon he sau&yogh; non o&thorn;ur won,</L>
<L>he bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him sone Anon,</L>
<L N="249">wher him was best to be.</L>
<L>To him-self he seide and &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>'si&thorn;en &thorn;at Iesu ha&thorn; me brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="252">in-to &thorn;is Cite,
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I con no beter red of alle,</L>
<L>bote go to my fader halle,</L>
<L N="255">in pore mennes route.</L>
<L>I may sitte vppon &thorn;e rowe;</L>
<L>&thorn;er nis no mon schal me knowe,</L>
<L N="258">so longe ichaue ben oute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vppon a day Eufemiane</L>
<L>fro his paleis was he gane,</L>
<L N="261">and ham-ward he eode,</L>
<L>with muche folk &thorn;at wel was di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e swein, [&amp;] knaue, &amp; kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="264">&thorn;at gode weren at nede.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alix &thorn;ou&yogh;te he wolde him mete,</L>
<L>&amp; ron faste bi &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L N="267">til &thorn;at he him mette.</L>
<L>whon he sau&yogh; &thorn;at he was nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>with a vois [bo&thorn;] loude &amp; hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="270">Eufemian his fader he grette,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide with a milde steuene,</L>
<L>'sire, for godus loue of heuene,</L>
<L N="273">haue merci of me.</L>
<L>Icham a pilgrim pore &amp; naked,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; gret defaute ymaket,</L>
<L N="276">sire, as &yogh;e mowe se.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Receiue me in-to &thorn;in halle,<MILESTONE N="44a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;i pore men aren alle;</L>
<L N="279">and graunte me &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>And i schal pre&yogh;e ni&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>for &thorn;i sone &thorn;at is a-way,</L>
<L N="282">&thorn;at Iesu crist him gete,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And grante &thorn;e, for his woundes fyue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou mai seo him &yogh;it a-lyue</L>
<L N="285">&thorn;at was &thorn;in herte blisse;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e, sire, withoute strif,</L>
<L>Ioye of him in soule lyf,</L>
<L N="288">crist &thorn;e to him wisse.'
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;enne Eufemian with-stod,</L>
<L>and grantede wi&thorn; a milde mod</L>
<L N="291">&thorn;at pore mon his bone.</L>
<L>He grantede him forte clo&thorn;e and feede,</L>
<L>and bad his men heo scholden him lede</L>
<L N="294">to his hous al sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He grantede him, as i ou telle,</L>
<L>an hous al-one &thorn;er-in to dwelle,</L>
<L N="297">wi&thorn;-outen eny fere;</L>
<L>And a mon &thorn;at scholde him gete,</L>
<L>&amp; bringe him bo&thorn;e drinke and mete,</L>
<L N="300">whon &thorn;at mester were.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nou Alix, as &yogh;e han [i]herd,</L>
<L>is dwelled in his fader &yogh;erd,</L>
<L N="303">as a pore mon;</L>
<L>In pre&yogh;ere, wakynge, and fastinge,</L>
<L>he seruede Iesu, heuene kynge,</L>
<L N="306">in al &thorn;at he con.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seruauns &thorn;at were proude and &yogh;inge,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei driuen him ofte to skorninge,</L>
<L N="309">as heo eoden vp and doun;</L>
<L>And ofte-si&thorn;es bro&thorn; of fissches,</L>
<L>&amp; watur &thorn;at &thorn;ei wosschen in dissches,</L>
<L N="312">heo casten vpon his croun.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of al &thorn;e schome &thorn;at &thorn;ei him wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>he &thorn;onked Iesu &thorn;at him bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="315">&amp; &yogh;af him mi&yogh;t &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>He was meke in alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;er-of mi&yogh;te no mon him bring,</L>
<L N="318">for nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alix dwelled &thorn;ere stille,</L>
<L>as hit was Iesus cristes wille,</L>
<L N="321">seuentene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In his owne fader Inne;</L>
<L>kneu&yogh; him non of al his kunne,</L>
<L N="324">nei&thorn;er fer ne nere.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Atte seuentene &yogh;eres ende,</L>
<L>he wuste he scholde he&thorn;en wende,</L>
<L N="327">&thorn;orw grace of &thorn;e holi gost,</L>
<L>To Iesu crist, godus sone,</L>
<L>in blisse with him forte wone,</L>
<L N="330">in lyf &thorn;at euer schal last.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He gat him enke &amp; parchemyn;</L>
<L>al his lyf he wrot &thorn;er-in,</L>
<L N="333">as he hedde i-lyued here,</L>
<L>And radde hit si&thorn;en vchadel,</L>
<L>he &thorn;onked god, so mihte he wel,</L>
<L N="336">wi&thorn; ful bli&thorn;e chere.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whon he hedde don as i ou say,</L>
<L>vppon &thorn;e holy son[e]day</L>
<L N="339">&thorn;at com aftur nest,</L>
<L>With muche Ioie &amp; muche li&yogh;t</L>
<L>his soule, &thorn;at was so feir &amp; bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="342">went out of his brest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;at gost was went to heuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;er com a vois with milde steuene</L>
<L N="345">in-to an holy stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere as &thorn;e folk of Rome were,</L>
<L>godus seruise forte here,</L>
<L N="348">&amp; biddynge of holy bede,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide &thorn;is word with-outen fayle:</L>
<L>'come&thorn; to me, &thorn;at haue&thorn; trauayle</L>
<L N="351">or tene for mi sake;</L>
<L>Come&thorn; to me, i schal ou fille</L>
<L>with ioy &amp; blisse, &amp; al or wille,</L>
<L N="354">&thorn;at neuermore schal slake.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;ei hedde &thorn;is wordus herd,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei weren vchone sore a-ferd,</L>
<L N="357">&amp; fullen a-doun to grounde.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei le&yogh;e &amp; hudde heor face,</L>
<L>&thorn;er com eft, &thorn;orw godus grace,</L>
<L N="360">in a luytel stounde,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er steuene milde &amp; meke,</L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;ei schulde ris vp, &amp; seke</L>
<L N="363">A godus mon of Rome,</L>
<L>'&thorn;at &yogh;e mowe, &thorn;orw&yogh; his pre&yogh;ere,</L>
<L>of his godnes ben partinere</L>
<L N="366">atte day of dome.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;ei risen Al vp with bli&thorn;e chere,</L>
<L>&amp; sou&yogh;te bo&thorn;e fer and nere,</L>
<L N="369">bi wei and [eke] bi strete.</L>
<L>And for no&thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ei wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>with &thorn;at relik &thorn;at &thorn;ei sou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="372">mou&yogh;te &thorn;ei nowhere mete,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Til &thorn;at vois, with wordes meke,</L>
<L>com a-&yogh;ein &amp; bad hem seke</L>
<L N="375">in Eufemians house;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere scholde &thorn;ei sone fynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at scholde hele doumbe &amp; blynde,</L>
<L N="378">a relik preciouse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;en &thorn;ei ede sone anan,</L>
<L>&amp; asked sire Eufemian</L>
<L N="381">&yogh;if he kneu&yogh; such a mon.</L>
<L>He onswerde ful rediliche,</L>
<L>'i sigge ou lordingus sikerliche</L>
<L N="384">of such ne wot i non.'
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;enne wente for&thorn; &thorn;e Emperours,</L>
<L>Archadius &amp; honorius,</L>
<L>&amp; Inocent &thorn;e Pope,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Pope <I>eras't</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon to Eufemians in,&mdash;</L>
<L>er &thorn;ei weore &thorn;er, wolde &thorn;ei not blin,&mdash;</L>
<L N="390">with hem a god gret frape.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en com a knaue sone a-nan,</L>
<L>&amp; seide to sire Eufemian,</L>
<L N="393">'go we, sire, i rede,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>And loke, sire, at oure pilgrime,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e han fed in long tyme,</L>
<L N="396">wher he beo quik or dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&YOGH;if he be ded &thorn;at was so meke,</L>
<L>he is &thorn;at mon &thorn;at &thorn;ei seke,</L>
<L N="399">i wot, with-outen drede.</L>
<L>He was a mon of holy lif,</L>
<L>of him com nei&thorn;er cheste ne strif,</L>
<L N="402">ne vuel word ne dede.'
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon Eufemian hedde &thorn;is herd,</L>
<L>he ron to loke hou Alix ferd,</L>
<L N="405">in-to his hous ful ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He fond him ded whon he com &thorn;are,</L>
<L>his visage &thorn;er hit lay al bare,</L>
<L N="408">as sonne hit schined bri&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In his hond he heold a skrit,</L>
<L>Eufemian sturte him for&thorn; as tit,</L>
<L N="411">to wite what was &thorn;er-Inne.</L>
<L>Bote with non scunes ginne</L>
<L>of &thorn;e hond &thorn;at hit was Inne</L>
<L N="414">mi&yogh;te he hit not out winne.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whon he mihte no betere spede,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Emperour he ede,</L>
<L N="417">and tolde &thorn;at ti&thorn;ande.</L>
<L>&thorn;enne come &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e for&thorn; god pas,</L>
<L>til &thorn;ei come &thorn;er hit was,</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;e dede cors liggande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whon &thorn;ei come in-to &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L>&thorn;is Emperours &thorn;ei seiden &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="423">and on &thorn;is Maneere:</L>
<L>'&thorn;au&yogh; we for sunne are vnwor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>we han kepinge not for&thorn;i</L>
<L N="426">of &thorn;eos londes heere.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And &thorn;is Mon &thorn;at we pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pope <I>eras't</I>]</NOTE> calle,</L>
<L>ha&thorn; &thorn;e pouwer of vs alle,</L>
<L N="429">and of al holichirche;</L>
<L>ffor&thorn;i diliuere vp &thorn;at scrite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we &thorn;er-&thorn;orwh mai seo and wite</L>
<L N="432">hou we schul with &thorn;e worche.'
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon &thorn;ei &thorn;us hedde iseid heor wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pope <I>eras't</I>]</NOTE> leide his hond &thorn;er-tille,</L>
<L N="435">&amp; he &thorn;enne let hit go.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pope <I>eras't</I>]</NOTE> let rede hit &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>bi-foren alle &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L N="438">heringe his fader Also.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon his fader hedde herd hit red,</L>
<L>he was a-wondred &amp; a-dred,</L>
<L N="441">for serwe he was nei&yogh; ded.</L>
<L>As mon &thorn;at hedde &thorn;e de&thorn;es wounde,</L>
<L>he fel a-doun to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="444">as heui as &thorn;e led.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whon he hedde longe i-leyn,</L>
<L>&amp; his stat was comen a&yogh;ein,</L>
<L N="447">he made reu&thorn;ful chere.</L>
<L>He tar his clo&thorn;us &amp; drou&yogh; his her,</L>
<L>with delful cri &amp; siking sor,</L>
<L N="450">&thorn;at del hit was to here.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Muche deol hit is to telle,</L>
<L>hou&yogh; he on &thorn;at bodi felle</L>
<L N="453">of weopyng blon he nouht.</L>
<L>He seide, 'Allas! mi dere sone,</L>
<L>hou mi&yogh;test &thorn;ou &thorn;us longe wone</L>
<L N="456">with me &thorn;at kneu&yogh; &thorn;e nouht?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas! nou hastou dwelled here</L>
<L>al &thorn;is seuentene &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="459">in myn owne Inne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast boren &thorn;e so lowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest neuere ben a-knowe</L>
<L N="462">&thorn;at &thorn;ou wer of mi kinne.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas! allas! and weilawai,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euere I a-bod &thorn;is day,</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;is serwe forte seo.</L>
<L>I wende haue had of &thorn;e solas</L>
<L>in myn elde; Allas! Allas!</L>
<L N="468">for deol ded wol i beo.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon his Moder herde of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>heo sturte for&thorn; in haste i-wis,</L>
<L N="471">As A lyonesse;</L>
<L>with hirself heo ferde to wonder,</L>
<L>heo ter hir clo&thorn;us al in sunder,</L>
<L N="474">in a gret woodnesse.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo drou&yogh; hir her as heo weore wod,</L>
<L>&amp; seide, 'for him &thorn;at died on rod,</L>
<L N="477">Men, &yogh;e &yogh;iue me way,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I mai to mi sone go;</L>
<L>was neuer Moder half so wo</L>
<L N="480">as me is &thorn;is day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if me roum, &amp; let me se</L>
<L>&thorn;e bodi &thorn;at was boren of me,</L>
<L N="483">and fed of my breste.</L>
<L>Let me come &thorn;at cors to,</L>
<L>for wel &yogh;e witen hit is skil so</L>
<L N="486">&thorn;at i beo hit nexte.'
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon heo mi&yogh;te nei&yogh;e hit neer,</L>
<L>heo fel &thorn;er-on with deolful cher,</L>
<L N="489">&amp; seide, 'Allas! mi sone,</L>
<L>Whi woldestou &thorn;us with us fare,</L>
<L>to leten vs dwellen in serwe &amp; care?</L>
<L N="492">whi hastou &thorn;us done?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou hast i-se&yogh;en &thorn;i fader and me</L>
<L>wepen &amp; maken gret del for &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="495">bo&thorn;e erly and late;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast seuentene &yogh;er</L>
<L>vnknowen i-dwelled mid vs her,</L>
<L N="498">in pore beggers state.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte-si&thorn;es heo fel doun</L>
<L>on &thorn;at dede cors al in swoun,</L>
<L N="501">and custe hondes and feet;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at face &thorn;at was so swete,</L>
<L>heo custe hit &amp; mad hit wete</L>
<L N="504">with teres &thorn;at heo leet.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo seide, 'allas! &thorn;at me is wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou were my sone with-outen mo,</L>
<L N="507">wepe&thorn; alle wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>Ichaue &thorn;e fed moni a day,</L>
<L>Allas! sone, weilaway,</L>
<L N="510">&thorn;at i ne knewh not &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou mist haue be a gret lordyng,</L>
<L>and ben honoured as a king,</L>
<L N="513">&yogh;if hit hedde beo &thorn;i wille.</L>
<L>Nou hastou had despit and wrong</L>
<L>of &thorn;i &thorn;ralles euer among,</L>
<L N="516">and boren hit ful stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas! ho schal &yogh;iue to me</L>
<L>welle of teres to wepe for &thorn;e</L>
<L N="519">bo&thorn;e dai and niht?<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Allas! allas! me is wo,</L>
<L>icholde myn herte wolde breken a-two,</L>
<L N="522">&thorn;at i sai&yogh; nou &thorn;is siht.'
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;enne com for&thorn; a dreri &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>i-clo&thorn;ed in clo&thorn;us of mournyng,</L>
<L N="525">&thorn;at was his owne wyue.</L>
<L>Heo wepte &thorn;at pite was to se,</L>
<L>and seide, 'Allas! &thorn;at wo is me,</L>
<L N="528">&thorn;at euere hedde I lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou al my ioye a-wei is gon,</L>
<L>er hedde i hope, nou habbe i non</L>
<L N="531">to seon him a-lyue.</L>
<L>Nou am i widewe, allas! &thorn;e stounde,</L>
<L>serwe ha&thorn; &yogh;iue myn herte a wounde,</L>
<L N="534">&thorn;at me to de&thorn; wol driue.
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas! what is me to rede,</L>
<L>mi Muror is broken &amp; is dede,</L>
<L N="537">&thorn;at my likynge was Inne.</L>
<L>Hope of ioie nou haue I loren,</L>
<L>&amp; serwe is newed me beforen</L>
<L N="540">&thorn;at neuermore schal blinne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at stod be-side,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sei&yogh; heore serwe so vnride,</L>
<L N="543">a wepten ful tenderliche.</L>
<L>&thorn;er was non &thorn;at mi&yogh;te hem holde,</L>
<L>Mon ne wommon, &yogh;ong ne olde,</L>
<L N="546">and &thorn;at was no feorliche.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pope <I>crosst through</I>]</NOTE> com, &amp; &thorn;e Emperours</L>
<L>bad bringe him for&thorn; out of &thorn;e hous</L>
<L>&amp; lei him on A bere,</L>
<L>And bar him wi&thorn; solempnete,</L>
<L>for&thorn; Amidde &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L N="552">&amp; cri&yogh;inge &thorn;at almi&yogh;te here,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide, 'come seo&thorn; &thorn;at holi mon</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e haue sou&yogh;t euerichon,</L>
<L N="555">here he is in &thorn;is place.</L>
<L>He is founden, and he is here,</L>
<L>&thorn;at holi bodi on a beere,</L>
<L N="558">&thorn;orwh help of godus grace.'
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at wusten of &thorn;at cri,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ornen &thorn;idere wel hasteli,</L>
<L N="561">&thorn;ei tolde &thorn;eron nout a lyte.</L>
<L>An Alle &thorn;e seke &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>&thorn;at mi&yogh;te touche &thorn;at bodi &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;ei weren hole as tite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e blinde hedde &thorn;ere of him here si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>woode of him heore wit fol ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="567">&thorn;e halt here limes hole Anon.</L>
<L>Hit was non &thorn;at &thorn;ider mi&yogh;te winne,</L>
<L>what seknes &thorn;ei were inne,</L>
<L N="570">&thorn;at &thorn;ei were hole vchon.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon &thorn;e Emperours sai &thorn;e wonder</L>
<L>&thorn;ei toke &thorn;e bere &amp; eode &thorn;er-vndur,</L>
<L>with the Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>crosst out</I>]</NOTE> helpande;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei wolde be i-mad holi,</L>
<L>&thorn;orwh beringe of &thorn;at bodi,</L>
<L N="576">&thorn;ei toke &thorn;e bere in hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ei made sowen in &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>gold &amp; seluer gret plente;</L>
<L N="579">and &thorn;at was for &thorn;is skil</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e folk scholde hem with-drawe,</L>
<L>and &thorn;at auayled not wor&thorn; an haue,</L>
<L N="582">&thorn;ei tok no tent &thorn;er-til.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ei preced euer neer and neere,</L>
<L>forte come to &thorn;at bere</L>
<L N="585">&thorn;at &thorn;e cors lay Inne.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei precede wi&thorn; so gret fors</L>
<L>&thorn;at vnne&thorn;e with &thorn;e holi cors,</L>
<L N="588">to chirche mi&yogh;te &thorn;ei winne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; whon &thorn;ei come to &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L>A toumbe of gold &thorn;ei lette worche</L>
<L N="591">of preciouse stones.</L>
<L>In A schort tyme hit was diht,</L>
<L>ful richeliche and Al ari&yogh;t</L>
<L N="594">&thorn;ei leide &thorn;er-in his bones.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whon &thorn;at holi cors was leid</L>
<L>in &thorn;at toumbe &thorn;at wel was grei|&thorn;ed,</L>
<L N="597">wi&thorn; ful gret honour,</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at weren in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&thorn;er com out, &thorn;orwh godes grace,</L>
<L N="600">a ful swete odour;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So swote felede &thorn;ei neuer non,</L>
<L>as wyde as &thorn;ei hedden gon,</L>
<L N="603">of no spicerie.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>&thorn;enne worschupeden heo Alle with o steuene,</L>
<L>Iesu, godus sone of heuene,</L>
<L N="606">and his Modur Marie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iesu crist, &thorn;orwh &thorn;e prei&yogh;ere</L>
<L>of him &thorn;at we haue of told here,</L>
<L N="609">&yogh;if &thorn;i wille hit be,</L>
<L>Graunt vs alle god endyng,</L>
<L>and in heuene a wonyng.</L>
<L N="612">AMEN par Charite.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="manuscript"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20">
<HEAD>[<I>Laud MS.</I> 108, <I>leaf</I> 233, <I>back</I>.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>VITA CUIUSDAM SANCTI VIRI NOMINE ALEX. OPTIMA VITA.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sitte&thorn; stille wi&thorn;outen strif,</L>
<L>And I schal telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e lif</L>
<L N="3">Of an holy man.</L>
<L>Alex was his ry&yogh;tte name;</L>
<L>To serue god &thorn;oute him no schame,</L>
<L N="6">&amp; &thorn;erof neuere he ne blan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his fader was a gret lording</L>
<L>Of rome, a kynges euening,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="9">&amp; hy&yogh;tte sire Eufemian.</L>
<L>Pore men to clo&thorn;e &amp; fede,</L>
<L>In al rome, &thorn;at riche &thorn;ede,</L>
<L N="12">Swich ne waster non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eche day were in his halle</L>
<L>Leyd &thorn;re bordes, forto calle</L>
<L N="15">Pore men to fede.</L>
<L>Hem to serue he was wel glad,</L>
<L>&amp; dede as Iesu crist him bad;</L>
<L N="18">&thorn;erfore he hopede han mede.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;ei were serued by &amp; by,</L>
<L>&thorn;ane at arst was he redy</L>
<L N="21">To gon to his mete;</L>
<L>&thorn;anne in drede of godes sone,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; men of religione</L>
<L N="24">He wolde sitte &amp; ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His wif hy&yogh;tte dame Agles,</L>
<L>To seye &thorn;e so&thorn;e wi&thorn;oute les,</L>
<L N="27">&thorn;at meche was to preyse;
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;e my&yogh;tte do &thorn;e same maner</L>
<L>&thorn;at dede hire lord, as y seyde er,</L>
<L N="30">Was &yogh;e nat wel atayse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="234a" UNIT="folio">Child hem bi-twene ne hadde &thorn;ei non;</L>
<L>&thorn;er-fore to god he maden here mon,</L>
<L N="33">Bo&thorn;e be day &amp; ny&yogh;the;</L>
<L>Iesu crist herde here bone,</L>
<L>&amp; sente hem a ful god sone,</L>
<L N="36">here hertes forto ly&yogh;the.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When he was bore, &thorn;at blisful child,</L>
<L>Alex, bo&thorn;e mek &amp; myld,</L>
<L N="39">And of maneres hende:</L>
<L>A litel after, wi&thorn; greth hast</L>
<L>&thorn;ei a-voweden to him chast,</L>
<L N="42">To here lyues ende.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er-after was it nat lange:</L>
<L>Alex coude speke &amp; gange,</L>
<L N="45">And was set to lere.</L>
<L>Sone he was a ful good clerk,</L>
<L>&amp; meche he louede godes werk</L>
<L N="48">fforto speke &amp; here.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone whan he gan to belde,</L>
<L>&amp; forto comen to mannes elde,</L>
<L N="51">him was chosen a wif,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e emperoures bour,</L>
<L>A mayde good, of greth honur,</L>
<L N="54">To wedde wi&thorn;-oute strif.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were wedded &thorn;e ferste ny&yogh;th</L>
<L>In godes [lawe], as it was ry&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="57">&amp; was I-brouth to house:</L>
<L>Mek[e]liche he gan hire teche,</L>
<L>To drede god, of sinne leche,</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at is maydenes spouse.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he prechede hire wi&thorn; al his my&yogh;th:</L>
<L>Of s[i]nne &yogh;e scholde hauen no ply&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="63">Bote kepe hire maydenhod;</L>
<L>&amp; of iesu, &thorn;at mayde clene,</L>
<L>In whom was neuere wem I-sene,</L>
<L N="66">&yogh;e scholde habbe hire mede.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne tok he his gold ring,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af &thorn;at mayde, &thorn;at was &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="69">&amp; seyde to hire &thorn;us:</L>
<L>'Tak &thorn;is ring, &amp; kep it me,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at godes wille be,</L>
<L N="72">God bi-twene vs.'
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne he hadde ido, as [I] &yogh;ou sey,</L>
<L>He tok his leue &amp; wente his wey</L>
<L N="75">fro &thorn;at mayde fre;</L>
<L>A parti of his good he wi&thorn; him tok,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at o&thorn;er he for-sok,</L>
<L N="78">he wente to &thorn;e see.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He fond schipes redely;</L>
<L>To on he wente priueli,</L>
<L N="81">ouer forto fare;</L>
<L>He seyde he was a chapman,</L>
<L>&amp; preyde, he moste wi&thorn; hem gon,</L>
<L N="84">&yogh;if &thorn;at here schip were &yogh;are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor&thorn; he wente wi&thorn; godes wille;</L>
<L>A fair cyte he com vn-tille;</L>
<L N="87">&thorn;e name I schal &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L>Edissa hatte &thorn;at cite;</L>
<L>Godes seruant &thorn;er to be,</L>
<L N="90">&thorn;er-inne wolde he dwelle.
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e goodes &thorn;at he wi&thorn; him brougth,</L>
<L>Of hem ne wolde he ry&yogh;th nowth,</L>
<L N="93">Bote &yogh;af hem pore menne;</L>
<L>his robe he &yogh;af &thorn;er he sey nede,</L>
<L>&amp; clo&thorn;ede him-sulf in pore wede,</L>
<L N="96">ffor noman scholde him kenne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he &yogh;ede to a churche-&yogh;ate,</L>
<L>&thorn;er pouere men sete in &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L N="99">Almesse forto take;</L>
<L>Among hem he sat a-doun,</L>
<L>&amp; Askede wi&thorn; deuocion</L>
<L N="102">Sum good for godes sake.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at churche was of oure leuedy;</L>
<L>&thorn;er-inne was a greth selly,</L>
<L N="105">An ymage of hire son,</L>
<L>Maked of a wonder werk,<MILESTONE N="234b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at ney&thorn;er lewed man ne clerk</L>
<L N="108">Niste hou it was don.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;erfore was &thorn;ider greth sekyng</L>
<L>Of on &amp; o&thorn;er, old &amp; &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="111">Of al &thorn;at countre;
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;e pouere &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e betere my&yogh;tte fare</L>
<L N="114">&thorn;oru here charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alex, of &thorn;at he my&yogh;tte gete</L>
<L>Nedliche bote &thorn;at him-self wolde ete</L>
<L N="117">he ne held to his by-houe;</L>
<L>To pouere men &thorn;at wolde it take,</L>
<L>Al he &yogh;af for godes sake,</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at is in heuene A-boue.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou is Alex dwelled &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>his fader at hom seyet&yogh; sore,</L>
<L N="123">&amp; sey&thorn; 'allas! allas!'</L>
<L>his moder wepu&thorn; ny&yogh;th &amp; day</L>
<L>&amp; sey&thorn; 'allas &amp; weylawey,</L>
<L N="126">&thorn;at euere &yogh;he born was.'
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his wif wep&thorn; &amp; make&thorn; hire mone,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us [&yogh;he] schal lyuen allone,</L>
<L N="129">As turtle opon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Euere-more wi&thorn;oute make;</L>
<L>Ioye &amp; blisse &yogh;e wile for-sake,</L>
<L N="132">Til &yogh;e hire spouse se.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou his fader wi&thorn; dreri chere</L>
<L>He bidde&thorn; his men him comen nere,</L>
<L N="135">Als &thorn;ei willen hauen &thorn;ere mede,</L>
<L>&amp; preye&thorn; hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben boun,</L>
<L>To wende &amp; sechen his dere sone</L>
<L N="138">In euerich ilk a &thorn;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&thorn;at &yogh;e ne dwelle for no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Ar &yogh;e hauen herd sum tyding,</L>
<L N="141">Where &thorn;at he be;</L>
<L>Go&thorn; nou swy&thorn;e, &amp; god &yogh;ou spede!</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I schal, so god me rede,</L>
<L N="144">&yogh;iuen &yogh;ou gold &amp; fee.'
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou gon &thorn;ei for&thorn; Alex sekynd</L>
<L>In diuerse londes to here tyding,</L>
<L N="147">&yogh;if &thorn;ei him my&yogh;tte wynne;</L>
<L>Somme of hem, &thorn;oru godes grace,</L>
<L>Comen into &thorn;at ilke place</L>
<L N="150">&thorn;er Alex was Inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he sat in pore mene rowe;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore couden he hym nat knowe;</L>
<L N="153">he &yogh;af him charite;</L>
<L>&amp; he it tok wi&thorn; milde mod,</L>
<L>And seyde 'Iesu, &thorn;at deyde on rod,</L>
<L N="156">Louerd, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e!
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Louerd, i-her[i]d be &thorn;ou ay!</L>
<L>&thorn;at i haue beden &thorn;at ilke day,</L>
<L N="159">&thorn;at I may, for &thorn;i sake,</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at in myn owene lond</L>
<L>Serueden me to fot &amp; hond</L>
<L N="162">Here Almesse forto take.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;ese men &thorn;at were out-sent,</L>
<L>a&yogh;en homward &thorn;ei ben I-went</L>
<L N="165">To sire eufemian.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei swore to him be heuene king:</L>
<L>Of Alex herde &thorn;ei no tyding,</L>
<L N="168">As wyde as &thorn;ei hadde gan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'In eche a lond &thorn;an haue we be,</L>
<L>We ne founden no man &thorn;at cou&thorn;e him se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to him coude vs wisse.'
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>'Allas, he seyde, &thorn;at he was born!</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bo&thorn;o MS.]</NOTE> haue I nou for-lorn</L>
<L N="174">Mi ioye &amp; ek my blisse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;is tale wille we nat dwelle,</L>
<L>Bote of Alex wile we telle,</L>
<L N="177">&thorn;at riche pore man.</L>
<L>Alex was pouere mannes fere</L>
<L>ffulli seuentene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="180">fro &thorn;at he bi-gan,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syttynde in a churche-&yogh;erd</L>
<L>Amonges o&thorn;ere men an herd</L>
<L N="183">In a simple wede.</L>
<L>An ymage in &thorn;at cherche stod,</L>
<L>Of his moder &thorn;at deyde on rood</L>
<L N="186">ffor oure al&thorn;res nede.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e seuentene &yogh;eres ende,</L>
<L>Spak &amp; seyde wordes hende,</L>
<L N="189">&thorn;at ymage of tre,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wardeyn of &thorn;e churche,</L>
<L>&amp; seyde: 'wardeyn, &yogh;if &thorn;ou werche</L>
<L N="192">Eny&thorn;ing for me,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffeche &thorn;ou In my sones man,</L>
<L>ffor seuentene &yogh;er it is i-gan</L>
<L N="195">&thorn;at he ha&thorn; ben &thorn;er-oute;</L>
<L>I &thorn;e warne wyterly,</L>
<L>To duelle her-inne he is wor&thorn;i;</L>
<L N="198">Whar-of ne haue no doute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he ha&thorn; deserued heuene bry&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy gost is in him ly&yogh;th</L>
<L N="201">&amp; &yogh;iuen him my&yogh;tte &amp; grace,
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>&thorn;at his preyer wi&thorn; milde stephene</L>
<L>Is good &amp; swete &amp; mylde in heuene</L>
<L N="204">Byfore my sones face.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne ansuerede &thorn;e wardeyn</L>
<L>&amp; seyde: 'lauedi, I wille ful fayn,</L>
<L N="207">and I wiste wilk.'<MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'Go owt so swi&thorn;e so &thorn;ou mayst go,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ne fyndest &thorn;er no mo,</L>
<L N="210">Bryng him [in] &thorn;at ilk!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e wardeyn wente him out ful &yogh;are,</L>
<L>he fond [him] redy sittinde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="213">he brougthe him In ful sone;</L>
<L>And [seyde]: 'sire, &yogh;if it be &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art welcome vs vntille,</L>
<L N="216">Her-Inne schaltou wone;
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I was out after &thorn;e i-sent</L>
<L>&thorn;oru our lauedies comandement,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. comandemement]</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e in forto take.</L>
<L>Mechul honur schaltou haue,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt craue,</L>
<L N="222">ffor &thorn;at lauedies sake.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;is word be-gan to springe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of him was a gret spekyngge</L>
<L N="225">ffor his holinesse,</L>
<L>Sone he &thorn;outthe forto wende,</L>
<L>To o&thorn;er londe forto lende,</L>
<L N="228">&thorn;ere men him knewe lesse.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ere ne wolde he lengere be,</L>
<L>Mannes honur forto fle,</L>
<L N="231">ffro &thorn;at stede he wende</L>
<L>Anon to laodician</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; &thorn;e ry&yogh;tte wey anon,</L>
<L N="234">Als iesu crist him sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To A-no&thorn;er lond he &thorn;out,</L>
<L>Godes wille to han I-wrouth,</L>
<L N="237">&thorn;er noman ne hadde him knowe.</L>
<L>Als swi&thorn;e as he was in &thorn;e se</L>
<L>fforto wende &thorn;er he wolde be,</L>
<L N="240">&thorn;e wynd be-gan to blowe.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e wynd be-gan &thorn;e schip to dryue</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he be-gonne to Aryue,</L>
<L N="243">Als it was godes wille,</L>
<L>In rome &thorn;er he was fed &amp; born,</L>
<L>&thorn;er his wonyng was be-forn,</L>
<L N="246">&thorn;ei al him &thorn;oute ille.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he saw non o&thorn;er won,</L>
<L>he be-&thorn;outte him sone anon,</L>
<L N="249">Whare him was best to be;</L>
<L>To him-sulf he seyde &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;th:</L>
<L>'Si&thorn;en Iesus me ha&thorn; hider i-brou&yogh;th</L>
<L N="252">In-to &thorn;is cite,
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I ne can no betere red of alle,</L>
<L>Bote gon to my faderes halle</L>
<L N="255">In pore mannes rowte,</L>
<L>I may sitte in &thorn;e rowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;er nis no man &thorn;at me schal knowe:</L>
<L N="258">So longe Ich haue ben oute.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vpon a day sire Eufemian</L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e paleys was he gan,</L>
<L N="261">And homward he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mikel folk &thorn;at wel waren dy&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e knaue sweyn &amp; knyth,</L>
<L N="264">&thorn;at gode were in nede.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alex &thorn;oute he wolde him mete;</L>
<L>&amp; ran for&thorn; faste be &thorn;e strete</L>
<L N="267">Vn-til &thorn;at he him mette;</L>
<L>Whan he say &thorn;at [he] was ney,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a voys bo&thorn;e loud &amp; hey,</L>
<L N="270">Sire Eufemian he grette,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; seyde wi&thorn; a mylde stephene:</L>
<L>'Sire, for godes loue of heuene</L>
<L N="273">haue merci on me!</L>
<L>Ich am a pilgrym pore &amp; nakud,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gret defaute ha&thorn; I-maked,</L>
<L N="276">Sire, as &yogh;e may I-se.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Resceyue me into &thorn;in halle,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere &thorn;ine pore men ben alle,</L>
<L N="279">&amp; graunte me &thorn;e mete!</L>
<L>And I schal preye ny&yogh;th &amp; day</L>
<L>for &thorn;i sone &thorn;at is awey,</L>
<L N="282">&thorn;at Iesu crist him &thorn;e gete,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&amp; grante &thorn;e, for his wondes fiue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou myttest him se in &thorn;ine lyue,</L>
<L N="285">&thorn;at was &thorn;in herte blisse,</L>
<L>&amp;, sire, to habbe wi&thorn;oute strif</L>
<L>Ioye of him in soule &amp; lif,</L>
<L N="288">Crist &thorn;e til him wisse.'
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne eufemian &thorn;er wi&thorn;stod,</L>
<L>&amp; grantede him wi&thorn; milde mod,</L>
<L N="291">&thorn;e pore man his bone;</L>
<L>he grantede him to clo&thorn;e &amp; fede,</L>
<L>&amp; bad his men he scholde him lede</L>
<L N="294">To his hous as sone;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And grauntede him, as [I] &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>An hous allone &thorn;er-in to dwelle</L>
<L N="297">Wi&thorn;-outen eny fere,</L>
<L>&amp; a man &thorn;at scholde him gete</L>
<L>And bringe him bo&thorn;e drynk &amp; mete,</L>
<L N="300">Whan &thorn;at mester were.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou Alex, As &yogh;e habbe&thorn; i-herd,</L>
<L>Is dweld in his fader &yogh;erd</L>
<L N="303">As a pore man.</L>
<L>In preyere of fasting &amp; waking,</L>
<L>he seruede Iesu, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="306">In al &thorn;at he can.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seruant&yogh; &thorn;at were proute &amp; &yogh;ungge,</L>
<L>him dryuen ofte to he&thorn;ingge,</L>
<L N="309">As he &yogh;ede vp &amp; doun;</L>
<L>&amp; ofte-si&thorn;es, bro&thorn; of ffissches,</L>
<L>&amp; water, as he wessch here dissches,</L>
<L N="312">&thorn;ei caste vp-on his croun.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="235b" UNIT="folio">Of al &thorn;e schame &thorn;at &thorn;ei him wrou&yogh;the,</L>
<L>He &thorn;onkede Iesu, &thorn;at him bouthe,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;af him my&yogh;tte &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>He was &thorn;olemod in alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>&thorn;er-out ne my&yogh;tte no man him bringe,</L>
<L N="318">ffor nowth &thorn;ei couden do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ere dwelde Alex stille,</L>
<L>As it was Iesu cristes wille,</L>
<L N="321">Seuentene &yogh;er;</L>
<L>In his owene faderes In,</L>
<L>kneu him non of al his kyn,</L>
<L N="324">Ney&thorn;er fer ne ner.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e seuente&thorn;e &yogh;eres ende,</L>
<L>he wiste he scholde hennes wende,</L>
<L N="327">&thorn;oru grace of &thorn;e holy gast,</L>
<L>To Iesu crist, godes sone,</L>
<L>In blisse of heuene ay forto wone,</L>
<L N="330">In &thorn;e lif &thorn;at euere schal last.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// he gat him enke &amp; parchemyn;</L>
<L>And al his lif he wrot &thorn;er-In,</L>
<L N="333">&thorn;at he had lyued here,</L>
<L>And radde it se&thorn;en eueri-del,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onkede god, so my&yogh;t he wel,</L>
<L N="336">Wi&thorn; ful bli&thorn;e chere.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he hadde I-do as I &yogh;ou say,</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e holy soneday</L>
<L N="339">&thorn;at com after nest,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; meche ioye &amp; meche ly&yogh;th,</L>
<L>his soule, &thorn;at was so fair &amp; bry&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="342">Wente out at his brest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When his soule was went to heuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;er com a vois wi&thorn; milde stephene</L>
<L N="345">In-to an holy stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;er al &thorn;e folk of rome were,</L>
<L>Godes seruise forto here,</L>
<L N="348">To bidden holy bede,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyde &thorn;es wordes wi&thorn;oute faille:</L>
<L>"Come&thorn; to me, &thorn;at haue&thorn; trauaille</L>
<L N="351">O&thorn;er charge for my sake!</L>
<L>Come&thorn; to me, I schal &yogh;ou fille</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioye &amp; blisse at al &yogh;oure wille,</L>
<L N="354">&thorn;at neuere mor schal slake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;e folk hadde &thorn;at word herd,</L>
<L>&thorn;e[i] were echone sore a-fered</L>
<L N="357">&amp; fullen doun to grounde;</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei leyen &amp; hedde here face,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar com owth, &thorn;oru godes grace,</L>
<L N="360">In a litel stounde,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er stephene mylde &amp; meke,</L>
<L>&amp; bad hem vp arise, &amp; seke</L>
<L N="363">A godes man of rome,</L>
<L>'&thorn;at &yogh;e mowe, &thorn;oru his preyer,</L>
<L>Of his godnesse ben partener</L>
<L N="366">At &thorn;e day of dome.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;ei risen alle wi&thorn; bli&thorn;e chere</L>
<L>&amp; southe bo&thorn;e fer &amp; nere,</L>
<L N="369">Be weye &amp; ek be strete;</L>
<L>Bote for no&thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ei wrouth,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at relyk &thorn;at &thorn;ei south,</L>
<L N="372">My&yogh;tte &thorn;e[i] nowar mete;
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Til &thorn;at voit&yogh; wi&thorn; worde meke</L>
<L>Com a&yogh;en, &amp; bad hem seke</L>
<L N="375">In sire Eufemianes hous,</L>
<L>'&thorn;er &yogh;e scholle sone fynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at schal hele dombe &amp; blynde,</L>
<L N="378">A relik precious.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne wente &thorn;ei for&thorn; a-nan,</L>
<L>&amp; askeden sire eufemian:</L>
<L N="381">&yogh;if he knew swich a man.</L>
<L>he ansuerede redely</L>
<L>&amp; seyde: lordingges, sikerly,</L>
<L N="384">Of swich ne wot I non.
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne wente for&thorn; &thorn;e emperuors,</L>
<L>Archadious &amp; honorius,</L>
<L N="387">&amp; Innocent &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>Anon to sire Eufemia[n]s In;</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come &thorn;ere, wolde &thorn;ei nat blyn;</L>
<L N="390">Wi&thorn; hem wente for&thorn; greth frape.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;anne cam for&thorn; a knaue anan,</L>
<L>&amp; seyde to sire eufemian:</L>
<L N="393">'Go we, sire, I rede,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>And loken [sire] at &yogh;oure pilgrim</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e han fed of long tym,</L>
<L N="396">Wher he be quik o&thorn;er dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&yogh;if he be ded &thorn;at was so meke,</L>
<L>he is &thorn;at man &thorn;at &thorn;ei seke,</L>
<L N="399">I wot wi&thorn;-oute drede:</L>
<L>he was a man of holy lif,</L>
<L>Of him com neuere stout ne strif,</L>
<L N="402">Ne wikke word ne dede.'
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne eufemian &thorn;at i-herde,</L>
<L>he &yogh;ede to loke hou alex ferde,</L>
<L N="405">To his hous ful ry&yogh;th;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio">he fond him ded whan he com &thorn;are,</L>
<L>his face, &thorn;er it lay on bere,</L>
<L N="408">As sonne schinede bry&yogh;th.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In his hond he fond a skript,</L>
<L>Eufemian &yogh;ede to him as tyd</L>
<L N="411">To wyte what was &thorn;er-Inne;</L>
<L>Bote for nones kynnes gyn</L>
<L>out of &thorn;e hond &thorn;at it was In</L>
<L N="414">My&yogh;tte he it nat wynne.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he ne my&yogh;tte no betere spede,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e emperour he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="417">&amp; tolde him &thorn;at tydingge.</L>
<L>&thorn;ane come&thorn; he a&yogh;en god pas,</L>
<L>Til he comen &thorn;ar he was,</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;e dede corps liggynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ei comen Into &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L>&thorn;e emperour seyde &thorn;us</L>
<L N="423">And on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei we for synne ben vn-wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>We han to kepyng nawth for-&thorn;i</L>
<L N="426">of &thorn;ese londes here;
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And &thorn;is man &thorn;at we pope calle,</L>
<L>ha&thorn; &thorn;e kepyng of vs alle</L>
<L N="429">&amp; of holy churche;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore deliure vs vp &thorn;e skryt,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we &thorn;ere-&thorn;oru may se &amp; wyt</L>
<L N="432">hou we schulle wi&thorn; &thorn;e werche."
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen &thorn;ei hadde &thorn;us seid here wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope leyde his hond &thorn;er-tille,</L>
<L N="435">Alex &thorn;an let go.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope as tyd let rede it &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Byfore al &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L N="438">herynde his fader also.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan his fader herde it rede,</L>
<L>he was for-wondred &amp; for-drede,</L>
<L N="441">for sorwe he was ney ded;</L>
<L>As man &thorn;at hadde de&thorn;es wounde</L>
<L>He fel swingge doun to grounde,</L>
<L N="444">Heuy so any led.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wan he hadde longe I-leyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;an his stat bi-com a-gayn,</L>
<L N="447">&amp; made reuly chere;</L>
<L>he rof his brest, he drou his her</L>
<L>wi&thorn; duelful cry &amp; syking sor,</L>
<L N="450">&thorn;at pite it was to here.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meche doel it is to telle</L>
<L>hou he on &thorn;at body felle,</L>
<L N="453">of weping blan he nouth.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Allas nou hastou duelled here</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese seuentene &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="459">In myn owene In,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou hast boren &thorn;e so lowe,</L>
<L>&amp; noldest neuere ben o knowe</L>
<L N="462">&thorn;at &thorn;ou were of oure kyn.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out ay, allas, &amp; weylawey,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I euere a-bod &thorn;is day</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;is sorwe forto se!</L>
<L>I wende han had of &thorn;e solas</L>
<L>In myn elde, allas, allas,</L>
<L N="468">for doel ded willi be!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne his moder herde of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&yogh;e sterte for&thorn; in haste i-wis</L>
<L N="471">as a leonesse,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire sulf sche ferde to wonder,</L>
<L>Sche rof hire clo&thorn;es al to sonder</L>
<L N="474">In a gret wodnesse;
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche drou hire her as sche were wod,</L>
<L>&amp; seyde: "for him &thorn;at deyde on rod,</L>
<L N="477">&yogh;e men, &yogh;iue&thorn; me wey,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I may to my sone go!</L>
<L>Was neuere moder half so wo</L>
<L N="480">As me is &thorn;is day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;iue&thorn; me roum, &amp; lat me se</L>
<L>&thorn;e body &thorn;at was boren of me,</L>
<L N="483">&amp; fed was of my brest!</L>
<L>lete&thorn; me come &thorn;e cors vntil,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e wyten &thorn;at it is skyl</L>
<L N="486">&thorn;at I be it next."
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan sche my&yogh;tte neyh it nere,</L>
<L>Sche fel &thorn;er-on wi&thorn; sori chere,</L>
<L N="489">&amp; seyde: "allas, my son,</L>
<L>Whi hauest tou &thorn;us wi&thorn; vs fare,</L>
<L>Suffred vs for &thorn;e sorwe &amp; care,</L>
<L N="492">Whi hastou &thorn;us don?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou hast i-seye &thorn;i fader &amp; me</L>
<L>Wepen &amp; maken gret doel for &thorn;e</L>
<L N="495">Bo&thorn;e erly &amp; late;</L>
<L>And tou hast seuentene &yogh;er</L>
<L>Vn-knowe duelled wi&thorn; vs her</L>
<L N="498">In pouere beggeres state."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte-si&thorn;e &yogh;e fel doun</L>
<L>opon &thorn;e body al I-swoun,</L>
<L N="501">&amp; kissede honden &amp; feet;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at face &thorn;at was so swete,</L>
<L>Sche it kiste, &amp; made it wete</L>
<L N="504">Wi&thorn; teres &thorn;at sche let.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche seide: "allas, what me is wo!</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="236b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ou were my sone wi&thorn;-oute mo;</L>
<L>Wepe&thorn; al folk wi&thorn; me!</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;e fed many a day;</L>
<L>Allas owt &amp; weylawey,</L>
<L N="510">&thorn;at I ne knew nout &thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou my&yogh;test han ben a greth lording,</L>
<L>&amp; honured als a kyng,</L>
<L N="513">&yogh;if it hadde ben &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>Nou hauest &thorn;ou had despit &amp; wrong</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine &thorn;ralles euere among,</L>
<L N="516">&amp; bor[e]n it ful stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas, who schal &yogh;iue to me</L>
<L>Welle of teres to wepe for &thorn;e</L>
<L N="519">Bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;th?</L>
<L>Allas allas, what me is wo!</L>
<L>I wolde myn herte it breke a-tuo</L>
<L N="522">&thorn;at I ne saye nowth &thorn;is sy&yogh;th."
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;anne cam for&thorn; a drery &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>I-clad in clo&thorn;es of mournyng,</L>
<L N="525">It was Alex wif;</L>
<L>Sche wep &thorn;at pite was to se</L>
<L>&amp; seyde: "Allas, ful wo is me,</L>
<L N="528">&thorn;at euere hadde I lyf!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou al my ioye awey is gon.</L>
<L>Er hadde I hope, now haue I non</L>
<L N="531">To sen him on lyue;</L>
<L>Nou am I wydewe, allas &thorn;at stounde!</L>
<L>Sorwe ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen myn herte a wounde</L>
<L N="534">&thorn;at me to de&thorn;e schal dryue.
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Allas! what is me to rede?</L>
<L>Mi mirour is broken &amp; is dede</L>
<L N="537">&thorn;at my liking was Inne.</L>
<L>hope of ioye now haue I lorn,</L>
<L>&amp; sorwe is newed me be-forn</L>
<L N="540">&thorn;at neuere more schal blynne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Al &thorn;at folk &thorn;at stod be-syde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at say &thorn;e sorwe so vn-ruyde,</L>
<L N="543">&thorn;ey wepe ful tendreliche;</L>
<L>&thorn;er ne was non &thorn;at my&yogh;tte him holde,</L>
<L>Man ne wif man, &yogh;ung ne old;</L>
<L N="546">&amp; &thorn;at nas no ferliche.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e pope com for&thorn;, &amp; te Emperours</L>
<L>Leten him bringe owt of &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L N="549">&amp; leyden him on a bere,</L>
<L>And beren wi&thorn; gret solempnete</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e mydeward of &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L N="552">&amp; cryeden &thorn;at alle my&yogh;ten here,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; seyden: "come&thorn;, se&thorn; &thorn;is holyman</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e han south euerichon!</L>
<L N="555">here he is in &thorn;is place;</L>
<L>ffounden he is, &amp; is here,</L>
<L>&thorn;at holy body on a bere,</L>
<L N="558">&thorn;oru help of godes grace."
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Alle &thorn;at wisten of &thorn;at cry,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ronne &thorn;ider hastifly,</L>
<L N="561">&amp; ne drou it nowt to abyd.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e sike &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>&thorn;at my&yogh;tte touche &thorn;e body &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;ei were hol als tyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e blynde, of him hadden here sy&yogh;th;</L>
<L>&thorn;e wode, here wyth hadde ful ry&yogh;th;</L>
<L N="567">&thorn;e halte, here lymes lele.</L>
<L>&thorn;er ne was non &thorn;at &thorn;ider my&yogh;te wynne,</L>
<L>What syknesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei were Inne,</L>
<L N="570">&thorn;at &thorn;ei ne hadde here hele.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Whan &thorn;e emperour him say &thorn;at won|der,</L>
<L>he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. ho]</NOTE> tok &thorn;e bere &amp; &yogh;ide &thorn;er-vnder,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e pope he wende,</L>
<L>ffor he wolde ben mad holy</L>
<L>&thorn;oru &thorn;e bering of &thorn;at body,</L>
<L N="576">he tok &thorn;e bere in hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// he let sowe in &thorn;e cyte</L>
<L>Gold &amp; siluer gret plente,</L>
<L N="579">&amp; &thorn;at was for &thorn;is skyl,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e folk scholde hem wi&thorn;drawe;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;at a-vaillede nat an hawe,</L>
<L N="582">&thorn;ey toke no tent &thorn;er-til.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ei preceden euere ner &amp; nerre,</L>
<L>fforto comen to &thorn;e bere</L>
<L N="585">&thorn;at &thorn;e corps lay Inne;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei preseden &thorn;erto wi&thorn; gret fors,</L>
<L>&thorn;at vnne&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;at holy cors</L>
<L N="588">To churche my&yogh;te &thorn;ei wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Whanne &thorn;ei comen to &thorn;e churche,</L>
<L>A toumbe of gold he leten wurche</L>
<L N="591">Wi&thorn; preciouse stones;</L>
<L>In seue dayes it was dy&yogh;th</L>
<L>fful richeliche al a-ry&yogh;th,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei leyden &thorn;er-inne &thorn;e bones.<MILESTONE N="237a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wan &thorn;at holy cors was leyd</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e toumbe richeliche I-grey|&thorn;ud</L>
<L N="597">Wi&thorn; ful meche honour:</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at were in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&thorn;er com owt &thorn;oru godes grace</L>
<L N="600">A ful swete odour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So swete ne smelde &thorn;ei neuere non,</L>
<L>Als so wyde as &thorn;ey hadden gon,</L>
<L N="603">Of no spiserye.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei worchipeden him alle wi&thorn; o stephne</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ankeden Iesu crist of heuene</L>
<L N="606">&amp; his moder Marye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Nou Iesu crist &thorn;oru &thorn;e preyer</L>
<L>of &thorn;at cors seint I tolde &yogh;ou her,</L>
<L N="609">&yogh;if &thorn;i wille it be,</L>
<L>Graunte vs alle god endyng,</L>
<L>And in heuene a wonying!</L>
<L N="612">Amen, par charite.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<DIV3 TYPE="manuscript"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20">
<HEAD>[<I>Laud MS.</I> 463, <I>leaf</I> 116.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEstene&thorn; alle &amp; herkene&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&yogh;ong &amp; olde, thewe &amp; freo,</L>
<L N="3">And I. &yogh;ou telle sone,</L>
<L>hou a &yogh;ong man, gent &amp; freo,</L>
<L>Bigan &thorn;e werldes wele to fleo,</L>
<L N="6">y-bore was in Rome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Rome was a doughty man,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was cleped Eufemyan,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="9">Man of mychel myghte;</L>
<L>Gold &amp; Siluer he hadde .y.-nouh,</L>
<L>Halles &amp; boures, oxen &amp; plouh,</L>
<L N="12">And wonder wel it dyghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor all &thorn;e seke of &thorn;e burhg</L>
<L>ffaste were y.-sough[t] &thorn;oruhg,</L>
<L N="15">&amp; brouht to his house.</L>
<L>he let hem bedde wel &amp; fede,</L>
<L>And to hem tok goed hede,</L>
<L N="18">him-self &amp; his spouse.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e man hadde a god wif,</L>
<L>She ne louede flyt ne stryf</L>
<L N="21">In al hire liue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sekemen ofte she fedde,</L>
<L>&amp; softe brou&yogh;t hem obedde,</L>
<L N="24">blessed beo she to wiue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;ei were to-gedere &yogh;eres two,</L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ei were somdel mo,</L>
<L N="27">With-outen any blede.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei bede god with herte gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hem sende suich a fode</L>
<L N="30">to serue hem &amp; drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Iesu Crist, &thorn;at is so mylde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;af hem grace, she was with chylde,</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;e gode lauedye.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e be day, &amp; be nyght,</L>
<L>&YOGH;erne &thorn;ei &thorn;onked our dright,</L>
<L N="36">&amp; Seinte Marie.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e child y.-bore was,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &thorn;onked Crist of his grace</L>
<L N="39">wi&thorn; glad chiere.</L>
<L>Also as &thorn;e wone was,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei coude with softe pas,</L>
<L N="42">to chirche &thorn;ei it bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o &thorn;is child to chirche com,</L>
<L>To afong Cristendom,</L>
<L N="45">as &thorn;e ryght is,</L>
<L>his fader &amp; his moder &thorn;o</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e bli&thorn;e were bo,</L>
<L N="48">&amp; cleped it Alexijs.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;ei nadde bot &thorn;ilk sone,</L>
<L>therfore as it is &thorn;e wone,</L>
<L N="51">&thorn;ei loued it &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he was old, &yogh;eres seuen,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei him wissed with mylde steuen,</L>
<L N="54">&amp; sette him to lore.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;is child wex &amp; wel they,</L>
<L>Cristes help him was ney,</L>
<L N="57">&amp; &thorn;at was wel y.-sene;</L>
<L>for more he lerned in on &yogh;er</L>
<L>&thorn;an any of his o&thorn;er fere</L>
<L N="60">dide in &yogh;eres tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// As sone as he vnderstod</L>
<L>Werldes blisse nas not god,</L>
<L N="63">Who it vnderstode,</L>
<L>Werldes wele he forsok,</L>
<L>&amp; to Iesu. Crist him tok,</L>
<L N="66">&thorn;at deyede on &thorn;e Rode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// he besought nyght &amp; day</L>
<L>heuen king, &thorn;at al wel may,</L>
<L N="69">&yogh;eue him strength &amp; mygh[t]e</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;e feond &thorn;at is aboute</L>
<L>to bring his soule in gret doute,</L>
<L N="72">gostliche to fighte.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his bone herde &thorn;e King of heuen,</L>
<L>&amp; spak to him wi&thorn; mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="75">&amp; seide, 'Alexijs,</L>
<L>To-day &thorn;ou may bli&thorn;e beo,</L>
<L>&thorn;i bone I. grante &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="78">&amp; a sete in heuen blisse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And .I. &thorn;e do to vnderstonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou most &thorn;ole shame &amp; shonde,</L>
<L N="81">al for my sake.</L>
<L>Into vnkou&thorn; lond &thorn;ou most wende,</L>
<L>Sone I. wile &thorn;e &thorn;ider sende,</L>
<L N="84">&amp; al &thorn;i kin forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Into vnkou&thorn; lond &thorn;ou shalt fare,</L>
<L>&amp; suffre myche tene &amp; care,</L>
<L N="87">&amp; al for loue myn;</L>
<L>&amp; sithen &thorn;ou shalt a&yogh;ein come,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i fader hous wone,</L>
<L N="90">&amp; &thorn;er-in haue goed fyn.'
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e childes fader fel in elde,</L>
<L>&amp; his moder godes helde</L>
<L N="93">&yogh;eres hadde fele.</L>
<L>he wold his sone shold wiue,</L>
<L>To glade hem in her liue,</L>
<L N="96">&amp; haue werldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ei sought hem sone a mayde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at witty was, as al folk sayde,</L>
<L N="99">comen of hy kinne.</L>
<L>Womman she was of heu bright,</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ouht on crist day &amp; nyht,</L>
<L N="102">&amp; kepte hir fro sinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ei wer to-gidere come,</L>
<L>&thorn;is maide &amp; &thorn;is &yogh;ong gom,</L>
<L N="105">In godes lawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere was game &amp; myche gleo,</L>
<L>Ac, for-so&thorn;e, tel I, &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="108">eyled him no plawe.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e day was go, &thorn;e nyht was com,</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;e fader to &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="111">wi&thorn; glad cher,</L>
<L>'vp arys, sone myn,</L>
<L>&amp; go into boure &thorn;yn,</L>
<L N="114">To glade &thorn;i fere.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o he com to boure to his fere,</L>
<L>he beheld &thorn;e may of glad chere,</L>
<L N="117">&amp; of bright hewe.</L>
<L>Sone menged his &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>In fonding he was brouht,</L>
<L N="120">his car began al newe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ne sy&yogh;te &amp; made sory chere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e teres out of his wete lere</L>
<L N="123">bitter he let falle.</L>
<L>Ne myht glade him his fere</L>
<L>with wordes ne with fair chere,</L>
<L N="126">&thorn;at stod shred in palle.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio">&para; No lenger to hele of he brak,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;ongman to his bride spak,</L>
<L N="129">with wel fair bere:</L>
<L>'Lemman, haue goday,</L>
<L>No lenger I ne may</L>
<L N="132">wi&thorn; &thorn;e leuen here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Wende I. mot fer of lond,</L>
<L>&amp; suffre tene &amp; peines strong,</L>
<L N="135">my sinnes to bete.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e I. mot, for godesake,</L>
<L>ffader &amp; moder myn forsak,</L>
<L N="138">&amp; &thorn;e &thorn;at art so suete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o she hadde herde &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>Al hir blis turned to bale,</L>
<L N="141">y.-swowe she fel to gronde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o she of swounyng ros,</L>
<L>Atterliche hir agros</L>
<L N="144">with care she was y-bound.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;o she myht stonde,</L>
<L>She tar hir heer, &amp; wrong hir hond,</L>
<L N="147">&amp; made reuful bere.</L>
<L>'Nou &thorn;ou wilt my lef of londe,</L>
<L>Loke I. may after &thorn;e long,</L>
<L N="150">Alas, &thorn;at I. ded nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Allas, mi lef, what hastou &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Iu myche care &thorn;ou hast me brouht,</L>
<L N="153">on me &thorn;ou hast sinne.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;ou art gon,</L>
<L>Vpbreid me tyt manyon</L>
<L N="156">of &thorn;i riche kinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Awey, mi lef, &thorn;at I. was bore,</L>
<L>ffor al my blisse is forlore,</L>
<L N="159">&amp; nou waxe&thorn; my pine.</L>
<L>Alone her-inne I. wile wone,</L>
<L>&amp; euere eft mannes mone shone,</L>
<L N="162">Al for loue &thorn;ine.'
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Lemman, al for &thorn;i sake,&mdash;</L>
<L>So do&thorn; &thorn;e turtel for hir make</L>
<L N="165">whan he is y.-slawe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Al myrthe I. wile forsake,</L>
<L>&amp; euere-more sorwe take,</L>
<L N="168">&amp; shone al plawe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he tok his girdel in his hond,</L>
<L>&amp; his mantel &thorn;erwi&thorn; he wond,</L>
<L N="171">&amp; his ring of golde.</L>
<L>'Mi lemman, haue &thorn;is to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er while &thorn;enk on me</L>
<L N="174">Whan I. lye vnder molde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gret wel fader &amp; modur myn,</L>
<L>leue her-inne, &amp; beo her hyne</L>
<L N="177">with wel milde mode.</L>
<L>&thorn;ilk lord .I. &thorn;e beteche,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is of alle bales leche,</L>
<L N="180">&amp; de&thorn; &thorn;oled on &thorn;e rode.'
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Out of bour he went anon,</L>
<L>As swi&thorn;e as he myht gon,</L>
<L N="183">Right to &thorn;e stronde.</L>
<L>Sone a ship he fond &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was redy to fare</L>
<L N="186">Into vnkou&thorn; lond.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Into &thorn;e ship anon he wend,</L>
<L>&amp; god suche wind sende</L>
<L N="189">&thorn;at sone to lond hem brouht.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ship was god, &thorn;e watur deope,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er while sore he wepe,</L>
<L N="192">&amp; was in gret &thorn;ouht.
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o he vp to londe com</L>
<L>he seld his clo&thorn;es euerichon,</L>
<L N="195">&amp; bou&yogh;t him pore wede;</L>
<L>And his gold &amp; his feo</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e pore delte he</L>
<L N="198">&thorn;at hadde mych neode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone he it vndernom,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he to a borugh com,</L>
<L N="201">&thorn;at mychel was &amp; kete.</L>
<L>Sone so he &thorn;ider com</L>
<L>to &thorn;e temple &thorn;e weye he nom,</L>
<L N="204">God selue to grete.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among &thorn;e pore he woned &thorn;ar</L>
<L>In sorwe &amp; in myche care,</L>
<L N="207">til he fel to elde.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>Ouht &thorn;at he spare myht</L>
<L>Be day, &amp; eke be nyht,</L>
<L N="210">his pore feren he delde.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e ti&thorn;ing was y.-com</L>
<L>To &thorn;e fader of &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="213">hou [he] was a-go,</L>
<L>him &thorn;ouht his herte wold to-breke,</L>
<L>On word ne myht he speke,</L>
<L N="216">for sorwe ne for wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte he sy&yogh;te, &amp; grente sore,</L>
<L>To tar his her, his lockes hore,</L>
<L N="219">&thorn;e gode old man.</L>
<L>&yogh;erne he gradde godes ore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne moste liue namor</L>
<L N="222">to swoune he began.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his moder wi&thorn; softe pas</L>
<L>went to bedde, &amp; gradde 'allas</L>
<L N="225">&thorn;at she was y.-bore.'</L>
<L>Nolde she neuere eft out-com,</L>
<L>&thorn;er she weope for hir sone,</L>
<L N="228">&thorn;at she hadde lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All &thorn;at &thorn;er-inne were</L>
<L>// hem-self drou&yogh; be &thorn;e her,</L>
<L N="231">&amp; wrong her hond;</L>
<L>Besou&yogh;te god, he shold hem ler,</L>
<L>To what lond he go wer,</L>
<L N="234">&amp; wher he wer astond.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his fader &amp; his moder bo,</L>
<L>ffor her sone wer wo,</L>
<L N="237">&thorn;at .I. ne may of telle.</L>
<L>fforto seke her sone,</L>
<L>In which lond he wer becom</L>
<L N="240">Men &thorn;ei sent snell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; It befel vpon a day,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e men nom her wey</L>
<L N="243">for&thorn; right be &thorn;e chirche;</L>
<L>&thorn;ere her lord nyht &amp; day</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e pore folk lay,</L>
<L N="246">Cristes will to wirche.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he knew hem, &amp; &thorn;ei not him,</L>
<L>Of her goed &thorn;ei &yogh;euen him,</L>
<L N="249">as it wolde falle.</L>
<L>he heried god, &amp; made him glad,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he for his loue hadde</L>
<L N="252">Almes of his thralle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out of &thorn;e bourgh &thorn;ei went sone,</L>
<L>to her lord &thorn;ei come</L>
<L N="255">wi&thorn; goed spede.</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;inges none &thorn;ei brouhte</L>
<L>Of his sone &thorn;at &thorn;ei soughte,</L>
<L N="258">In vnkou&thorn;e theode.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is &yogh;ongman woned hadd</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toun as a pore ladde</L>
<L N="261">&yogh;eres seuentene,</L>
<L>God wolde his care wende,</L>
<L>&amp; to his fader hous him send,</L>
<L N="264">to bring him out of teone.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>It befel in a nyght</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e mone shon bright,</L>
<L N="267">&thorn;e belleward him wend.</L>
<L>&thorn;e leme of heuen he sey aliht,</L>
<L>&amp; stonde vpe godes knyght,</L>
<L N="270">&thorn;at al &thorn;e chirche a-tende.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="117a" UNIT="folio">&para; Sone at morwe whan it was day,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he be &thorn;is man say,</L>
<L N="273">wide he it tolde.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e chirche &thorn;ei gonne teo</L>
<L>&thorn;ilk holy man to seo,</L>
<L N="276">Bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong &amp; olde.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;is holy man turned his thought,</L>
<L>worshipe of men kepte he nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="279">&thorn;at is frakel atte ende.</L>
<L>Out of bourgh he went anon,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e watur he com gon,</L>
<L N="282">&thorn;er-ouer he moste wende.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Into &thorn;e shipe he went a nyght,</L>
<L>Elles-whare &thorn;ei hadde tyght</L>
<L N="285">Into vnkou&thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei went fair swi&thorn;e ryght,</L>
<L>&amp; sone at morwe &thorn;o it was lyht</L>
<L N="288">At Rome &thorn;ei gonne astonde.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o he to londe come</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e toun he moste rome,</L>
<L N="291">his liflode to wynne.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>As he went &thorn;oruh &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>his oune fader he gan mete,</L>
<L N="294">As he com fro his inne.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o &thorn;e sone his fader mette,</L>
<L>Mildeliche he him grette,</L>
<L N="297">And bad him som gode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e godeman sone herd his bone,</L>
<L>for al his blod gan menge sone</L>
<L N="300">vpon his oune fode.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;et spak &thorn;is holy man</L>
<L>To his fader Eufemyan,</L>
<L N="303">wi&thorn; mylde mode:</L>
<L>'&thorn;at goed &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest do me,</L>
<L>Iesu Crist it &yogh;elde &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="306">&thorn;at diede on &thorn;e Rode;
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor if it is in &thorn;i mode</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast any fode,</L>
<L N="309">In vnkou&thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>Crist .I. beseke, par charite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wile to him seo</L>
<L N="312">wher he beo astonde.'
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o he spak of his sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e godeman, as it was his wone,</L>
<L N="315">Gan to sike sore.</L>
<L>his herte fel cold so stone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e teres fellen to his tone,</L>
<L N="318">Ouer his berd hore.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To his hous &thorn;e pore he broughte,</L>
<L>And a &yogh;ong man him betaughte</L>
<L N="321">to serue him to queme.</L>
<L>&thorn;ere he woned day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>&amp; serued god wi&thorn; al his myht,</L>
<L N="324">&yogh;eres &yogh;ette seuentene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Somme &thorn;at of &thorn;e in were</L>
<L>&thorn;e holymannes clo&thorn;es tere,</L>
<L N="327">&thorn;ere he lay in his bedde;</L>
<L>Ofte &thorn;ei drowe be &thorn;e here,</L>
<L>&amp; of broht &amp; watur cler</L>
<L N="330">&thorn;ei caste in his nebbe.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Ofte &thorn;ei him bete &amp; buste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e lord &thorn;er-of niste,</L>
<L N="333">&thorn;ese wikkede fode.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei clepeden him waste bred,</L>
<L>&amp; wissheden &thorn;at he wer ded,</L>
<L N="336">y.-wis &thorn;ei wer wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al &thorn;e shame &thorn;at he drey,</L>
<L>&thorn;e while he was his fader ney,</L>
<L N="339">he &thorn;olede with mylde mode.</L>
<L>And ofte to god he gan grede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he for&yogh;af her misdede,</L>
<L N="342">&amp; bringe hem to gode.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e while he was in &thorn;e house,</L>
<L>eche day he sey his spouse,</L>
<L N="345">his fader &amp; his moder.</L>
<L>Ac sone he tornede to &thorn;e wowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nere not y-knowe</L>
<L N="348">of hem ne of non o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;is holy man &thorn;ought &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at his lif was almest do</L>
<L N="351">ffor seknesse &thorn;at he hadde.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>parchemyn he &thorn;er wan,</L>
<L>&amp; al his lif wrot &thorn;er-on</L>
<L N="354">as he lay on bedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Also he wrot on his bok</L>
<L>hou he his &yogh;ong wif forsok,</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;o he of londe wolde;</L>
<L>hou his mantel he hire betok,</L>
<L>And his girdel he forsok,</L>
<L N="360">&amp; his ring of golde.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// It befel on a sonenday</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle men of cristes lay</L>
<L N="363">to &thorn;e chirche come;</L>
<L>Clerkes, knyghtes, &yogh;ong &amp; olde,</L>
<L>&thorn;emperour, wi&thorn; eorles bolde,</L>
<L N="366">&thorn;e pope self of Rome,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;o &thorn;ei &thorn;idere come were</L>
<L>to her, as &thorn;ei sholde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="369">Godes seruise,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei beden here bede;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e lift &thorn;ei herde grede,</L>
<L N="372">In wonder wise:
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Come&thorn; alle now to me,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sinful haue&thorn; .y.-beo,</L>
<L N="375">And afong &yogh;oure meode.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at haue&thorn; &thorn;olede pine,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e loue of me &amp; myne,</L>
<L N="378">I. &yogh;ou wile feode.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Of &thorn;is steuene hem &thorn;oughte wonder,</L>
<L>Many wende it were thonder,</L>
<L N="381">to gronde &thorn;ei gonne falle.</L>
<L>what &thorn;is cry betokne sholde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at god hem shewe wolde</L>
<L N="384">A kneo<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. keneo]</NOTE> &thorn;ei beden alle.
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Alle &thorn;at &thorn;er-inne were</L>
<L>Herde &yogh;et an no&thorn;er bere,</L>
<L N="387">Right about non.</L>
<L>'Go&thorn;, beseche&thorn; godes knyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at crist serue&thorn; day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;at he bidde for Rome.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e pope &amp; his clerkes alle<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Adoun on kneo &thorn;ei gon falle,</L>
<L N="393">Beforne &amp; behynde,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>And bede god Almyghty king</L>
<L>// &thorn;at he hem sende som tokenyng</L>
<L N="396">wher &thorn;ei myghte him fynd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iesu Crist, &thorn;at is so mylde,</L>
<L>Reuthe hadde of &thorn;is childe,</L>
<L N="399">&thorn;at is in care bounde.</L>
<L>To hem seide heuene spouse,</L>
<L>'Go&thorn; to Eufemianes house,</L>
<L N="402">&thorn;er he wor&thorn; y.-founde.'
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// After &thorn;is steuen vp &thorn;ei stod,</L>
<L>&amp; heried god wi&thorn; glad moed,</L>
<L N="405">Alle &thorn;at &thorn;ere were.</L>
<L>ffor nought &thorn;e pope was so gram,</L>
<L>Eufemian he vndernam</L>
<L N="408">wi&thorn; wel sterne bere:
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'wikke man, whi hastou hyd,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne moste er beo kyd,</L>
<L N="411">&thorn;e holy man!'</L>
<L>&thorn;e emperour began to chide,</L>
<L>&amp; fele o&thorn;er &thorn;at stode beside</L>
<L N="414">toward Eufemian.
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Na&thorn;eles wi&thorn; hem he &yogh;eode,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope &amp; many of &thorn;e theode,</L>
<L N="417">toward his hous &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope self &amp; &thorn;emperour</L>
<L>Sought halle, &thorn;ei souhte bour,</L>
<L N="420">so wel so &thorn;ei coude go;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;ei soughte him one stounde,</L>
<L>atte laste &thorn;ei him founde,</L>
<L N="423">&thorn;er he lay on bedde.</L>
<L>thoruh an hyne hem tolde be mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of his lyf mychel cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="426">And hem y-wissed hedde.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Beforen &thorn;e bed &thorn;ei stoden &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;emperour also;</L>
<L N="429">ac &thorn;ei ne dorste ouer him trine,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wende he wer liues man;</L>
<L>Ac his gost was out-gan,</L>
<L N="432">Brought he was of pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Eufemian adoun bey&yogh;,</L>
<L>his hond his neb he vnwrey</L>
<L N="435">wi&thorn; michel drede.</L>
<L>So suete smel of him tey&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;at wer ney&yogh;,</L>
<L N="438">wonder of him heuede.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Out of his mou&thorn; &thorn;er stoed a leom</L>
<L>Brighter &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne beom,</L>
<L N="441">&thorn;at al &thorn;e stede atende.</L>
<L>Adoun &thorn;ei fellen all on kneo,</L>
<L>to thanke god &thorn;at is so freo</L>
<L N="444">Of wonder &thorn;at he sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Toward god he gan his hondes holde,</L>
<L>A writ betwene &thorn;ei seye folde,</L>
<L N="447">&thorn;ei &thorn;at wer &thorn;er-inne.</L>
<L>Eufemian adoun bey&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ he drow &amp; &yogh;erne tey</L>
<L N="450">he ne myght it out-winne.
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e pope her-of was adred.</L>
<L>In his herte god he bad,</L>
<L N="453">&thorn;at him grante sholde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ &thorn;at was in his hond,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei myhte it vnderstond,</L>
<L N="456">betokne what it wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e pope to &thorn;e bed bey&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;e writ of his hond he tey&yogh;,</L>
<L N="459">Right wi&thorn;-outen gynne.</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ he began to sprede,</L>
<L>&amp; to foren &thorn;e folk to rede,</L>
<L N="462">&thorn;at weren &thorn;er-inne.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o eufemian was y-war</L>
<L>&thorn;at his sone lay &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="465">&amp; so long had wi&thorn; him beo,</L>
<L>he fel in swounyng on &thorn;e molde,</L>
<L N="468">'Allas,' he seide, '&thorn;at euer .I. sholde so vnkynde beo.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Be a stounde he gan vp-stonde,</L>
<L>Tar his her &amp; wrong his honde,</L>
<L N="471">&thorn;at &thorn;e folk myghte rewe.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei weopen &amp; made reuly cry,</L>
<L>for him &thorn;ei wer wel sory</L>
<L N="474">&thorn;at &thorn;ei him euere knewe.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Awey, lord, &thorn;at herest my bone,</L>
<L>whi helestou my leoue sone</L>
<L N="477">So long in my house,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wee ne moste him knowe,</L>
<L>And for&yogh;ete mychel wowe,</L>
<L N="480">bo&thorn;e .I. &amp; my spouse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// 'Awey, my sone, listou her,</L>
<L>&amp; euer .I. hoped of &thorn;e to here</L>
<L N="483">A-lyue &thorn;at &thorn;ou were.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; myn herte wile breke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I. ne may wi&thorn; &thorn;e speke.</L>
<L N="486">Allas, &thorn;at .I. ded nere.'
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e noyse into &thorn;e bour sprong</L>
<L>of &thorn;e sorwe was hem among,</L>
<L N="489">&thorn;at in &thorn;e halle were.</L>
<L>his moder was wel sory,</L>
<L>&amp; axed what were &thorn;at cry</L>
<L N="492">&thorn;at she herde wi&thorn; ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Of hir sone men tolde anon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at out while was y.-gon,</L>
<L N="495">&amp; hou he was y.-founde,</L>
<L>&amp; hou he hadde &thorn;er-inne woned,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is werldes blisse shoned,</L>
<L N="498">And tholed harde stounde.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o she herde of hir sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was a&yogh;ein come,</L>
<L N="501">out of bedde she sprong;</L>
<L>Al hir yuel she for&yogh;at,</L>
<L>And hardiliche held hir gate</L>
<L N="504">Al &thorn;at folk among.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// 'war anon, par charite,</L>
<L>Let me go my sone to seo,</L>
<L N="507">And myn oune fode.'</L>
<L>&thorn;e teres felle to hir kneo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at al &thorn;e folk myhte seo</L>
<L N="510">&thorn;e brest orn al o blode.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So sone so she to him come,<MILESTONE N="118a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e liche she fel y.-lome,</L>
<L N="513">And kiste it wel &yogh;erne.</L>
<L>she kist his neb, she kiste his hond,</L>
<L>on &thorn;e liche she lay, &amp; nolde not wond,</L>
<L N="516">Mighte noman hire werne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// 'Allas, my sone, my dere lyf,</L>
<L>Soriere nas neuere wif</L>
<L N="519">&thorn;an .I. am for &thorn;e nou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>ffor .I. hopede euer &thorn;e to seo,</L>
<L>Er .I. diede, &amp; speke wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="522">And kisse &thorn;e wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac Al myn hope is y.-lore,</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou list ded me before,</L>
<L N="525">&amp; wi&thorn; me ne myght speke.</L>
<L>Lord Crist, .I. bidde &thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>Ne let me liuen namore,</L>
<L N="528">ac let myn herte breke.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// She wrong hir hondes &amp; siked sore,</L>
<L>And to tar hire lokkes hore,</L>
<L N="531">As she were woed.</L>
<L>'Leoue sone, bidde .I. &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Let me dien nou wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="534">Mi lyf nis not goed.'
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;o com his wif,</L>
<L>&thorn;at louede him as hir lyf,</L>
<L N="537">To &thorn;e hous ago.</L>
<L>So sone so she com him to,</L>
<L>betwene hire armes she gan him fo,</L>
<L N="540">&amp; kissed his mou&thorn;e &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// 'Awey, my leof, what hastou do?</L>
<L>whi hastou holde &thorn;e so</L>
<L N="543">In &thorn;in oune house,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non ne most com &thorn;e to,</L>
<L>So freond au&yogh;te to o&thorn;er do,</L>
<L N="546">Ne .I. &thorn;at was &thorn;i spouse?
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// 'Allas, &thorn;at I. was woman bore,</L>
<L>Nou .I. haue &thorn;e forlore,</L>
<L N="549">My leof so hende.</L>
<L>Sorwefulliche me is dyght,</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou wi&thorn; me speke ne myht,</L>
<L N="552">I. ne recke whider to wende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// vp she stod beforn hem alle,</L>
<L>to drouh hir heer &amp; hir calle,</L>
<L N="555">as she were feye.</L>
<L>Bitter teres she let falle,</L>
<L>for hire &thorn;ei wer sory alle,</L>
<L N="558">&thorn;at hir wepe seye.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So mychel sorwe &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>Bot who-so hadde a tong of bras</L>
<L N="561">ne myghte it al telle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e day was almest do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;emperour also</L>
<L N="564">Might no lenger dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at liche &thorn;ei let wake &amp; shride,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pal &amp; wi&thorn; o&thorn;er pride,</L>
<L N="567">&thorn;at &thorn;ei founde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>wi&thorn; michel ioye &amp; hey song,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshopes hem alle among</L>
<L N="570">&thorn;e corps to chirche bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Amydde ryght &thorn;e heye strete</L>
<L>So mychel folk &thorn;ei gonne mete</L>
<L N="573">&thorn;at &thorn;ei most astonde.</L>
<L>&para; Alle seke &thorn;at to him come</L>
<L>y-helede were .y.-lome</L>
<L N="576">Of feet &amp; of honde.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e blynde come to her sight,</L>
<L>&thorn;e crokede gonne to righte,</L>
<L N="579">&thorn;e lame to go;</L>
<L>&thorn;at doumbe wer fonge speche,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei heried god, &thorn;e so&thorn;e leche,</L>
<L N="582">&amp; &thorn;e halwe also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// &thorn;e day &yogh;eode &amp; drouh to nyght,</L>
<L>No lenger dwelle &thorn;ei ne myght,</L>
<L N="585">to chirche &thorn;ei most wend.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bellen begonne to rynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;e clerkes forto singe,</L>
<L N="588">Euerich in his ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;ei to &thorn;e chirche cam,</L>
<L>Glad &thorn;ei were eche of ham</L>
<L N="591">&thorn;at &thorn;er-inne were.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;emperour</L>
<L>before &thorn;e auter of seint sauour</L>
<L N="594">sette &thorn;e bere.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Aboute &thorn;e ber was mychel lyght,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; fair pal it was betyght,</L>
<L N="597">&amp; wi&thorn; clo&thorn;es of golde.</L>
<L>fforto honour &thorn;is holy man,</L>
<L>of al &thorn;at lond folk &thorn;ider cam,</L>
<L N="600">&thorn;at fayn wake wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>// Alle seke &thorn;at &thorn;ere were,</L>
<L>As sone as &thorn;ei turned &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L N="603">hole &thorn;ei were anon</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e yuel &thorn;at &thorn;ei hedde,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei in &thorn;e nome bede</L>
<L N="606">of &thorn;is holy mon.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To chirche com &yogh;ong &amp; olde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at holy corps to beholde,</L>
<L N="609">&thorn;at &thorn;ider was .y.-brought.</L>
<L>A wel gentyl marbelston,</L>
<L>To louke inne his holy bon,</L>
<L N="612">Sone was y.-sought.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e thridde day was .y.-come,</L>
<L>So me dide &thorn;e londes wone,</L>
<L N="615">Men dide &thorn;e seruise.</L>
<L>&thorn;eder com more &amp; lasse,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope self song &thorn;e masse,</L>
<L N="618">wi&thorn;-outen feyntise.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e masse was y.-do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;emperour also,</L>
<L N="621">&thorn;e holy corps &thorn;ei kiste.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei nome &thorn;o &thorn;e holy bon,</L>
<L>&amp; leide it in a marbelston,</L>
<L N="624">y-loke in a chiste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;ilk &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>heried god wi&thorn; loude bere,</L>
<L N="627">&amp; crieden mercy,
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wonder &thorn;at he dide</L>
<L>In &thorn;e selue holy stede,</L>
<L N="630">ffor loue of Alexij.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Beseke we &yogh;erne &amp; ofte,<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ihesu &thorn;at vs deore boughte,</L>
<L N="633">&thorn;at he vs grace sende.</L>
<L>&thorn;at we mote him seruy,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of Alexij,</L>
<L N="636">To his blisse wende. AMEN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="manuscript"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="20">
<HEAD>[<I>Trin. Coll. MS., Oxf.</I>, 57 [81], <I>lf</I> 73.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vita Sancti Allexij.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lestene&thorn; alle, and herkene&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&yogh;onge and olde, bonde &amp; fre,</L>
<L N="3">And ich &yogh;ow telle sone,</L>
<L>How a &yogh;ong man, gent and fre,</L>
<L>By-gan &thorn;is worldis wele to fle:</L>
<L N="6">Y-born he was in Rome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In Rome was a do&yogh;ty man,<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at was y-clepud Eufemian.
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="9">Man of moche my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Gold and seluer he hadde y-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Halle and boures, oxse and plou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="12">And swi&thorn;e wel it dy&yogh;te,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e sike of &thorn;e borgh,</L>
<L>ffaste &thorn;e&yogh; were y-sou&yogh;t &thorn;orgh,</L>
<L N="15">And i-bro&yogh;t to his house;</L>
<L>&para; And set hem bedde wel &amp; fede,</L>
<L>And to hem toke guod hede,</L>
<L N="18">Him-selue &amp; eke his spouse.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is man hadde a wel guod wyf;</L>
<L>Hy ne louede fy&yogh;t ne stryf</L>
<L N="21">In al here lyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sike men wel ofte hy fedde,</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;te hem to hare bedde:</L>
<L N="24">I-blessed be hy to wyue!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hy were to-gyderes &yogh;eres two,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e&yogh; were somdel mo,</L>
<L N="27">With-oute eny blede.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&thorn;e&yogh; bede god with herte guode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hem sende such a fode,</L>
<L N="30">To seruy him &amp; drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And iesu crist, &thorn;at is so mylde,</L>
<L>Hem &yogh;af grace hy was with childe,</L>
<L N="33">&thorn;at guode Leuedye.</L>
<L>&para; Bothe be daye &amp; eke be ny&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Wel &yogh;erne hy &thorn;onkede oure dry&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="36">And so hy dede Marie.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;is child y-bore was,</L>
<L>Crist &thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;onkede of &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L N="39">With wel glade chere.</L>
<L>Al-so as &thorn;e wone was,</L>
<L>As hy cou&thorn;e with softe pas</L>
<L N="42">&thorn;at child to cherche bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is child to cherche com,</L>
<L>To vnderfonge cristendom,</L>
<L N="45">As ri&yogh;t it is,</L>
<L>His fader &amp; his moder bo,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e blithe were &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="48">And clepude it 'allexis.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hy nadde bote &thorn;at ilke sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore, as it is &thorn;e wone,</L>
<L N="51">Hy louede him &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o he was old &yogh;eres seuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e&yogh; wissede him with mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="54">And sette him to lore<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. sore]</NOTE>.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is child wax, and wel y-&thorn;e&yogh;,</L>
<L>Cristis help him was ne&yogh;,</L>
<L N="57">And &thorn;at was wel y-sene;</L>
<L>ffor more he lernede<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. sernede]</NOTE> in one &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;an eny of his o&thorn;ere fere</L>
<L N="60">Dede in &yogh;eres tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor sone &thorn;is child him vnderstod</L>
<L>&thorn;is worldis blisse was no&yogh;t guod,</L>
<L N="63">&thorn;e man &thorn;at him vnderstode,</L>
<L>Worldes wele he forsoke,</L>
<L>And to iesu crist him toke,</L>
<L N="66">&thorn;at do was on &thorn;e rode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He by-so&yogh;te ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>Heuene kynge, &thorn;at al &thorn;ynge may,</L>
<L N="69">He &yogh;eue him streng&thorn;e &amp; my&yogh;te</L>
<L>&para; A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fend &thorn;at is a-boute,</L>
<L>To brynge vs in euel route,</L>
<L N="72">Gostlich to fy&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His bone y-herde &thorn;e kynge of heuene,</L>
<L>And spake to him with mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="75">And seyde, 'allexis,</L>
<L>To-day &thorn;ou my&yogh;t wel bly&thorn;e be,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;yne bone ich granty &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="78">And my blessynge y-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And ich &thorn;e do wel to vnderstonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou most &thorn;olye shame &amp; shonde,</L>
<L N="81">Al for myne sake.</L>
<L>Into vncou&thorn;e londe &thorn;ou most wende,</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;uder ich wil &thorn;e sende,</L>
<L N="84">And al &thorn;y ken forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In-to vncou&thorn; lond &thorn;ou most fare,<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And soffry moche tene &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="87">Al for sone myne.</L>
<L>&para; And su&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou shelt a-&yogh;e come,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;y fader hous [shalt] wone,</L>
<L N="90">And &thorn;er-ynne fyne.'
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="27"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is childis fader fel on elde,</L>
<L>And his moder godis helde,</L>
<L N="93">&yogh;eres hadde fele.</L>
<L>Hy wolde here sone sholde wyue,</L>
<L>To gladen hem in &thorn;is lyue,</L>
<L N="96">And haue worldis wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hy by-so&yogh;ten him a mayde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at witty was and ful of rede,</L>
<L N="99">I-come of he&yogh;e kenne;</L>
<L>Woman hy was of hewe bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hy &thorn;o&yogh;te on crist day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="102">And wiste here fro senne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor &thorn;o hy were to-gydere y-come,</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde and &thorn;is &yogh;onge gome,</L>
<L N="105">In godis lawe,</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;er was game and moche gle,</L>
<L>Ac, al for-so&thorn;e ich telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="108">Ne eysede hem no plawe.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e day was go, &thorn;e ny&yogh;t was come;</L>
<L>&thorn;o seyde &thorn;e fader to &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="111">With wel glade chere,</L>
<L>'Op arys, &thorn;ou sone myn,</L>
<L>And go [&thorn;ou] in-to boure &thorn;yn,</L>
<L N="114">To glady &thorn;yne fere.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o he was in-to boure y-bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He by-held &thorn;at may swa&thorn;el &amp; to&yogh;t</L>
<L N="117">Of bri&yogh;te hywe.</L>
<L>Sone turnde he his &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In fondynge he was y-bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="120">His care be-gan al nywe;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He si&yogh;te, &amp; made sorweful chere,</L>
<L>Teres ouer his whyte lere</L>
<L N="123">Bytere he let falle.</L>
<L>&para; Ne my&yogh;te him gladye his fere,</L>
<L>With wordes ne with fayre chere,</L>
<L N="126">&thorn;at stod y-shrud in palle;
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o it alles op a brake,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;onge man to his brede spake,</L>
<L N="129">With wel fayre bere:</L>
<L>'Leman, haue guod day,</L>
<L>No lenger ich ne may</L>
<L N="132">With &thorn;e by sene here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wende ich mot fer out of londe,</L>
<L>And soffry tene &amp; peynes stronge,</L>
<L N="135">My synnes to bete.</L>
<L>Bothe ich mot, for godis sake,</L>
<L>ffader &amp; moder myne forsake,</L>
<L N="138">And &thorn;e &thorn;at art so swete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o hy hadde y-herd &thorn;e tale,</L>
<L>Hire blesse turnde to bale,</L>
<L N="141">A-swo&yogh;e hy fel to grounde.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o hy of swo&yogh;enynge a-ros,</L>
<L>Wel sore here a-gros,</L>
<L N="144">With care hy was y-bounde.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone so hy my&yogh;te op-stonde,</L>
<L>Hy tar here her, &amp; wrang here honde,</L>
<L N="147">And made reuful bere:</L>
<L>'Now &thorn;ou wilt lef out of londe,</L>
<L>Loky ich may after &thorn;e longe;</L>
<L N="150">Allas! &thorn;at ich ded nere!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas my lef! what hast &thorn;ou &thorn;o&yogh;t?</L>
<L>In moche care ich am y-bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="153">Of me &thorn;ou hast synne.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;ou art a-gon,</L>
<L>Op breyde me tyt of manyon,</L>
<L N="156">Of &thorn;yne riche kynne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-wey my lef, &thorn;at ich was y-bore,</L>
<L>ffor al my blisse is for-lore,</L>
<L N="159">And now wexe&thorn; my pyne.</L>
<L>&para; Allone her-ynne ich wille wonye,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio">And euere eft mannes mone shonye,</L>
<L N="162">Al for loue &thorn;yne.'
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Leman, al for &thorn;yne sake,&mdash;</L>
<L>So do&thorn; &thorn;e drake for here make,</L>
<L N="165">Whanne he is a-slawe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Alle merthe ich wille forsake,</L>
<L>And euere-more sorwe take,</L>
<L N="168">And shonye alle plawe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He nam his gerdul on his hond,</L>
<L>And his mantel &thorn;er-on he wond,</L>
<L N="171">And his ryng of golde.</L>
<L>'My leman, haue now &thorn;is to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er whyle &thorn;enk on me,</L>
<L N="174">whanne ich ligge vnder molde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gret wel fader &amp; moder myn,</L>
<L>By-lef her-ynne, &amp; serue him</L>
<L N="177">With wel mylde mode.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;ulke lord ich &thorn;e by-teche,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is of alle bale leche,</L>
<L N="180">&thorn;at de&thorn; &thorn;olede on rode.'
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out of &thorn;e borgh he wente anon,</L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e so he my&yogh;te gon</L>
<L N="183">Ry&yogh;t to-ward &thorn;e stronde;</L>
<L>Sone a schip he fond &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was redy to fare</L>
<L N="186">In-to vncou&thorn;e londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In-to &thorn;e schip anon he wente,</L>
<L>And god wel sone such a wynd sente,</L>
<L N="189">&thorn;at to &thorn;e lond hem bro&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;at schip was guod, &thorn;at water dep,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er whyle sore he wep,</L>
<L N="192">And was in moche &thorn;o&yogh;te;
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o he in-to &thorn;e lond com,</L>
<L>He solde his clo&thorn;es euerichon,</L>
<L N="195">And bo&yogh;te him pouere wede.</L>
<L>&para; Al his gold and al his fe,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e pouere delte he,</L>
<L N="198">&thorn;at hadde moche nede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone he it vnder-nom,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he to one borgh com,</L>
<L N="201">&thorn;at moche was &amp; kete.</L>
<L>Sone so he &thorn;uder com,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e temple he wente anon,</L>
<L N="204">God self to grete.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Among &thorn;e pouere he wonede &thorn;are,</L>
<L>In moche sorwe and moche care,</L>
<L N="207">ffor-to he fel to elde.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he spelye my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Be daye and ek be ny&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="210">His pouere feren he delde.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e tydynge was y-come</L>
<L>To &thorn;e fader of &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="213">How he was a-go,</L>
<L>&para; Him &thorn;o&yogh;te his herte wolde breke,</L>
<L>O lepy word he ne my&yogh;te speke,</L>
<L N="216">ffor sorwe and for wo;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte he si&yogh;te &amp; grente sore,</L>
<L>To tar his shroud, his lokkes hore,</L>
<L N="219">&thorn;e guode olde man.</L>
<L>&yogh;erne he gradde godis ore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne moste lyue namore;</L>
<L N="222">To swo&yogh;eny he be-gan.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His moder with wel softe pas</L>
<L>Wente to bedde, &amp; gradde, 'allas,</L>
<L N="225">&thorn;at hy was y-bore.'</L>
<L>Nolde hy neuere eft out-come,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ere hy wep for here sone,</L>
<L N="228">&thorn;at hy hadde for-lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;er-ynne were,</L>
<L>Hem-selue drowe by &thorn;e here,</L>
<L N="231">And wronge hare honde.</L>
<L>&para; Be-so&yogh;te god &thorn;at sholde hem lere,</L>
<L>To what londe &thorn;at he were,</L>
<L N="234">And where he were a-stonde.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His fader &amp; his moder bo,</L>
<L>ffor hare sone were ful wo,</L>
<L N="237">&thorn;at ich ne may al telle.</L>
<L>ffor to sechen hare sone,</L>
<L>In what londe he were by-come,</L>
<L N="240">&yogh;onge men he sente snelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; It by-fel opon a day,<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;onge men nome hare way</L>
<L N="243">ffor&thorn; ri&yogh;t by &thorn;e cherche</L>
<L>&thorn;ere hare lord ny&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e pouere folk lay,</L>
<L N="246">Cristis wille to werche.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hem knew, and hy no&yogh;t him;</L>
<L>Of hare guode hy &yogh;eue him,</L>
<L N="249">As it wolde falle.</L>
<L>&para; He herede god, and made him glad,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he for his sone bad</L>
<L N="252">Almesse of &thorn;ralle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out of &thorn;e borgh hy wente sone</L>
<L>To here lord til &thorn;at &thorn;e&yogh; come</L>
<L N="255">with wel guode spede.</L>
<L>Tydynges none hy ne bro&yogh;te</L>
<L>Of his sone, &thorn;at him so&yogh;te</L>
<L N="258">In vncou&thorn;e &thorn;ede.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is &yogh;onge man y-woned hadde</L>
<L>In toune as a pouere ladde,</L>
<L N="261">&yogh;eres seuentene,</L>
<L>God self wolde his care wende,</L>
<L>And to his fader him sende,</L>
<L N="264">And bringe him of tene.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>It by-fel in one ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e mone shon swy&thorn;e bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="267">&thorn;e belward hym by-wende.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e leome of heuene he se&yogh; a li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And stonde ope godis kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="270">&thorn;at al &thorn;e cherche attende.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone amorwe, so it was day,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he by &thorn;is manne i-say,</L>
<L N="273">Wyde he it tolde.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e cherche hy gonne teo,</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy man for to seo,</L>
<L N="276">Bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;is holy man turnde his &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Herynge of man ne kepte he no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="279">&thorn;at frel is atte ende.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e borgh he wente anon,</L>
<L>To a water til &thorn;at he com,</L>
<L N="282">&thorn;er-ouer he moste wende.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In-to &thorn;e schip he wente any&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor elles-whar he hadde i-dy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="285">In-to vncou&thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>&para; He wende fare swi&thorn;e ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac sone amorwe &thorn;o it was li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="288">At Rome hy gonne a-stonde.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o he in-to &thorn;e lond com,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e toune he moste gon,</L>
<L N="291">His lyflode to wynne.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>As he wente &thorn;orgh &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>His owene fader he gan mete,</L>
<L N="294">As he com fram his ynne.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e sone his fader mette,</L>
<L>Wel myldeliche he him grette,</L>
<L N="297">And bad him of his guode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e guode man grantede his bone,</L>
<L>ffor al his blod gan menge sone</L>
<L N="300">Ope his owene fode.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor &yogh;ut him spak &thorn;e holy man</L>
<L>To his fader Eufemian,</L>
<L N="303">With wel mylde mode:</L>
<L>&para; '&thorn;at guod &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest do me,</L>
<L>Iesu crist it &yogh;elde &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="306">&thorn;at deyde on &thorn;e rode.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor &yogh;if it is in &thorn;yne mode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hauest eny fode,</L>
<L N="309">In vncou&thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>Crist ich by-seche par charite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wel to him by se,</L>
<L N="312">Wher &thorn;at he be a-stonde.'
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So sone so he spak of his sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e guode man, as was his wone,</L>
<L N="315">Gan to sike sore.</L>
<L>His herte fel so cold so ston,</L>
<L>&thorn;e teres felle to his ton,</L>
<L>Ouer his berd hore.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio">To his house &thorn;e pouere he bro&yogh;te;</L>
<L>One &yogh;onge man him be-to&yogh;te</L>
<L N="321">To seruy him to queme.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;ere he wonede day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And seruede god with al his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="324">&yogh;eres &yogh;ut seuentene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Some of &thorn;o &thorn;er-ynne were</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy mannes clothes tere,</L>
<L N="327">&thorn;ere hy le&yogh;e on his bedde.</L>
<L>Ofte hy drowe him by &thorn;e here,</L>
<L>And of water and of bro&thorn; him bere,</L>
<L N="330">And caste in his nebbe.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ofte hy him bete and burste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e lord &thorn;er-of nuste,</L>
<L N="333">&thorn;o vnlede fode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e&yogh; clepude him 'waste bred,'</L>
<L>And weste &thorn;at he wer ded;</L>
<L N="336">I-wis hy wer wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;e shame &thorn;at he dre&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyle he wonede his fader ne&yogh;,</L>
<L N="339">He &thorn;olede with mylde mode.</L>
<L>&para; And ofte to god he gan grede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he for-&yogh;eue hem hare mysdede,</L>
<L N="342">And bro&yogh;te hem to guode.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e whyle he wonede in &thorn;e house,</L>
<L>Eche day he se&yogh; his spouse,</L>
<L N="345">His fader &amp; his moder.</L>
<L>Ac sone he wente him to &thorn;e wowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he neuere nere y-knowe</L>
<L N="348">Of hem ne of non o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e holy man him &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at his lyf was almest ydo,</L>
<L N="351">ffor siknesse &thorn;at he hadde.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>Parchemyn he him wan,</L>
<L>And al his lyf wrot &thorn;er-an,</L>
<L N="354">As he lay in his bedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al he wrot opon his bok,</L>
<L>How he his &yogh;onge wyf forsok,</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;o he of londe wolde.</L>
<L>How he his mantel here by-tok,</L>
<L>And his gerdel &thorn;at was so guod,</L>
<L N="360">And a ryng of golde.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;at fel opon a soneday,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle men of cristis lay</L>
<L N="363">To &thorn;e cherche come,</L>
<L>Clerkes, kny&yogh;tes, &yogh;onge &amp; olde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e emperour with his erles bolde,</L>
<L N="366">&thorn;e Pope self of Rome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o hy &thorn;uder y-come were,</L>
<L>To here al so hy sholde &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="369">Hare seruise.</L>
<L>Al so hy hare bedes bede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e luft hy herde grede,</L>
<L N="372">In a wonder wise:
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Come&thorn; alle now to me,</L>
<L>&thorn;at synful haue&thorn; for me y-be,</L>
<L N="375">And a-fonge&thorn; &yogh;oure mede.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at haue&thorn; y-&thorn;oled pyne,</L>
<L>Honger and &thorn;erst for loue myne,</L>
<L N="378">Ich &yogh;ow wille fede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of &thorn;is steuene hem &thorn;o&yogh;te wonder;</L>
<L>ffele wende it were &thorn;onder;</L>
<L N="381">To gronde hy gonne falle.</L>
<L>What &thorn;is cry be-tokny sholde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at god hem sone schewy wolde,</L>
<L N="384">A-kneo hy beden alle.
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;at &thorn;er-ynne were,</L>
<L>I-herde &yogh;ut ano&thorn;er bere,</L>
<L N="387">Ri&yogh;t aboute none:</L>
<L>'Go&thorn;, by-sechest godis kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at crist serue&thorn; day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="390">&thorn;at he bidde for Rome.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e Pope and his clerkes alle</L>
<L>A-doun on kneo gonne falle,</L>
<L N="393">By-fore &amp; ek be-hynde,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>&para; And bede god almy&yogh;ty kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hem sende som toknyng</L>
<L N="396">Wher &thorn;orgh hy my&yogh;te him fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iesu crist, &thorn;at is so mylde,<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ruthe hadde of &thorn;is childe,</L>
<L N="399">&thorn;at was in care y-bounde.</L>
<L>To hem he seyde, &thorn;e heuene spouse,</L>
<L>'Go&thorn; to Eufemia[ne]s house,</L>
<L N="402">&thorn;ere he wor&thorn; y-founde.'
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; After &thorn;is steuene, op hy stode,</L>
<L>And herede god with glade mode,</L>
<L N="405">Alle &thorn;at &thorn;er were.</L>
<L>ffor no&yogh;t &thorn;e Pope was ful gram,</L>
<L>Eufemian he vnder-nam,</L>
<L N="408">With wel sterne bere:
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'O lu&thorn;er man, why hastow y-hud</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne moste er be y-kud,</L>
<L N="411">&thorn;ulke holy man?'</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e emperour be-gan to chyde,</L>
<L>And fele &thorn;at &thorn;er stode be-syde,</L>
<L N="414">To-ward Eufemian.
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Na&thorn;eles, with him hy &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope, and manye of hare dede</L>
<L N="417">To-ward &thorn;is house.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope self and &thorn;e emperour,</L>
<L>Hy so&yogh;te halle, hy so&yogh;te bour,</L>
<L N="420">So wel so hy cou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hy so&yogh;te him one stounde,</L>
<L>Ac atte laste hy him founde,</L>
<L N="423">&thorn;er he lay in his bedde,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh an hyne of the house,</L>
<L>&thorn;at moche of his lyf cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="426">&thorn;at hem y-wissed hedde.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By-fore &thorn;e bed hy stode &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope and &thorn;e emperour al-so,</L>
<L N="429">Ac hy ne dorste hem tryne.</L>
<L>Hy wende he were a lyues man,</L>
<L>Ac his gost was out a-gon,</L>
<L N="432">I-bro&yogh;t he was of pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eufemian a-doun bei&yogh;,</L>
<L>His neb, his hondes, he vn-wrei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="435">With wel mochel drede.</L>
<L>So swote bre&thorn; out of him tei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;at wer &thorn;er nei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="438">&thorn;er-of wonder hauede.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Out of his mouth stod a lem</L>
<L>Bri&yogh;ter &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne-bem,</L>
<L N="441">&thorn;at al &thorn;e stede atende.</L>
<L>A-doun hy felle, alle on kneo,</L>
<L>To &thorn;onky god &thorn;at is so freo</L>
<L N="444">Of wonder &thorn;at hem sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Op to-ward god held his honde;</L>
<L>A writ be-twixe hy se&yogh;e y-folde,</L>
<L N="447">Hy &thorn;at wer &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>Eufemian a-doun bei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ he drou&yogh; &amp; &yogh;erne tei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="450">Ne my&yogh;te he it wynne.
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e Pope her-of was a-drad,</L>
<L>In his herte, god he bad,</L>
<L N="453">&thorn;at him granty sholde</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ &thorn;at was in his honde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;te it vnderstonde,</L>
<L N="456">Be-tokny what it wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e Pope to &thorn;e dede bei&yogh;;</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ out of his hond he tei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="459">Al with-oute gynne.</L>
<L>&thorn;at writ anon he gan sprede,</L>
<L>And by-fore hem alle rede,</L>
<L N="462">&thorn;at &thorn;o wer &thorn;erynne.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o sir Eufemian was y-war</L>
<L>&thorn;at his sone lay &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="465">His armes he to-spradde,</L>
<L>He tar his her, he tar his clo&thorn;,</L>
<L>And fel a-swo&yogh;e opon &thorn;e cors,</L>
<L N="468">So moche sorwe he hadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By a stounde he gan op-stonde,</L>
<L>To-tar his her &amp; wrang his honde,</L>
<L N="471">&thorn;at alle folk mi&yogh;te rewe;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio">He wep and made reuful cry;</L>
<L>ffor him hy were wel sory,</L>
<L N="474">&thorn;at he him er ne knewe.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "A-wey, lord, &thorn;at art vs a-boue,</L>
<L>Why hele &thorn;ou my leue sone?</L>
<L N="477">To longe in myn house,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we ne moste him y-knowe,</L>
<L>And for-&yogh;ute oure wowe,</L>
<L N="480">And kesse him with mou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A-wey, my sone, now listow here,</L>
<L>And euere ich hopede of &thorn;e y-here,</L>
<L N="483">A-lyue &thorn;at &thorn;ou were.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; my herte wil breke,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;t with me speke,</L>
<L N="486">A-wey &thorn;at ded y-nere."
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e drem in-to &thorn;e bour sprong,</L>
<L>Of sorwe &thorn;at hem was among,</L>
<L N="489">&thorn;at in &thorn;e halle were.</L>
<L>His moder lay &thorn;ere wel sory,</L>
<L>And axste what were al &thorn;at cry</L>
<L N="492">&thorn;at hy herde with ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of here sone me tolde anon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at out whyle was a-gon,</L>
<L N="495">And how he was y-founde;</L>
<L>And how he hadde &thorn;er-ynne y-woned,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is worldis blesse y-shoned,</L>
<L N="498">And &thorn;olede wel harde stounde.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o hy herde of here sone,</L>
<L>How he was a&yogh;en y-come,</L>
<L N="501">Of here bedde hy sprong;</L>
<L>Al hyre euel hy for-&yogh;at,</L>
<L>And hardeliche a-doun stap,</L>
<L N="504">&thorn;e folk alle among:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Reme&thorn; me, for godis lone,</L>
<L>And lete&thorn; me go to my sone,</L>
<L N="507">I se myn owene fode.'</L>
<L>&thorn;e teres felle to here kneo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at al &thorn;at folk my&yogh;te wel y-seo,</L>
<L N="510">Hire brest al a-blode.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So sone &thorn;o hy to him com,</L>
<L>Ope &thorn;e lich hy fel anon,</L>
<L N="513">And keste it wel &yogh;erne;</L>
<L>Hy keste his neb and his honde,</L>
<L>Ope &thorn;e lich hy lay wel longe,</L>
<L N="516">Hire ne my&yogh;te noman werne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "A-wey, my sone, &thorn;ou were my lyf!</L>
<L>Sorwere nas y-neuere wyf,</L>
<L N="519">&thorn;an ich am for &thorn;e nou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>ffor euere ich hopede &thorn;e to seo,</L>
<L>Er ich deye, and speke with &thorn;eo,</L>
<L N="522">And kesse &thorn;e with mou&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac al myn hope is y-lore,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou list ded me by-fore,</L>
<L N="525">And with me ne my&yogh;t speke.</L>
<L>'Lord crist, ich bidde &thorn;yn ore,</L>
<L>Ne let &thorn;ou me lyue namore,</L>
<L N="528">Ac let myn herte breke."'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hy wrang here hond, and si&yogh;te sore,</L>
<L>To-tar here shroud, here lokkes hore,</L>
<L N="531">As hy were wod.</L>
<L>'Leue sone, by-seche ich &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou lete me deye now byfore &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="534">&thorn;e lyf me nis no&yogh;t guod.'
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;er-after com his wyf,</L>
<L>&thorn;at louede him more &thorn;an here lyf,</L>
<L N="537">In-to &thorn;ulke house.</L>
<L>So sone so hy com him to,</L>
<L>Be-twixe here armes hy gan him fo,</L>
<L N="540">And keste him with mou&thorn;e;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "A-wey! my lef, what hastow y-do?</L>
<L>Why hastow &thorn;e y-heled so,</L>
<L N="543">In &thorn;yn owene house,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou ne woldest come me to,</L>
<L>So frend o&yogh;te to o&thorn;er do,</L>
<L N="546">Ne ich &thorn;at was &thorn;y spouse?
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio">&para; A-wey, &thorn;at ich was woman y-bore,</L>
<L>Now ich haue &thorn;e for-lore,</L>
<L N="549">My leman so hende.</L>
<L>Sorweful is me y-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou with me speke ne my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="552">Ne reiche ich whyder to wende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of hy stod by-fore hem alle,</L>
<L>To-drou&yogh; here her, and here calle,</L>
<L N="555">As hy were vei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Bytere teres hy let falle,</L>
<L>ffor hire were sory alle,</L>
<L N="558">&thorn;at here wepe y-sei&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So moche sorwe &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>Bote who-so hadde a tonge of bras,</L>
<L N="561">Ne my&yogh;te he it telle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e day him was al-mest y-do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope and &thorn;e emperour al-so</L>
<L N="564">Ne my&yogh;te lenger dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;at lich hy lete by-wake, and shrude</L>
<L>With palle and with o&thorn;er prude,</L>
<L N="567">&thorn;at hy founde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>With mochel li&yogh;t, and mochel song,</L>
<L>&thorn;at holy cors hem alle among,</L>
<L N="570">Bischoppis to cherche bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amyddes ri&yogh;t &thorn;e he&yogh;e strete,</L>
<L>So moche folk hy gonne mete,</L>
<L N="573">&thorn;at hy resten a stounde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e sike &thorn;at to him come,</L>
<L>I-heled were swi&thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="576">Of fet and ek of honde.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e blynde come to har si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;e crokede gonne sone ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="579">&thorn;e lame for to go;</L>
<L>&thorn;at dombe were fenge speche,</L>
<L>&thorn;e&yogh; herede god, &thorn;e so&thorn;e leche,</L>
<L N="582">And &thorn;at halwe al-so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e day &yogh;ede, and drou&yogh; to-ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No lenger dwelle hy ne my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="585">To cherche hy moste wende;</L>
<L>&thorn;e bellen hy gonne to rynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;e clerkes he&yogh;e to synge,</L>
<L N="588">Euerich in his ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e cors to cherche com,</L>
<L>Glad hy were euerichon,</L>
<L N="591">&thorn;at &thorn;er-ynne were.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope and &thorn;e emperour,</L>
<L>By-fore an auter of seint sauour,</L>
<L N="594">&para; &thorn;er sette by &thorn;e bere.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-boute &thorn;e bere was moche li&yogh;t;</L>
<L>With proude palle was be-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="597">I-beten al with golde.</L>
<L>ffor to worschipe &thorn;is man,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at lond folk &thorn;uder cam,</L>
<L N="600">&thorn;at cors by-wake wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;e sike &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>As sone as hy touchede &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L N="603">Hol hy were anon</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e euel &thorn;at hy hadde,</L>
<L>&yogh;if hy in &thorn;e name badde</L>
<L N="606">Of &thorn;is holy man.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To cherche come &yogh;onge &amp; olde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at holy cors to by-holde</L>
<L N="609">&thorn;at &thorn;uder was y-bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A wel gentel marbel ston,</L>
<L>To louke in his holy bon,</L>
<L N="612">Sone was by-so&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day was y-come,</L>
<L>So it is &thorn;e londis wone,</L>
<L N="615">Me dude &thorn;e seruyse;</L>
<L>&thorn;uder come more and lasse,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope self song &thorn;e masse,</L>
<L N="618">With herte wel bly&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e masse was y-do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Pope and &thorn;e emperour al-so,</L>
<L N="621">&thorn;at holy cors hy kiste.</L>
<L>Hy nome &thorn;e holy man,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And leyde him in &thorn;e marbel ston,</L>
<L N="624">By-loke in one chiste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;ulke &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>Herede god with loude bere,</L>
<L N="627">And cride him mercy,
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wondres &thorn;at he dude</L>
<L>&thorn;o in &thorn;at ilke holy stude,</L>
<L N="630">ffor loue of allexi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By-seche we &thorn;anne, &yogh;erne &amp; ofte,</L>
<L>Crist self &thorn;at vs dere bo&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="633">&thorn;at his grace vs sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we mote him seruy,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of allexi,</L>
<L N="636">To his blesse wende. Amen.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="[80]">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
