<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000083.tif" N="81">
<HEAD>King Solomon's Book of Wisdom,</HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P>A BOOK OF MORAL PRECEPTS AND PRACTICAL ADVICE (lines 1-105),</P><P><I>Taken from the Laud MS. 622's headless rymed Bible Story, and followd by the end of that Story, an account of</I><LIST>
<ITEM>1 King SOLOMON'S love of Lechery, p. 85, l. 107-111. (For his Coronation, his Judgment on the Child claimd by 2 Mothers, and his Wisdom, &amp;c., see p. 96-8);</ITEM>
<ITEM>2 of his son REHOBOAM, l. 113-131; and the separation of the Kingdoms of Judah and Israel, 132-146; p. 85-86;</ITEM>
<ITEM>3 legends of the prophet ELIJAH, 150; his raising the prophet Jonah<NOTE PLACE="foot">That Jonah was the son of the widow of Zarephath is in the Midrash Yalq&ucirc;t (a legendary Commentary on the Old Testament, called Yalq&ucirc;t) to the book Jonah, quoted from the Talmud of Jerusalem.&mdash;A. Neubauer.</NOTE> (the widow of Zarephath's son, 1 Kings xvii. 17) to life, 156-65; going to Horeb, 166-73; his choosing Elisha, 174-7; burning up king Ahaziah's messengers (2 Kings i. 10-12), 178-199; and going to heaven in a fiery horse and cart (2 Kings ii. 11), 200-213; p. 86-88;</ITEM>
<ITEM>4 of ELISHA, his purifying a well with salt, 214-225 (2 Kings ii. 19-22); and multiplying a poor woman's oil, 226-233 (2 Kings iv. 1-3); p. 88;</ITEM>
<ITEM>5 of DANIEL in the lions' den, fed with Abacue's food, 234-263; and of Apostles and Friars preaching Christianity, 264-7; p. 88-89;</ITEM>
<ITEM>6 of the <I>Day of Doom</I>, 268; and herein, p. 89-90;</ITEM>
<ITEM>7 of ANTICHRIST, 272; how he shall go into the Holy Land, 274; slay Enoch and Eli, who have come to earth from Paradise to fight him, 292-6; and shall then himself be smitten to death by the Holy Ghost in the form of a sword.</ITEM></LIST>
All in alternate fours and threes<NOTE PLACE="foot">A few fours, as 183, 202, 207, are but three measures; while a few threes, as 234 and 244, are fours.</NOTE>, the latter ryming. In the rymes the equiva|lence of final '&yogh;th' with '&yogh;t' is to be noted<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cp. <I>Havelok</I>, fiht, rith, 2716; with, knith = wiht, knight, 2720.&mdash;Skeat.</NOTE>,&mdash;l. 52, 51, 71-2; (but see 57-8, 7-8, 19-24, 33-4, &amp;c.),&mdash;and these forms and rymes: <I>prep.</I> mytte (with), wytte, 43-4; but 'myde', iryde (ridden), 249-50; er&thorn;e, fier&thorn;e (fourth), 99-100; mesure, here, 89-90; consaile (<I>obl.</I>), availe (<I>inf.</I>), 115-16; but conseil (<I>obj.</I>), israel, 141-2; sei&yogh;e (3 <I>pl. perf.</I> saw), di&yogh;e (<I>inf.</I> die), 191-2; but 'sei&yogh;', on hei&yogh; (high), 201-2; pite (put,? <I>inf., imp.</I>, or <I>subj.</I>), a 'lite' (little), 225-6; ydytte (<I>pp.</I> of dihtan, see 254) 'pytte' (pit), 241-2; vchone, fon, 262-3. The <I>ie</I> is right: folie, wrie (<I>inf.</I>), 79-80; Elye, prophecie, 152-3, &amp;c. The final <I>e</I> can hardly be allowd to &thorn;ing (<I>obl.</I>) to match springe (<I>inf.</I>), 3-4 (see 59-60); cp. telle, wel, 55-6. Mowe, abou&yogh;e, 27-8, seem to show the silence of &yogh;. There are two 'longe' s probably of the same mean|ing ryming, 91-2. The ryming of 'ysed' (<I>pp.</I>) with 'ded' (dead, <I>pp.</I>), 195-6; of 'sede' (<I>perf.</I>) with 'falshede', 266, and the six '-ede' words in 267-272 (<I>drede</I> among them); of 'seide' with 'rede', 179-180, shows that the Elizabethan and our 'sed' is not, as has been asserted, a mere late slurring of the broad 'said', tho' that form or spelling has won in the fight for the survival of the fittest.</P><P>
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="82">[<I>Laud MS.</I> 622, <I>leaf</I> 69, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SO mychel wisdom neuer y-herd was; as kyng salamon cou&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Vche word wyt &amp; wisdom was; &thorn;at com out of his mou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynde he cou&thorn;e of vche beest; &amp; of vche quik &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;e vertu of vche herbe; &thorn;at do&thorn; on er&thorn;e spr[i]nge;</L>
<L>And &thorn;orou&yogh; queintise in book ywrite; &thorn;e fende to ouer-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ise clerkes &yogh;utt to &thorn;is day; in priuete habbe&thorn; some.</L>
<L>A Book he made of wisdom; &thorn;orou&yogh; his owen &thorn;ou&yogh;th;</L>
<L N="8">Sum ich wil &thorn;erof telle; for al ne may I nou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&THORN;e book bigan in &thorn;is manere; euerich wyt &amp; wisdom,</L>
<L>Euer with oure lord it is; &amp; fro hym first it com.</L>
<L>Who schulde &thorn;e rein-dropes telle; oi&thorn;er &thorn;e grauel in &thorn;e Cee,</L>
<L N="12">Oi&thorn;er &thorn;e dayes &thorn;at euere were; bot &yogh;if it were he?</L>
<L>To douten god almi&yogh;tty; of vche wisdom it is rote.</L>
<L>On er&thorn;e &amp; at &thorn;ine endyngday; of alle bales he is bote.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou louest wisdom; look &thorn;ou ri&yogh;th loue;</L>
<L N="16">Vnbuxum ne be &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th; to &thorn;em &thorn;at ben &thorn;e aboue.</L>
<L>Helpe &thorn;e man &thorn;at nedeful is; be a&yogh;eins hym &thorn;at is vnmylde.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou merciable to widewe; &amp; to faderles childe.</L>
<L>Ne hide nou&yogh;th &thorn;i wisdom; ne wi&thorn;seie nou&yogh;th &thorn;e ri&yogh;th.</L>
<L N="20">A&yogh;ein stronge men &amp; ireful; look &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne fi&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Answere &thorn;e pouere myldelich; to longe abid &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th</L>
<L>Forto turne a&yogh;ein to god; &yogh;if &thorn;ou be in synne brou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>// Ne bileue &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th to trauaile; oi&thorn;er to de&thorn;[e] fi&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="24">For Iesu cristes swete loue; to susteyne &thorn;e ri&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e fole ne wone &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th; &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt good lerne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wisse hym &thorn;at litel good can; &thorn;e vnwise teche &yogh;erne.</L>
<L>Ne wilne nou&yogh;th Iustise to be; bot &yogh;if &thorn;ou cunne &amp; mowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e vnbuxum, chastise wi&thorn; ri&yogh;th law&yogh;e; &amp; make &thorn;e proude abou&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei&yogh; &thorn;ou haue a .M. frendes; take on &thorn;at be good &amp; priuee,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at &thorn;ou mowe &thorn;i conseil telle; lest &thorn;e o&thorn;er failen &thorn;e.</L>
<L>For summe ben at &thorn;i borde &thorn;i frende; ac at &thorn;i nede bihynde.</L>
<L>Best tresore is &thorn;ine elde frende; &thorn;at men on er&thorn;e may fynde;</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;i trewe frende emfor&thorn; &thorn;i-self; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;th telle &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Michel solas he wil &thorn;e don; &yogh;if &thorn;ou art in baret brou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&para; To Newfangel ne be &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th; lest &thorn;ou finde vntrewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ine olde frende &thorn;at &thorn;ou fonded haste; bileue &thorn;ou for no newe.</L>
<L N="37">Faire speche is [ful] good &thorn;ing; it passe&thorn; many fon,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; many a good frend; &amp; holde&thorn; hol many a bon.</L>
<L>Chese &thorn;e a witty hyne; &amp; loue hym with al &thorn;i mi&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Of his Salerie wi&thorn;holde &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt hym with ri&yogh;th.</L>
<L N="41">&THORN;erwhile &thorn;i sones &yogh;onge be&thorn;; &thorn;ou hem chastise &amp; lere;</L>
<L>Wite &thorn;i douttren with eye wel; &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue of &thorn;e fere;</L>
<L>Selde &thorn;ou make hem fair semblaunt; &thorn;er while &thorn;ai ben &thorn;e mytte;</L>
<L N="44">Whan &thorn;ai schullen ywedded be; take hem a man of wytte.</L>
<L>// Honoure fader &amp; moder; &thorn;at &thorn;e in-to &thorn;is werlde brou&yogh;th;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pyne &thorn;at &thorn;i moder had; haue it mychel in &thorn;ou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Who so honoure&thorn; fader &amp; moder; &thorn;e lenger he wor&thorn;e alyue;</L>
<L N="48">His hous &amp; al his er&thorn;lich &thorn;ing; &thorn;e better schal y&thorn;riue.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e seke gladlich &thorn;ou go; &thorn;an doostou as &thorn;e kynde.</L>
<L>In euerych dede &thorn;at &thorn;ou doost; &thorn;ine endynge haue in mynde.</L>
<L>&para; Ne chide nou&yogh;th wi&thorn; no foule speker; with riche ne plede &thorn;ou no&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="52">For oft &thorn;e ri&yogh;th, &thorn;orou&yogh; gret mede; is in-to wrong y-brou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Mid a fole, of &thorn;i &thorn;ing; ne make &thorn;ou non In mone.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a Man &thorn;at fool-hardy is; ne goo &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th alone.</L>
<L>To fool ne to non vncou&thorn; man; &thorn;i conseil [&thorn;ou] ne telle,<MILESTONE N="69b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="56">For &thorn;e fool, bot his foly; no&thorn;ing ne loue&thorn; wel.</L>
<L>Ne biholde no faire wymmen; &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne chaunge &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ne loue no womman with &thorn;ine hert; &thorn;at sche ne gile &thorn;e nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ne biholde nou&yogh;th in &thorn;e strete; aboute fram &thorn;ing to &thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;if a li&thorn;er man do&thorn; &thorn;e vnri&yogh;th; ne haue &thorn;erof no likyng.</L>
<L>Dele &thorn;i frendes &amp; pouere men; &thorn;i good by &thorn;i daye;</L>
<L>Ne bileue it nou&yogh;th to o&thorn;er men; lest &thorn;ai &thorn;e bitraye.
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Ne delite &thorn;e nou&yogh;th to gete children; many &amp; vnmylde,</L>
<L N="64">ffor &yogh;ut &thorn;e were better; to deye wi&thorn;outen childe.</L>
<L>&para; Amended is al a cuntre; wi&thorn; a Man &thorn;at is wys.</L>
<L>And for a li&thorn;er man; mychel enpaired I-wis.</L>
<L>A riche werk of dronkelew man; selde is yfounde,</L>
<L N="68">For Tauerne &amp; leccherie; many man bringe&thorn; to grounde</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er &thorn;i frende ne &thorn;i foo; ne telle &thorn;ou &thorn;i priuete;</L>
<L>For bot he be &thorn;e better frend; &yogh;if he wot any yuel by &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne most &thorn;e more hym bow&yogh;e; &yogh;if &thorn;ou misseist hym ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at yuel &thorn;at he wot by &thorn;e; he nyll it hele nou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Vndernyme &thorn;i frend; &yogh;if &thorn;ou seest hym mysdo;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he is a fool or &thorn;i foo; ne do &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th so.</L>
<L>Riche &yogh;iftes &amp; present&yogh;; maken &thorn;ise Iuges blynde,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at &thorn;ai cunnen yse &thorn;e ri&yogh;th; &thorn;e wrong sone &thorn;ai fynde.</L>
<L>// wisdom yheled, litel is wor&thorn;; oi&thorn;er treu&thorn; ihyd;</L>
<L>Bot bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai wexen swi&thorn;e; &yogh;if &thorn;ai ben y-kyd.</L>
<L>Good is, wisdom to schewe; &amp; to hely folie;</L>
<L N="80">For &thorn;e fool ne can hele no&thorn;ing; bot he it out wrie;</L>
<L>His hert is as a vessel; &thorn;at bo&thorn;ome ne ha&thorn; non;</L>
<L>Whan any &thorn;ing &thorn;erinne come&thorn;; it go&thorn; out onon.</L>
<L>A fool, men mowen wel yknowe; for oft he go&thorn; aboute</L>
<L N="84">With erandes to many hous; &amp; oft he stant withoute,</L>
<L>And go&thorn; to a windowe stillelich; &amp; soft loke&thorn; &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L>Oi&thorn;er herkne&thorn; &thorn;erat what men; seien &thorn;ere wi&thorn;inne.</L>
<L N="87">Sone &amp; lovde he wil li&yogh;e; whan he here&thorn; foly telle:</L>
<L>A wise man wolde aschamed be; &yogh;if swich a cas hym bifelle.</L>
<L>Vche word &thorn;at at his mou&thorn;e schal come, schal be by mesure;</L>
<L N="90">Hym is lo&thorn; to telle myche; ac leue myche to here.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ut &thorn;re wisdoms lerne of me; ne &thorn;enche nou&yogh;th to longe;</L>
<L N="92">Be nou&yogh;th sory for no los; ne after no&thorn;ing longe,</L>
<L>Namelich &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;th nou&yogh;th haue; ne nou&yogh;th &thorn;erfore ne care.</L>
<L>Ne al &thorn;at &thorn;ou herest, ne leue &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th; &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt wel fare.</L>
<L>An vntau&yogh;t childe his fader schent more; &thorn;an &thorn;ei hem selue don;</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e man &thorn;at teche&thorn; his children wel; sore sawe&thorn; his fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;re &thorn;inges on er&thorn;e be&thorn;; &thorn;at men mowen nou&yogh;th y-knowe:</L>
<L>Whiche hij ben, I schal &yogh;ou telle; bo&thorn;e to hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe:
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>&THORN;e fissches weie in &thorn;e Cee; &thorn;e snakes weie on er&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="100">And &thorn;e foules waie in &thorn;e sky; &thorn;e werst is &thorn;e fier&thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is, childes waie in his &yogh;ou&thorn;e; &yogh;if it ha&thorn; his wille.</L>
<L>For many a foule waie it will goo; &amp; selde sitt stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;is book made Salamon; of &thorn;ise wisdoms &amp; more:<MILESTONE N="70a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="104">To mychel he loued leccherie; for al his wise lore,</L>
<L>Seuenty wyues in spousehode; he helde al his lyf,</L>
<L>And &thorn;re hundre&thorn; in leccherie; &thorn;at non &thorn;erof was his wyf.</L>
<L>Fourty wyntren he was kyng; &amp; died in &thorn;e fourtide &yogh;ere.</L>
<L N="108">Telle men mi&yogh;tten &thorn;at he were saf; &yogh;if leccherie nere.</L>
<L>Foure hundre&thorn; &yogh;er &amp; seuentene; it was &thorn;o he died, &amp; mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e folk of Israel; out of Egipte gunnen go.</L>
<L>Affter kyng Salomons de&thorn;; Roboam his sone</L>
<L N="112">Was of &thorn;at londe kyng ymade; as it was &thorn;e wone.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk cried on hym a day; &thorn;at he a-legge scholde</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruage &thorn;at his fader hem made; &thorn;e better serue hym &thorn;ai wolde.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;erfore with alle his olde men; &thorn;e kyng went to conseile:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai radden hym mylde forto be; &thorn;e more it wolde hym availe.</L>
<L>He cleped for&thorn; his &yogh;onge folk; as he hym self was,</L>
<L>&amp; axed whe&thorn;er &thorn;e reed was good; &thorn;ai seiden &thorn;at it nas;</L>
<L N="119">Bot "be &thorn;ou sterne &amp; dredeful; &amp; &thorn;an wil &thorn;ai ben good;</L>
<L>Ne schaltou hem neuere good holde; bot with sterne mood."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng &thorn;is conseil loued wel; his bondemen he lete fecche.</L>
<L>"Wene &yogh;e for my fader was wys; &thorn;at ich wil be a wrecche.</L>
<L N="123">In &thorn;e left fynger &thorn;at ich haue; streng&thorn;e &thorn;ere is more</L>
<L>&THORN;an was in al my fader schulder; for al his wise lore</L>
<L>&yogh;if he &yogh;ou brou&yogh;th in seruage; to more I wil &yogh;ou drawe.</L>
<L>Wene &yogh;e &thorn;ei&yogh; ich be &yogh;ong; &thorn;at ich ne cou&thorn;e &yogh;ou lawe?"</L>
<L>&THORN;is folk crieden &yogh;erne &amp; wepen; sore &thorn;ai hem dradd;</L>
<L N="128">Ac for no&thorn;ing &thorn;ai mi&yogh;tten do; o&thorn;er word &thorn;ai nadd.</L>
<L>&THORN;O &thorn;ai weren from hym ywent; gret conseil &thorn;ai token.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten kyndes of israel; for kyng &thorn;ai hym forsoken,</L>
<L>And made hem a newe kyng; ne stode hem of hym non eie;</L>
<L N="132">ffor &thorn;ere ne leued wi&thorn; hym; bot &thorn;e kyndes tweie,
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e kynde of Beniamyn; &amp; &thorn;e kynde of Iudas;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e kyndes of &thorn;e o&thorn;er ten; a&yogh;eins hym fast was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng sent messagers to hem; &amp; gret doel to hym he nom;</L>
<L N="136">Wi&thorn; stones &thorn;ai slow&yogh;en his messagers; &thorn;at to hem from hym com.</L>
<L>Affter &thorn;ai maden Ieroboam kyng; wel he gan hem paie;</L>
<L>And euere &thorn;e kyngdom departed is &yogh;ut to &thorn;is daye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdom of &thorn;e tweie kyndes; Iudee ycleped is;</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;erinne oure lord was ybore; in Bethleem iwis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdom of &thorn;e ten kyndes; ycleped is israel;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere mi&yogh;th Roboam &thorn;e kyng; acursy fole conseil.</L>
<L>Ofte eye &amp; pride, harme doe&thorn;; &thorn;ere men mi&yogh;th yse;</L>
<L N="144">So riche a man in londe nis; &thorn;at mowe al-one be;</L>
<L>So riche a kyng in &thorn;e werlde nys; &thorn;at poure begger he nere,</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e richesse &thorn;at he ha&thorn;; &yogh;if vche man his fo were.</L>
<L>IT bifel in israel; by &thorn;e kyngesday, swiche a cas:</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;ere was a wise prophete; Elye ycleped he was.</L>
<L>In wildernesse he woned; &thorn;e good prophete Elye,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e kyng awaited hym to sle; for his prophecie.</L>
<L>A morewen &amp; an euen a Rauen; &thorn;ere com vche a day,</L>
<L N="152">And brou&yogh;th &thorn;e prophete mete; in wildernesse &thorn;ere he lay.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en as oure lorde hym hete; to a toun he wende,</L>
<L>And sei&yogh; a widewe gadre wood; onon to hir he kende.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he woned longe wi&thorn; hire; a day &thorn;er fel a cas</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;at &thorn;e widewe son died; he was yhote Ionas;</L>
<L>Elie arered hym fram de&thorn; to lyue; &thorn;orou&yogh; goddes sonde;</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en he was a prophete; &thorn;e wisest in &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>ffor wel longe afterward; oure lord bad Ionas gon</L>
<L N="160">To &thorn;e Cite of Niniue; &thorn;at schulde haue ben fordon</L>
<L>ffor synne &thorn;at &thorn;ai hadden ydon; Ionas was adradd,</L>
<L>Ac forto prechen &thorn;ider he &yogh;ede; as oure lord hym bad.</L>
<L>// To &thorn;e hil of Oreb; Ely redy wende</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;ere Moyses in &thorn;e brennyng &thorn;orne; oure lorde kende:</L>
<L>ffourty dayes he was &thorn;iderward; &thorn;at he ne ete ne dronk</L>
<L>As it goddes will was; he had mychel &thorn;onk.
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere oure lorde spak wi&thorn; hym; &amp; hete hym good lyf lede,</L>
<L N="168">And wende a&yogh;ein to israel; &amp; no&thorn;ing ne drede.</L>
<L>"// A Man &thorn;at hatte Elisee; by &thorn;e waie &thorn;ou schalt fynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt hym take for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e; &thorn;at he ne leue bihynde."</L>
<L N="171">Elie &thorn;e prophete went for&thorn;; til he in-to desert cam.</L>
<L>He fonde Elyse gon on &thorn;e pleyn; with hym for&thorn; he hym nam</L>
<L>To &thorn;e londe of israel<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. isrk.</NOTE>; &thorn;ai nadden of &thorn;e kyng non eye.</L>
<L>Elise fonde ano&thorn;er prophete; &amp; &thorn;ider &thorn;ai wenten beie.</L>
<L>&THORN;o lay &thorn;e kyng sore seek; &amp; &thorn;o it was hym ysed,</L>
<L N="176">Elye tolde his messagers; &thorn;at he schulde be ded.</L>
<L>He hete his men wende after hym; &thorn;at &thorn;ai sparen ne scholde;</L>
<L>He wende, &yogh;if he mi&yogh;th hym haue hadd; &thorn;at he hym hele wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wenten for&thorn; &amp; comen to Elye; "goddes man" &thorn;ai seide:</L>
<L N="180">"&THORN;e kyng hete &thorn;e come &amp; speke with hym; &yogh;if &thorn;ou cou&thorn;est hym rede."</L>
<L>Elie seide "&yogh;if ich am goddes man; I. bid god al-one,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wilde fire come fram heuen adoun; &amp; brenne &yogh;ou vchone."</L>
<L>Amyd &thorn;is word onon; fire fram heuen com,</L>
<L N="184">And brent &thorn;ise men al to dust; &thorn;ere was an hard dom.</L>
<L>Sore alonged was &thorn;e kyng; after hym ylome;</L>
<L>Tueie he sent of o&thorn;er men; &thorn;o &thorn;ai nou&yogh;[th] ne come.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seiden as &thorn;e o&thorn;er deden; &thorn;o &thorn;ai Elye seie;</L>
<L N="188">And as &thorn;e o&thorn;er &thorn;ai weren serued; ibrou&yogh;th on li&yogh;th leie.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ai ne comen nou&yogh;th a&yogh;ein; &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ou&yogh;th longe,</L>
<L>And lete sende after hym; wise men &amp; stronge.</L>
<L>// &YOGH;erne &thorn;ai crieden mercie; &thorn;o &thorn;ai Elye sei&yogh;e:</L>
<L N="192">"Haue mercy on &thorn;e kyng; or elles he schal di&yogh;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;erof seide Elye; "Siker he may be.</L>
<L>Ac, forto paye his corage; ich wil hym ones see."</L>
<L>Elye went for&thorn; to &thorn;e kyng; &amp; seide he schulde be ded;</L>
<L N="196">And sone he died &thorn;erafter-ward; as he had ysed.</L>
<L>Elie &amp; Elisee in &thorn;e londe; wide aboute went,</L>
<L>For to tellen of prophecie; as oure lorde hem sent.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ai precheden goddes lawe; from heuen &thorn;ere ali&yogh;th</L>
<L N="200">A fyry hors &amp; a cart;&mdash;bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai weren wel bri&yogh;th;&mdash;
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="88"></L>
<L N="201">Elye &thorn;erinne went; &thorn;at hors hym drou&yogh; vp on hei&yogh;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cart to heuen; &thorn;at men neuer eft hym ne sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>// Ri&yogh;th to heuen ne segge ich nou&yogh;th; &thorn;at he euer come,</L>
<L>For he schal haue fleschlich lyf; forto a&yogh;eins &thorn;e day of dome.</L>
<L N="205">We rede nou&yogh;th bot of two Men; &thorn;at hennes alyue went,</L>
<L>Enok &amp; Elye; as god hem after sent.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai wonen in paradys; &amp; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai schullen ali&yogh;th</L>
<L N="208">A&yogh;eins &thorn;e day of dome; &amp; wi&thorn; antecrist fi&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Anticrist hem schal bo&thorn;e sle; &amp; si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ai schullen wende</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blisse of heuen; &amp; wonen &thorn;ere wi&thorn;outen ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;O Ely in &thorn;is fair cart; to heuen was ylad,<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">Elye</NOTE></L>
<L N="212">Elisee his felawe; was sory, &amp; nou&yogh;th glad.</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede to don his prophecie; in &thorn;e londe of Ierico:</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he fonde a li&thorn;er welle; &thorn;at many man dude wo,</L>
<L>ffor it wolde wex &amp; sprede; wide &amp; brode ilome,</L>
<L N="216">Ne mi&yogh;th &thorn;e er&thorn;e bere no fruyt; &thorn;ere &thorn;e water come.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prophete blissed salt; &amp; in &thorn;e watere cast;</L>
<L>&THORN;e li&thorn;erhede &thorn;at &thorn;erinne was; mi&yogh;th no lengere last;</L>
<L>It bicom &thorn;e best watere; &thorn;at euer mi&yogh;th ben;</L>
<L N="220">Al &thorn;at it come&thorn;-nei&yogh;; &thorn;e bettere schal &thorn;een.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e miracle &thorn;at men &thorn;o say; &thorn;at white salt had ydo,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e preest make&thorn; haliwater; salt he do&thorn; &thorn;erto.</L>
<L><B>A</B> Womman cried on Elisee; as sche hym mette,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eliseus</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; seide, men took al hir good; for hire hosebonde dette,</L>
<L N="225">&amp; &thorn;at sche nadd nomore good; bot Oile alite.</L>
<L>Elisee bad hire take &thorn;erof; &amp; in vche vessel it pite</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche had in al hire hous; &amp; &thorn;o sche had ydo &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="228">Euerich vessel was ful; of good oyle Iwis.</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman had &thorn;er &thorn;orou&yogh;; ynou&yogh; of al good</L>
<L>fforto &yogh;elde her dettes; &amp; to hire lyues food.</L>
<L>It bifel &thorn;at men of Babiloyne; weren of li&thorn;er bileue:</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;ai honoureden a fals god; a morewe &amp; ek an eue.</L>
<L><B>A</B> Wise prophete was in &thorn;at londe; &thorn;at hi&yogh;th Danyel.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para;Danyel.</NOTE></L>
<L>He com &amp; told &thorn;e kyng 'fore; his men bileueden no&yogh;t wel.</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue me power ouer hem; &amp; ich hem wil bringe of dawe.'</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;an seide &thorn;e kyng to hym; "&thorn;at were no wise lawe."
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>&THORN;at folk &thorn;o &thorn;ai herden &thorn;is; &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ai comen to:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;iue vs" &thorn;ai seiden "Danyel; oure will with hym to do,</L>
<L>Oi&thorn;er we schullen &thorn;e sle; er we hennes gon."</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;e kyng was of hem sore adrad; &amp; graunted hem onon.</L>
<L>Onon &thorn;ai token Danyel &thorn;o; &amp; casten hym in-to a pytte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere seuen hungri lyouns weren; &thorn;ereinne all ydytte,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai hym strangli scholden; ac &thorn;ai deden hym non harme;</L>
<L>Bot whan &thorn;at he was sett adoun; &thorn;ai leneden in-to his barme.</L>
<L>A Man &thorn;ere was &thorn;at hi&yogh;th Abacuc; in-to &thorn;e felde he went,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Abacuk.</NOTE></L>
<L>Repmen forto bere mete; sone he hym &thorn;ider sent.</L>
<L N="247">&THORN;e Aungel hym bad abide; &amp; to Danyel it bere.</L>
<L>Sone he seide 'he nolde'; &amp; &yogh;af hym li&yogh;th ansuere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungel took hym by &thorn;e top; &amp; bare hym for&thorn; &thorn;er myde,&mdash;</L>
<L>Hym had ben bettere to haue ygo; &thorn;an so fer to haue iryde,&mdash;</L>
<L N="251">&amp; so hym he bare to Danyel; &amp; &thorn;o he com hym to,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af hym &thorn;e mete &thorn;at he bare; &amp; lete Abacuc go.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Danyel had seueni&yogh;th; ibe in &thorn;e dep pytt,</L>
<L N="254">&THORN;e kyng loked to his lyouns; &amp; lete hem vndytt.</L>
<L>&para; Alyue he fond Danyel; gret wonder he hadde.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret ioye he took hym vp; &amp; to his fon hym lad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e men &thorn;at brou&yogh;tten hym &thorn;ere; he lete nyme fast,</L>
<L N="258">And euerych after o&thorn;ere; amonge &thorn;e lyouns cast.</L>
<L>Sone hadden &thorn;e Lyouns; forswelewed hem vchone;</L>
<L>And so oure lorde euer among; take&thorn; wreche of his fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;apostles, forto &thorn;ai weren yslawe; precheden cristendom;</L>
<L N="262">And many man after hem; good prechour bycom.</L>
<L>And now &thorn;ise freres don also; prechen aboute ylome,</L>
<L>ffor of prechyng it wor&thorn;e nede; er &thorn;e day of dome.</L>
<L>&THORN;E first signe &thorn;er a&yogh;eins; as oure lord hym-self sede,</L>
<L N="266">Hungere schal on er&thorn;e be; treccherie &amp; falshede,</L>
<L>Batailes &amp; litel loue; sekenesse &amp; haterede;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e er&thorn;e schal quaken; &thorn;at vche man schal drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e mone schal turne to blood; &thorn;e sunne to derkhede;</L>
<L>Antecrist schal on er&thorn;e gon; &amp; prechen his li <I>er</I> hede.</L>
<L>He schal go bot in &thorn;e holy londe; &thorn;ere oure lord &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; his deciples in-to al &thorn;e werlde; his yuel wordes wil bede.
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>As &thorn;ai speken, &thorn;ai schullen do; miracles grete &amp; ryue;</L>
<L N="274">Bot we ne fynde nou&yogh;th &thorn;ai mowe; arere &thorn;e ded to lyue.</L>
<L>Bot in-to cursed gostes; fendes wille&thorn; go,</L>
<L>fforto bere hem witnesse; of al &thorn;at he sei&thorn; hem to.</L>
<L>&THORN;ise grete clerkes &amp; wise; a&yogh;ein hym schullen speke,</L>
<L N="278">fforto holden vp cristendom; &thorn;at men it nou&yogh;th ne breke.</L>
<L>Bot many of &thorn;ise foles siggen; in her hastite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at clerkes schullen fordo &thorn;is werld; bot so schal it no&yogh;t be,</L>
<L N="281">Bot &thorn;e fals clergie; &thorn;at antecrist schal of preche;</L>
<L>&amp; fele &thorn;at in godenesse schulden be; li&thorn;er he wil hem teche.</L>
<L>Ac so wys clerk ne wor&thorn; &thorn;er non; &thorn;at ne schal haue to don ynou&yogh;</L>
<L>fforto disputen a&yogh;eins hym; &thorn;ei&yogh; he haue &thorn;e wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="285">Many men schullen turne; to yuel, men may drede,</L>
<L>ffor on er&thorn;e men may se; to li&thorn;er, stedfast hede.</L>
<L>Oure lord let hym on er&thorn;e gon; for &thorn;at he wil fonde</L>
<L>Whiche men of stedfastnesse be&thorn;; &amp; cristendom vnderstonde.</L>
<L N="289">Tueie men ben in paradys; Enok &amp; Elye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ne suffreden neuer de&thorn;; as we han seid twie.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins &thorn;e day of dome; &thorn;ai schullen on er&thorn;e ali&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And her ei&thorn;er after o&thorn;er; a&yogh;eins Antecrist fi&yogh;th.</L>
<L N="293">Anticrist hem schal bo&thorn;e sle; &amp; fele Men willen &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>Turne to her bileue; &amp; make her soules forlore.</L>
<L>Atte last schal come &thorn;e holi gost; in fourme of swerd al[i]&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="296">&amp; Anticrist to de&thorn; smyte; &thorn;orou&yogh; his swete mi&yogh;t.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000093.tif" N="91">
<HEAD>St. Jeremie's 15 Tokens before Doomsday. WITH LAMENTACIO ANIMARUM, WHAT OUR LORD SHALL DO AND SAY ON THAT DOOMSDAY; AND A SONG OF JOY AND BLISS, TO PRAISE THAT SWEET DEW, CHRIST.</HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P>(See other englisht copies of these '15 Tokens' attributed to St. Jerome, in my <I>Early English Poems</I> (Philolog. Soc. 1862), p. 7-12, and p. 162-4 (from <I>Metrical Homilies</I>, ed. Small, before publication); my <I>Hymns to the Virgin and Christ</I> (E. E. T. S., 1867), p. 118-125; Dr Morris's 'Hampole's <I>Pricke of Conscience</I>' (Philolog. Soc.), p. 135, l. 4738, &amp;c, and <I>Cursor Mundi</I> (E. E. T. Soc.), p. 1282-1298, Part IV, and p. 1616-18 (from the Edinburgh MS), in the Appendix, Part V; Mr T. Wright's <I>Chester Plays</I> (copid by Geo. Bellin in 1592), vol. ii. 147-9; and in the same vol., p. 219-21 (from Harl. MS. 913, ab. 1309 A.D.), and p. 222-4 (from Harl. 2255); Mr Small's Northern '<I>Metrical Homilies</I>', p. 25-6, given also in Morris and Skeat's <I>Speci|mens of Early English</I>, 1298-1393, p. 83-5; Sir David Lyndesay's <I>Monarche</I>, book iv, l. 5462 (in Skeat's <I>Specimens</I>, 1394-1579, p. 254-6), &amp;c, &amp;c, &amp;c. Old Friesic has a version of these 15 Tokens, says Mr Skeat: see Richtofen, <I>Friesische Rechtsquellen</I>, p. 130. Mr Small says that 'no copy of the original is to be found in the Benedictine edition of Jerome's Works'; and Mr Wright states that 'others say they are first found in the <I>Prognosticon futuri seculi</I> of Julianus Pomerius, a theologian, who died in the year 690'.)</P><P>The Song that follows the <I>Signs</I> here, has pretty bits and good words in it.</P><P>
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="92">[<I>Laud MS.</I> 622, <I>leaf</I> 70, <I>back, col.</I> 2.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; ffiftene toknes. &para; Ieremie.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Ieremie telle&thorn; in his book; of xv. tokenyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wil a&yogh;eins domesdai; here on er&thorn;e bring:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first day &thorn;e Cee schal arise; &amp; as a wal stonde,</L>
<L N="4">Wel hei&yogh;er by .xl feet; &thorn;an any hil in &thorn;is londe.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er dai, it schal so lowe ali&yogh;t; &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e men schul it se;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fissches &thorn;e &thorn;rid day; abouen &thorn;e water schull be,</L>
<L>&amp; so reuly a cri &yogh;iuen; &thorn;at all men schullen haue fere;</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e fier&thorn;e day, water schal brenne; as &thorn;ei&yogh; it coles were;</L>
<L>&THORN;e v<SUP>te</SUP>. day, schal euerych tre; blede dropes of blood;</L>
<L>&THORN;e vj<SUP>te</SUP>. day, schull castels &amp; houses fall; all &thorn;at euer stood;</L>
<L>&THORN;e vij<SUP>te</SUP>. day, stones schull fi&yogh;tt; &thorn;e viij. &thorn;e er&thorn;e quake;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ix<SUP>e</SUP> day, all hilles spreden abrod; &amp; al &thorn;e werld euen make;</L>
<L N="13">&THORN;e x. day, men schul renne aboute; as &thorn;ai wode were,</L>
<L>As wilde bestes holes to seche; to hide hem inne for fere.</L>
<L>// &THORN;e xj. day, bones of ded men; arisen schull &amp; vpri&yogh;t stonde;</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e xij dai, as &thorn;ei&yogh; it steren weren; fram heuen to &thorn;e londe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e xiij. dai, vche quik &thorn;ing schal dye; &thorn;e xiiij. fire ali&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And brenne al &thorn;e middelerd; so crist it wil di&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e xv. dai, schollen .iiij. Aungels comen; a .iiij. half mydlerde,</L>
<L>&amp; blowen &thorn;orou&yogh;-out al &thorn;e werlde; &thorn;at vche man schal be aferd;</L>
<L N="21">ffor in &thorn;ilk age he schal arise; &thorn;at god was inne ded,</L>
<L>Of litel more &thorn;an .xxx<SUP>ti</SUP>. wyntren; as ich &yogh;ou habbe ised,</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Lamentacio animarum.<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>This is the Head line in the MS, tho' there is no break in the story.</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio">Wi&thorn; &thorn;ilk body &thorn;at he had here; he ne schal so litel misse</L>
<L N="24">As &thorn;e lest her of his body; I sigge &yogh;ou Iwisse.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>Oure lord schal come &amp; smyte adoun; as li&yogh;ttyng do&thorn; to ground,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;at he to heuen sti&yogh;e; with his bledyng wounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. woud&emacr;</NOTE></L>
<L>An Aungel schal &thorn;e spere &amp; &thorn;e nails; &amp; &thorn;e crovne of &thorn;orn,</L>
<L N="28">&amp; &thorn;e rood &thorn;at he died on; with hym bringe aforn.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e vale of Iosephat; his dom he wil do;</L>
<L>&THORN;e best man schal sore agrise; &thorn;at schal come &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>Leuere had his owen moder; in helle pyne to be,</L>
<L N="32">Al &thorn;e while &thorn;e dom ylast; &thorn;an her sones face to see.</L>
<L>Allas! hou schull we &thorn;an ouercome; &thorn;ilk griselich fere,</L>
<L>Whan vche seint schal aferde be; oure lord crist to see &thorn;ere?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="35">OVre lord wil schewe his bitter woundes; And Sigge, "Man! for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Look what ich haue ysuffred; what hastow suffred for me?"</L>
<L>Mest he wil vnderstonde &thorn;ere; &thorn;e vij. merciful dedes:</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at ha&thorn; hem here ydo; as he with his mou&thorn; sede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hungri forto fede; &amp; schride &thorn;e clo&thorn;les,</L>
<L N="40">Ofte goo to sek men; &amp; herberewe &thorn;e housles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede forto bury,; &thorn;e bounden to vnbynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai &thorn;at &thorn;ise on er&thorn;e loueden; &thorn;ere hij schullen it fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OVre lord wil to &thorn;e li&thorn;er sigge; as we reden in gospelle,</L>
<L N="44">"&yogh;e cursed gostes, go&thorn;; in-to &thorn;e pyne of helle!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuelen willen come &yogh;ernend; &amp; speten fire &amp; blast,</L>
<L>&amp; taken &thorn;e wrecched soulen; &amp; in-to pyne hem cast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OVre lord wil to good men sigge; "in my ri&yogh;th honde &yogh;e come,</L>
<L>And afonge&thorn; my fador riche; &thorn;at a&yogh;eins &yogh;ow is ynome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &yogh;ou was ymaked; bifore &thorn;e werldes biginnyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &yogh;e schullen be in ioye with me; wi&thorn;-outen any endyng."</L>
<L>In &thorn;is book we finde ywrite; &thorn;at &thorn;re manere folk schal saued be,</L>
<L N="52">Maidenhod &amp; spousehod; &amp; widewehode: &thorn;ise &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Ich bid hym &thorn;at vs deme schal; kyng of all kynge,</L>
<L>Among his blissed sones; oure soules to heuen brynge. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off ioye &amp; blisse is my song; care to bileue,</L>
<L N="4">&amp; to herie hym among; &thorn;at al oure sorou&yogh; schal reue.</L>
<L>Ycome he is, &thorn;at swete dew; &thorn;at swete hony drope,
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="94"></L>
<L N="8">Iesus, kynge of alle kynges; to whom is al oure hope.</L>
<L>Bicome he is oure bro&thorn;er; whare was he so longe;</L>
<L N="12">He it is, &amp; non o&thorn;er; &thorn;at bou&yogh;th vs so stronge.</L>
<L>Oure bro&thorn;er we mowe hym clepe wel; so sei&thorn; hym-self ilome,</L>
<L N="16">&amp; so ne mi&yogh;tten &thorn;ai neuer adel; &thorn;at bifore vs come.</L>
<L>He nas oure bro&thorn;er nou&yogh;th; er he oure flesch nome;</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;erwi&thorn; he ha&thorn; vs dere abou&yogh;th; to maken vs ysome.</L>
<L>ysome nere we nou&yogh;th bifore; Aungels &amp; oure kynde,</L>
<L N="24">Er swete Iesus were ybore; &thorn;at to selde is in mynde.</L>
<L>// Bot now he ha&thorn; oure flesch ynome; &amp; oure bro&thorn;er is;</L>
<L N="28">Oure kynde is wel hei&yogh;e ycome; among o&thorn;er, Iwis;</L>
<L>ffor he is oure kynde heixt; saue his godhede,</L>
<L N="32">&amp; al aboue his throne next; so hei&yogh;e is manhede.</L>
<L>Aungel ne wor&thorn; hym nou&yogh;t so nei&yogh;; for he is oure bro&thorn;er nou&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="36">&amp; &thorn;at oure kynde is ek so hei&yogh;e; he ha&thorn; vs dere abou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Aungels he ne bou&yogh;th nou&yogh;th; we ben hym wel neer;</L>
<L N="40">Whan he ha&thorn; vs so dere bou&yogh;th; wel ou&yogh;tten we to louen hym here.</L>
<L>Ne aungel nys na&thorn;emo; bot his messagere,<MILESTONE N="71a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">How mi&yogh;th it &thorn;an go; to be his bro&thorn;er here?</L>
<L>&amp; in heuen &thorn;ai schullen also; whan &thorn;at we ben &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="48">Oure hestes &amp; oure will do; as &thorn;ai oure hynen were,</L>
<L>And to oure heste seruen vs; to foot &amp; to honde,</L>
<L N="52">Oure owen mowe we holden hem; as ich vnderstonde;</L>
<L>wel mowe we &thorn;an glade be; to habbe suich an hyne.</L>
<L N="56">&amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e we mowe here isee; as we ise&thorn; atte fyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ben al&thorn;er kynde hei&yogh;est; wi&thorn;-oute god al-one,</L>
<L N="60">And in heuen also hym next; among his aungels vchone.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at now late comen; si&thorn; oure lorde ali&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="64">And oure flesch ha&thorn; here ynomen; yheried be his mi&yogh;th!</L>
<L>&THORN;ilk &thorn;at toforne vs come; whan &thorn;ai &thorn;e de&thorn; founde,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;an were &thorn;ai onon ycast; in-to helle grounde.</L>
<L>Nere he neuer so holy ne so good; &thorn;ere nas non forbore;</L>
<L N="72">And so hem longed sore; after oure lorde &thorn;erfore.
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>// &THORN;e prophetes &thorn;at weren so good; &amp; so holy alle,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at of oure lorde vnderstoden; &amp; what schulde bi-fall,</L>
<L N="78">Hij wisten &thorn;at he schulde come; ac hij nysten whanne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t long ynou&yogh;; vche ynche hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t a spanne.</L>
<L N="82">&THORN;ai gradden after hym oft; in her prophecie,</L>
<L N="84">And in &thorn;e bokes &thorn;at &thorn;ai writen; &thorn;at he schulde dye:</L>
<L>"God &yogh;eue," quo&thorn; on of hem; "&thorn;at heuen broste atwo,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at he mi&yogh;th ali&yogh;th adoun; &amp; vs sauen so."</L>
<L>Sumdel hem longed &thorn;o; whan &thorn;ai nolden abide,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at heuen cleue soft a two; to saue vche side.</L>
<L>Ac it schulde al to brest; &amp; oure lorde falle adoune,</L>
<L N="96">Mi&yogh;th &thorn;ai hym haue yhent; fast by &thorn;e crovne.</L>
<L N="98">Ac he ne hei&yogh;ed nou&yogh;th so swi&thorn;; bot com soft adoun;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wolde hym narew&yogh; hab y-hent; ac he held hem &thorn;er doun.</L>
<L N="102">Parde, &yogh;it ne com he nou&yogh;th; ne were hem neuer so wo;</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;ai hadden &thorn;e grounde of helle isou&yogh;th; er he com hem to.</L>
<L>Seint Dauid after his anoie; after hym grad &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="108">"Lord, in heuen to vs abow&yogh;e; &amp; ali&yogh;th to vs!</L>
<L>Schewe vs &thorn;ine holy face; &amp; we wor&thorn;e hool onon."</L>
<L N="112">Hym longed ek after his face; &thorn;e holy Symeon,</L>
<L>And all blis hym was bynome; &amp; oft he gradd &thorn;erfore:</L>
<L N="116">"Lorde, whan wiltou come; &amp; wilt ben ybore?</L>
<L>Wene &yogh;e ich may dure; wene &yogh;e ich may see?"</L>
<L N="120">Her mone was doel to see; &thorn;ere gamed hem no gle.</L>
<L>// Ac hym ne greued nou&yogh;th; a&yogh;eins o&thorn;er bifore,</L>
<L N="124">ffor he nas nou&yogh;th to de&thorn; ibrou&yogh;th; er god were ibore,</L>
<L>Ac liued forto he hym sei&yogh;; &amp; in his armes nome,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;o he on Candelmesday; to &thorn;e temple come.</L>
<L>Lorde, wel may vs be; bet &thorn;an hem was &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at ne mi&yogh;tten nower fle; lorde, what hem was wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere oure lorde seide; &thorn;o he was ybore,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at we mi&yogh;tten ben ful glade; ouer o&thorn;er &thorn;at weren bifore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prophetes wilned hym forto see; &amp; many kynges also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we isen &yogh;if it mi&yogh;th be; ac hij ne mi&yogh;tten it nou&yogh;th do.</L>
<L N="142">// we mowen now as it were; for nou&yogh;th, to heuen come,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;en oure lord it had ibou&yogh;th; &amp; &thorn;e fendes power bynome.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="96"></L>
<L N="146">Ac &thorn;ai &thorn;at suich grace ne hadden; &thorn;at tofore vs come,</L>
<L N="148">After oure lorde &thorn;ai gradden; in &thorn;e prophecie ylome;</L>
<L>After hym &thorn;ai gradden; wi&thorn; gret wille &amp; longe;</L>
<L N="152">No mendement &thorn;ai ne seie; bot gret pyne &amp; stronge;</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at &thorn;ai wery weren; &amp; leten be al stille,</L>
<L N="156">And he[r] gredyng forberen; &amp; turneden to goddes wille;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai ne sei&yogh;en non o&thorn;er won; &thorn;ou&yogh; hem &thorn;ou&yogh;tten longe;</L>
<L N="160">Oure lorde lete her will ago; er he wolde flesch a-fonge.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;ai weren wery ynou&yogh;; as who sei&thorn; for sore,</L>
<L N="164">Vche of hem to rest drou&yogh;; &amp; speken of hym nomore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swete barne oure kynde took; bo&thorn;e of flesche &amp; felle,</L>
<L N="168">In whiche he dyed on rood; &thorn;e fendes streng&thorn;e to felle.</L>
<L>&THORN;orou&yogh; whiche preciouse de&thorn;; god vs grant &thorn;at grace</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at we mowe after oure de&thorn;; in heuen haue a place. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
