<DIV1 TYPE="fragment">
<HEAD>SOLOMON'S CORONATION, DEEDS, AND JUDGMENT ON THE TWO MOTHERS' CLAIM TO ONE CHILD. HIS COURT AND TEMPLE.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[In order to complete the Life of Solomon, of which his <I>Book of Wisdom</I>, &amp;c., form part, I add the MS. bit that comes before the <I>Book</I>. The passage about his birth is too far back to be taken.]</P><P>[<I>Laud MS.</I> 622, <I>leaf</I> 69, <I>col</I>. 1.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;o Dauid in elde was; his eldest son was alyue.</L>
<L>Adonye ycleped he was; with Salamon he gan striue.</L>
<L>Aboute he was kyng to be; by his fader daye.</L>
<L N="4*">Gret feste he made on a day; &thorn;at folk to paye.</L>
<L>He ne bad nowgth &thorn;ider Salamon; ne his moder &thorn;e quene;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sche was with hym wro&thorn;; for wymmen be&thorn; oft kene.</L>
<L>"Sir," sche seide to Dauid; "oft &thorn;ou swore me,</L>
<L N="8*">&THORN;at my son Salamon; schulde be kyng after &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Now ha&thorn; Adonye i&thorn;ou&yogh;th to be kyng bi &thorn;i lyue;</L>
<L>&amp; after &thorn;i day to sle my son; for &thorn;ai ne ben by on wyue."
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="97"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E kyng lete somony all his men: a fest he made sone,<MILESTONE N="69:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lete coroone Salamon; &amp; sette hym in his throne.</L>
<L>By his lyue he made hym kyng; &amp; bigan to prechi fast</L>
<L>fforto sustene vp goddes law&yogh;e; &thorn;er-while his lif ylast;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bulde for&thorn; goddes hous in Ierusalems burgh&yogh;,</L>
<L N="16*">&THORN;at &thorn;e law&yogh;es better weren; ysustened &thorn;orou&yogh; &amp; &thorn;orou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Dauid was kyng fourty wyntren; in werre &amp; in strife;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e fourtide &yogh;er; in pes he ended his lyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftere his fader, Salamon; slou&yogh; his bro&thorn;er Adonye</L>
<L N="20*">In &thorn;e first &yogh;er, &amp; all &thorn;at with hym weren; to hym he made boweye,</L>
<L>&amp; he wex fai&thorn;ful man &amp; wis; &thorn;at folk better to wisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynges dou&yogh;ttere of Egipte; he wedded in gret blisse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete &thorn;inges forto don; he destred<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? desired]</NOTE> goddes grace,</L>
<L N="24*">fforto arere goddes temple; in on faire place,</L>
<L>And aboute Ierusalem; treble wal arere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at to his bihof&thorn;e &amp; vche riche kyng; &thorn;e court arered were,</L>
<L>His sacrifise he dude to god; &amp; gan to hym crie:</L>
<L>"Lorde!" he seide, "to &yogh;ong icham; to haue suich maistrie.</L>
<L N="29*">Teche me, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be; wel my folk to wisse,</L>
<L>And to knowe god &amp; yuel; &thorn;at I &thorn;erof ne mysse."</L>
<L>Oure lord hym graunted &thorn;inges &thorn;re; to haue maistri ouer his fo,</L>
<L>To habbe worldes richesse ynou&yogh;; &amp; wisdom ynou&yogh; &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="33*">IT bifel &thorn;at two wymmen; in on In, a ni&yogh;th were;</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;er had a &yogh;ong childe; bo&thorn;e of on &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>In hire slep &thorn;at o womman; her owen childe ouerlay,</L>
<L N="36*">And si&thorn;&thorn;e leide it by her felawe; &amp; hir child nom away.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e womman awook; &amp; vnder&yogh;at &thorn;is gile,</L>
<L>&YOGH;erne &thorn;ai striueden &amp; chid &middot; for &thorn;e quik child a long while.</L>
<L>&THORN;at on seide, &thorn;e quyk childe was hire; &thorn;at o&thorn;er seide it nas.</L>
<L N="40*">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ei comen bifore &thorn;e kyng; &amp; tolden al her cas.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e kyng ne mi&yogh;th vnder&yogh;ete; whe&thorn;er had &thorn;e ri&yogh;th,</L>
<L>"Take hider," he seide, "my swerd; &amp; euen, I wil it di&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Cleuen ich wil, &yogh;if ich can; &thorn;e quyk childe a two.</L>
<L>&amp; taken ei&thorn;er of &yogh;ou &thorn;e haluendel; whan &yogh;e nyllen o&thorn;er do."
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="98"></L>
<L N="45*">"&YOGH;e, sir," seide &thorn;e fals quene; "crist it &yogh;elde &thorn;e;</L>
<L>So &thorn;ou mi&yogh;th best legge strif; &thorn;an mowe we euen be."</L>
<L>"Nay, sir," seide &thorn;e ri&yogh;th moder; "mercy, &thorn;at do &thorn;ou nou&yogh;th!</L>
<L>Take hire ra&thorn;er euerich del; &thorn;at it ne be to de&thorn; ybrou&yogh;th."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, good womman," &thorn;e kyng seide; "take &thorn;at child to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou hast &thorn;e ri&yogh;th weye; &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere &thorn;e falste."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MIchel wonder hadden al &thorn;at folk &middot; &thorn;at herden of &thorn;is strif,</L>
<L N="52*">&THORN;at &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ou&yogh;th swich wisdom; in his &yogh;ong lyf.</L>
<L>Men douteden &thorn;erafter-ward hym &thorn;e more; for &thorn;ilk cas.</L>
<L>Good pais &thorn;ere was in hil londe; &thorn;er while he kyng was.</L>
<L>Vche weke he spended in his hous; xxx. quarters of whete,</L>
<L N="56*">And an hundre&thorn; fatte we&thorn;ers; &amp; xxx. Oxen grete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen venison &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;ing; &thorn;at he had by deinte:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e werlde was non so riche court; ne of so gret plente.</L>
<L>He arered treble wal; swi&thorn;e fair &amp; strong</L>
<L N="60*">Aboute &thorn;e burgh&yogh; of Ierusalem; swi&thorn;e fair &amp; long.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fier&thorn;e &yogh;er of his regne; he gan his temple arere,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e elleuen&thorn;e &yogh;er was it; er it redy were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bigan he arere his court; swi&thorn;e noble &amp; hende;</L>
<L N="64*">Xiij. &yogh;er &thorn;er-aboute he was; er it were brou&yogh;th to ende.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>For what follows, see p.</I> 82, <I>above.</I> The Book of Wisdom may be compard with the A B C, and How the Good Wife and Good Man taught their Daughter and Son, in my <I>Babees Book, Q. Elizabethes Achademy</I>, &amp;c., and with Mr Lumby's <I>Ratis Raving</I>, &amp;c, &amp;c.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
